<SUBHEAD>
Tropical Storm Closer to Taiwan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A tropical storm brushed against Taiwan on Tuesday,
dumping heavy rain on the northern part of the island barely a week after a
typhoon killed 14 people and collapsed hundreds of homes. The storm, named
Prapiroon, caused little damage because its winds were relatively weak, but
officials were on alert for mudslides and flash floods that frequently follow
heavy rainfall on this mountainous island. In Miaoli county, downpours triggered
a landslide that blocked traffic on a mountain road, state radio said.
Forecasters predicted that mountainous areas around the capital, Taipei, could
record up to 20 inches of rain by Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug Reduces Heart Failure Deaths
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, The Netherlands (AP) -- A new heart drug has proven effective in
treating people with severe heart failure, reducing deaths by 35 percent,
research shows. The drug, carvedilol, belongs to a relatively new class of
medications called beta blockers, which lighten the heart's workload. It had
already proven effective in prolonging the lives of people with mild to moderate
stages of the disease, but doctors had been reluctant to give it to severe heart
failure patients. Experts say the findings, presented Tuesday at a conference of
the European Society of Cardiology, should allay long-standing concerns that
beta blockers could make heart failure worse because they depress the heart
rate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday. The Nikkei shed 72.13 points
to 17,069.62. In New York on Tuesday, the Dow closed down 37.74 at 11,215.10.
The Nasdaq Composite Index was up 11.58 at 4,082.17.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Astros Beat Mets 11-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wade Miller, Jeff Bagwell and the Houston Astros made it a
miserable night for Al Leiter and the New York Mets. Miller pitched a
five-hitter for his first complete game in the majors, Bagwell hit his 40th
homer and drove in three runs and the Astros romped past the Mets 11-1 Tuesday.
Leiter (14-6) left after three innings because of a strained muscle in his right
buttocks. Tony Eusebio's hitting streak was the best in Astros history and tied
Arizona's Tony Womack for the longest in the NL this season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
