<HEADLINE> Missing Mexican Plane Found  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A plane from the Mexican attorney general's
office that disappeared on its way to pick up a drug suspect was
found Tuesday, crashed into a mountainside. The two pilots and a
technician on board were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found the wreckage of the King Air 300 aircraft 10
miles outside the Ensenada, Baja California, airport, the attorney
general's office said. The cause of the crash has not been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   The small plane left its base in the western border state of
Sonora early Saturday en route to Ensenada, on the Pacific coast,
to pick up the son of an alleged Mexican drug lieutenant and bring
him back to Mexico City. The son is also wanted on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly an hour and a half after takeoff, the pilot asked the
Ensenada control tower to turn the runway lights on. The tower had
no further contact with the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Aldo Ismael Higuera Avila, was detained Friday on
drug charges by Ensenada police. The attorney general's office said
Tuesday that a judge had placed him under 90-day house arrest while
authorities build a case against him.
</P>
<P>
   Higuera Avila is the son of Ismael Higuera Guerrero, allegedly a
top lieutenant for the Tijuana-based Arellano Felix gang, one of
Mexico's most violent drug organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The son is accused of working with his father for the drug gang.
Higuera Avila was carrying a pistol and a false ID at the time of
his arrest, and tried to bribe police with $1,000, the attorney
general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Higuera is being held at a maximum security prison
pending trial on charges of aiding and financing drug trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
