<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports writer Lundquist dies at 86  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT ORANGE, Fla. (AP) - Carl Lundquist, a longtime sports
writer for United Press, died Saturday night at a hospice in Port
Orange, Fla. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   He contributed a column to College and Pro Football for 20
years, and was a frequent contributor to The Sporting News before
retiring in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he wrote ''United We Stand,'' a history of United Press
and its successor, United Press International, and was inducted
into the Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Fame and Babe Ruth Baseball Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Lundquist was born on Oct. 24, 1913, in Kansas City, Mo., and in
1929 became a reporter for the Kansas City Journal-Post, covering
high school sports. He moved to the Kansas City Grover's Telegram
from 1931-37, then joined UP in its Kansas City bureau in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, he moved to New York and was a baseball and football
editor through 1956. Lundquist, who covered his first World Series
in 1942, was the main lead writer for UP at the World Series from
1947-55, competing with Jack Hand of The Associated Press and Bob
Considine of International News Service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Lundquist moved to Columbus, Ohio, to become the public
relations director of the National Association of Professional
Baseball Leagues, the governing body of the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Lundquist returned to New York in 1963, getting involved with
advertising and promotions with the Yankees and Mets. In 1967 and
'68, he handled publicity for the Generals, New York's first team
in the North American Soccer League.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985-92, he handled public relations for the New York State
Games for the Physically Challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Lundquist is survived by a daughter, Susan; son, Richard; seven
grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral will be Saturday at the Westminster by the Sea
Presbyterian Church in Daytona Beach Shores. There will be a
memorial service on Long Island on Oct. 21, according to Marty
Appel, former public relations director of the New York Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
