<HEADLINE> Angels 9, Blue Jays 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Darin Erstad went 3-for-5 to reach 200
hits faster than any player in 65 years as the Anaheim Angels
rallied from a four-run deficit to beat the Toronto Blue Jays 9-4
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels trailed 4-0 before Troy Glaus hit a three-run homer
in the fourth inning and Mo Vaughn tied it with a solo shot in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim broke it open with four runs in the sixth, capped by
Erstad's two-run single. Erstad reached 200 hits in Anaheim's 132nd
game -- the fastest since the Cardinals' Ducky Medwick did it in 131
games in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carpenter (9-11) issued a one-out walk to Glaus, who
scored on Kennedy's line-drive double past the glove of first
baseman Carlos Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   Bengie Molina greeted Paul Quantrill with an RBI single. Kevin
Stocker followed with a double and Erstad hit a two-run single off
Mark Guthrie to make it 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holtz (2-2) retired Dave Martinez with the bases loaded --
the only batter he faced -- to end the sixth for the win.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, starting for the first time since being demoted to
the bullpen on Aug. 3, allowed six runs and six hits in 5 1-3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus' 38th homer put him within one of the club record Reggie
Jackson set in 1982. Vaughn's 32nd home run left him needing one
RBI to reach the 100 mark for the sixth time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The first inning was an eventful one for the Blue Jays, in terms
of milestones. Dave Martinez had an RBI single that gave him at
least one hit in all 19 games he has played for Toronto since the
Aug. 5 trade from Texas -- and equaled the longest hitting streak of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado followed with a double for his 400th career extra-base
hit and 88th this season, breaking the club record set last year by
Shawn Green.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto increased its margin to 4-0 in the third with five
consecutive one-out hits to chase Scott Karl, who allowed four runs
and nine hits in 2 1-3 innings of his Angels debut.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Erstad is the fastest AL player to reach 200 since Al
Simmons of the Philadelphia A's did it in 125 games in 1925. ...
The Angels won for the 12th time after trailing by at least three
runs. ... The Blue Jays lead the majors with 217 homers and need
four more to tie the club record. They are 6-18 when they don't
homer. ... Martinez is the first player in Toronto history to hit
safely in his first 19 games with the club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
