<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Avoids Religion Subject  </HEADLINE>
By GINA HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Dick Cheney wasn't using his Bible Belt
tour to talk about faith, discussing instead another popular issue
in the South -- the military.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential nominee was making stops Wednesday
in North Carolina and Georgia to talk about defense spending and
his concerns that the military is overstretched.
</P>
<P>
   In Charlotte, N.C., the former defense secretary was making a
luncheon speech before discussing military problems at an
international studies center in Atlanta. His final stop on a
five-state sweep was to be Florida on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before attending a fund-raiser Tuesday night in Jackson, Cheney
said the armed forces have been given too many duties and suffered
from low retention rates, lack of housing and poor equipment
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to go thoroughly scrub those commitments and look for
ways to ease some of the burden on the troops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he would not support more base closures, a concern
in Mississippi, where pilots train in Columbus and Meridian. The
military has more than 21,500 uniformed and civilian personnel
scattered across 12 Mississippi communities. The largest private
employer is Ingalls Shipbuilding, which builds vessels for the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The base closing process has gone about as far as it can because
the Clinton administration ''lost the trust of Congress'' with the
last round of closings, Cheney said. He criticized Clinton's
decision during his 1996 re-election campaign to allow private
contractors to assume work at some bases recommended for closure by
a nonpartisan commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''They had one more round of base closings and Bill Clinton
played fast and loose with the procedure and kept open a couple of
places in California that the commission had said to close,'' he
said. ''Congress then lost all confidence that the process would be
run in a fair and impartial fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney and his wife Lynne spent Tuesday night in Jackson, where
they celebrated their 36th wedding anniversary. ''I can't think of
a better place to spend it than Mississippi,'' he told several
hundred people who greeted the couple at the local airport.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of religion, the former Wyoming congressman told
reporters before the Jackson fund-raiser that although he was
raised in a religious family ''I also as a matter of course
throughout my career have not talked a lot about my faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman said
earlier this week that America ''is the most religious country in
the world and sometimes we try to stifle that fact or hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican businessman Mike Marsh of Brandon said he appreciated
Cheney's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very apprehensive about somebody who makes a big deal out
of their religion,'' Marsh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
