<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans To Reopen Peace Quest  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a deadline closing in, President Clinton
will make a fresh attempt next week to reopen summit talks with
Israel and the Palestinians and try to mediate a settlement on
Jerusalem's future and the shape of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   The odds against him appear long. A senior U.S. official
involved in the drive told The Associated Press on Tuesday that at
this point the two sides were too far apart on the issues to call
another summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans separate meetings with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat against the backdrop of
the United Nations' Millennium Summit, which will bring scores of
government heads to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians have set a Sept. 13 deadline for
settlement of their half-century-old dispute. Arafat has said he
would declare Palestinian statehood if there is no accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's immediate aim is to set up a three-way session; his
overall goal is the wide-ranging agreement that appeared to be
taking shape last month at Camp David, in Maryland's Catoctin
Mountains, but fizzled mostly over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too early to speak of a three-way summit,'' Saeb Erekat,
the top Palestinian negotiator, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are instructions from President Arafat to us to exert
every effort for an agreement,'' he said. ''We want peace, but not
at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   At the summit, Arafat demanded Palestinian sovereignty over the
eastern part of Jerusalem, held by Israel since Jordanian troops
were expelled in the 1967 Six-Day War. He would make it the capital
of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak offered the Palestinians administrative control over some
neighborhoods inside the city and in suburbs, as well as most of
the West Bank for a state. But the talks collapsed over Jerusalem
and over Palestinian demands that Israel grant hundreds of
thousands of Palestinian refugees the right to resettle in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In a move to make headway, Clinton's Middle East envoy, Dennis
Ross, is drafting a paper to summarize points of near-agreement at
Camp David, Israeli Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said Tuesday in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on Israel radio, he described the paper as a catalogue
of U.S. impressions and summations of the Camp David discussions.
Then, the summary will be put to Israel and the Palestinians for
their comments.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Palestinians will relate properly to this catalogue,
then we are in a positive game,'' Ben-Ami said. ''If their comment
will be entirely negative, it won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 90-minute meeting Tuesday in Cairo, Clinton and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak committed themselves to finding a solution
but indicated no breakthrough was near.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said the session was
''good, positive and important.''
</P>
<P>
   Moussa said Clinton brought no new plan, ''but there are ways
and proposals and ideas'' that could help Israel and the
Palestinians move closer together in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ''But this will require a great effort,'' Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross then briefed Barak in Jerusalem on the Clinton-Mubarak
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by Barak's office afterward said the prime
minister estimated chances of reaching an agreement with the
Palestinians as ''50-50,'' an assessment he has made before.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Erekat said the gap between the two sides
remained wide.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israelis are accusing us of backsliding and not being
flexible, then they say they are proposing new ideas and that this
has brought progress,'' he said. ''But that is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
