<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Postal Service Facing a Loss  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After five years in the black, the Postal
Service may be facing a loss in the fiscal year that ends next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not optimistic. Right now, our cash flow is down,''
Postmaster General William Henderson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said the agency could be in the red as much as $300
million when the books are tallied at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came in an interview after the monthly meeting of
the postal board of governors.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said the agency has faced a series of unexpected
costs. At the same time, there has been a decline in the volume of
first-class mail.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, however, he said advertising mail has
rebounded. It had dropped last year as enthusiasm grew for online
Internet sales, Henderson said, but that market has not expanded as
fast as businesses had expected and they have returned to postal
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   He reported a 5 percent growth in advertising mail this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, we're making money,'' he explained. The outcome of
the fiscal year ''depends on how far down our revenue falls this
last quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pessimistic,'' he said. ''I'd love to be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Internet usage by consumers was hurting the Postal
Service's bottom line, Henderson said the decline was not a
''diversion'' to other types of communication. There was a
diversion last year in advertising mail, he admitted, noting that
is now coming back.
</P>
<P>
   This quarter, which ends Sept. 30, usually is a weak one for the
post office, a lull before the heavy flow of pre-Christmas catalogs
and holiday cards and letters.
</P>
<P>
   The post office expects revenue of about $65 billion for the
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   While the post office made a profit in fiscal in 1995 and every
year since, surpluses have been shrinking as costs increased.
Profits have been used on new equipment, modernization, postponing
rate increases and reducing accumulated losses. The post office
still carries a $3.5 billion accumulated deficit, built up over
many years of operating in the red.
</P>
<P>
   A 1-cent rate increase took effect in January 1999, and the
agency has applied for another penny increase -- to 34 cents for
first-class mail -- to take effect next January.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the plan had been to finish this fiscal year about
$100 million in the black, but Henderson said a series of added
costs have forced the agency to cut back spending to make ends
meet. He cited an extra $150 million for workers' compensation
costs, $350 million in increased gasoline costs, $400 million
awarded to letter carriers through arbitration and a revenue
shortfall of more than $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring Henderson said in a speech that he was seeking to
make about $4 billion in savings at the agency by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The post office is starting negotiations with several of its
major unions, including clerks, mail handlers and rural carriers,
and must factor increased labor costs into its future planning.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service last showed a loss in 1994, when it was $913
million in the red. That was its fifth straight year of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress established the Postal Service as a
semi-independent federal agency in 1971, it phased out taxpayer
subsidies and instructed managers to operate it like a business
with a goal of breaking even over time.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Postal Service: http://www.usps.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
