<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Probe Japan Milk Maker  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Police on Wednesday raided the Tokyo headquarters
of Japan's largest dairy products maker, which is under
investigation for selling bacteria-tainted milk that caused a
massive food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also searched Snow Brand Milk Products Co.'s
regional main office in Osaka on suspicion of professional
negligence. No arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
   Both raids were being conducted by Osaka investigators, police
said. Most of the 14,800 people sickened in the June food poisoning
live in Osaka, about 254 miles west of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The Snow Brand case and a chain of other recent contamination of
food with bugs, broken pieces of plastic and other objects have
triggered a national food scare and loss of public trust in Japan's
food industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Snow Brand illnesses were initially blamed on staph bacteria
in a production-line valve for lowfat milk at the Osaka plant,
which was closed down indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Later, local government and company officials said it may have
been caused by staph bacteria toxins in powdered milk produced at
another Snow Brand factory on the northern island of Hokkaido but
used at the Osaka plant to make milk products.
</P>
<P>
   The powdered milk was not sold separately on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Police suspect Snow Brand failed to take necessary sanitary
measures at its plants resulting in the food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Snow Brand's president has resigned. No company officials have
been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''We apologize for the trouble we have caused to so many
people,'' Snow Brand said in a statement, repeating earlier
apologies. ''We will cooperate in the investigation in any way we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspections conducted by Health and Welfare Ministry officials
found that that Snow Brand had also recycled milk returned from
stores, including some with expired expiration dates for freshness.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Snow Brand spokesman Joji Tsugai said the
company's own internal probe has discovered that the Hokkaido plant
workers were routinely printing false production dates in an
attempt to get rid of months-old excess inventory.
</P>
<P>
   At least 70 bags of powdered milk produced in April, which
investigators suspected of containing the toxic bacteria, were
later given July production dates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The food poisoning caused Snow Brand to recall products and many
supermarkets stopped carrying anything made by the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
