<DOCNO> APW20000830.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Island Readies For Evacuation  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GUTTENFELDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIYAKE ISLAND, Japan (AP) -- An earthquake and small eruption
rocked a volcanic island south of Tokyo early Wednesday, and naval
forces stationed a destroyer off the coast in preparation for a
quick evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The seismic rumbling followed two larger eruptions of the
2,686-foot Mount Oyama on Tuesday that blanketed the island with
ash and cinder and forced the evacuation of 235 children and school
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo city government on Wednesday announced it was
preparing to accept the island's remaining 2,000 inhabitants and
shelter them on vacant city housing and evacuation centers. Tokyo
oversees the island.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are almost ready to evacuate all of them in a very short
time, if and when a large scale eruption occurs,'' said Koichi
Harukawa, a city official handling the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   A destroyer and two minesweepers requested by Tokyo reached the
island Wednesday. The destroyer can carry 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rumblings were the latest since the volcano came
back to life early last month after a 17-year silence and forced
the evacuation of about half the island's 4,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Oyama spewed a 1.6-mile-high column of smoke and ash at 4:24
a.m. Wednesday. That was followed by a magnitude-4.8 quake at 10:37
a.m. centered near the island at a depth of six miles.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of damage or injuries, and the
Meteorological Agency said there was no danger of tsunami tidal
waves from the quake.
</P>
<P>
   On the island, residents -- wearing towels over their faces --
were busy sweeping up the 6 inches of ash from their cars and
yards, many climbing onto their roofs to shovel off the debris and
carting it away in wheelbarrows.
</P>
<P>
   Sulfur dioxide from recent eruptions has been blown toward
Tokyo, where levels of the noxious gas have risen to about 10 times
normal, but not yet serious enough to warrant a health warning.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have said that shifts in huge underground pools of magma
are responsible for the recent volcanic and seismic activity on
Miyake, about 118 miles south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-square-mile island, part of the Izu chain, has now
erupted eight times since July 8. It and neighboring islands have
also been shaken by thousands of earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Oyama's last big eruption was in 1983. Five hundred homes
were destroyed when lava flowed over its western flank, though
timely evacuations prevented any casualties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 0251 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
