<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 14; Nasdaq Gains 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed on Wednesday, as brokerage
shares surged on the latest merger news while the broader markets
drifted in lackluster trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 14.06 to 11,201.45.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was up 3.17 to 4,085.34.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 1.15 at 1,508.69.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerages and financial services sector gained after Swiss
financial services giant Credit Suisse Group said it was buying
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette for $11.5 billion. DLJ was up $4 to
$88 on the New York Stock Exchange. A number of brokerages are
moving ahead on anticipation of further consolidation in the
industry, including Lehman Brothers, up $2.25 to $144.25 and JP
Morgan, up $5.13 at $154.13.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, off $1.88 at $130.75, leading some computer shares lower in
some profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the Nasdaq, Amazon rose $3.81 to $43.43 following some
bullish comments from a Goldman Sachs analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 109.12 million
shares, up from Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.59 at 530.22.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.40 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.14 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.17 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.19 percent.
</P>
