<HEADLINE> Indonesia May Aid in Clinton Probe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's attorney general has asked
police here to help U.S. investigators probe a local businessman's
contributions to President Clinton's 1992 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman, James Riady, is one of the central figures in
the campaign fund-raising scandals of 1992 and 1996. Clinton has
said he does not remember a 1992 limousine ride in which Riady
purportedly pledged to funnel $1 million in donations to his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have asked the police to investigate,'' Attorney General
Marzuki Darusman said in reply to a question about the possible
involvement of Riady, the billionaire owner of Lippo Group, in
Clinton campaign fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Darusman said that during a March visit, a senior U.S. Justice
Department official requested Indonesia's assistance in
establishing whether Riady had worked to illegally funnel
contributions to Clinton's White House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have written to police, suggesting to them to cooperate
with FBI in its investigation of the case,'' Darusman said.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI summary released last year said Democratic fund-raiser
John Huang, a Riady employee, alleged that Riady had told the
then-Arkansas governor during a limousine ride that he wanted to
raise $1 million for his campaign. In the following weeks, Riady
employees donated hundreds of thousands of dollars to the
Democratic Party, the summary said.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Clinton told federal investigators that he did not
have ''a specific recollection of what the conversation was, or
this fact of the car ride.'' He said he only remembered seeing
Riady ''sometime in '92 after I became the nominee,'' and that
Riady pledged to help his campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
