<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanic, Asian Population Booming  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DORAVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- Jose Quintana is among an increasing
number of Hispanics drawn to this Atlanta suburb, welcomed by a
tight community of helpful immigrants who came before.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, 17 people can come here together, live together,
look out for each other. We help each other,'' said Quintana, a
Salvadoran who moved to Georgia six months ago from Rochester,
N.Y., to live with his sister. ''No English? They'll help you. It's
a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau estimates released Wednesday show that increases
in the nation's two fastest-growing minority populations --
Hispanics and Asians -- are beginning to spur growth in
nontraditional immigrant destinations such as northern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   And in California, the state's minority population became a
majority during the 1990s, marking the first time since 1860 that
whites did not constitute a majority. Non-Hispanic whites were 57
percent of California's population a decade ago, according to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Between July 1, 1990, and July 1, 1999, the nation's Asian and
Pacific Islander population grew 43 percent to 10.8 million, and
the Hispanic population grew 38.8 percent to 31.3 million, the
Census estimates show. These are the last such estimates to be
released before detailed Census 2000 results come out next year.
</P>
<P>
   While California, Texas and New York -- the three most populous
states -- still have the highest numbers of minorities, Nevada,
Georgia and North Carolina experienced the biggest percent
increases, Census analyst Larry Sink said.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Georgia, a construction boom along with abundant
jobs at poultry processing and carpet-making plants have caused
Hispanic immigration to surge.
</P>
<P>
   Doraville sits on the edge of Gwinnett County, which saw its
Hispanic population surge 215.6 percent in the 90s to 26,731.
Another metro Atlanta county, Cobb, had a 158.9 percent jump to
24,350. Similar increases were seen among Asians, up 180.7 percent
to 28,793 in Gwinnett and up 135.7 percent to 18,758 in Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the white population increased 7.3 percent between
1990 and 1999 to 224.6 million. Blacks remained the largest
minority group, experiencing a 13.8 percent spike during the same
period to 34.8 million, while the American Indian and Alaska Native
population increased 15.5 percent to 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada's 50 percent population growth led all states during the
'90s. Its Asian population rose 123.7 percent to 88,208, the
largest such increase in the nation, while its Hispanic population
rose 144.6 percent to 304,364. Hispanics can be of any race.
</P>
<P>
   California had the biggest Hispanic population, with 10.4
million. Arkansas, meanwhile, had the largest percentage growth
among Hispanics, increasing 170.3 percent to 53,729 in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   New jobs in construction, food processing and textile industries
make Georgia attractive to immigrants, said Robert Giacomini,
director of research for the state's data center.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Tuesday, many Atlanta-area immigrants said an
abundance of jobs with decent wages had lured them to one of the
country's fastest-growing cities. Some, including Fernando Lopez,
said they moved from Texas after hearing friends say that
construction work paid better in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the money,'' said Lopez, rubbing his fingers together to
signify cash, who moved to suburban Atlanta last year from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The population changes can be seen in small ways: It's possible,
for example, to buy a daily Chinese newspaper at the Buford Highway
Farmers Market, a Korean-owned grocery with a majority Hispanic
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Yan, a manager of the Farmers Market, said Koreans flock
to Gwinnett County for the same reason so many others have moved to
Atlanta in recent years -- ''a lot of trees, fresh air and the
schools are OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Graciela Lopez Blancarte moved to Norcross, a neighboring
Gwinnett County suburb, from Mexico two years ago looking for work.
She doesn't speak English, but cleans houses and has found no
shortage of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good place to live,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau: http://www.census.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peet Plays Man-Slayer in Sex Comedy  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Beware Amanda Peet's beguiling smile, or
rather, what lurks beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   The actress has a flair for capturing seemingly picture-perfect
women whose dazzling looks and personalities cloak one serious mean
streak.
</P>
<P>
   There was Peet's sunny, ditsy dental assistant in the Bruce
Willis flick ''The Whole Nine Yards,'' a woman who's really an
aspiring hired killer.
</P>
<P>
   In ''Saving Silverman,'' due out next year, Peet plays the vile
fiancee of Jason Biggs, whose buddies kidnap her and tell him she's
dead to prevent the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the romantic black comedy ''Whipped,'' opening
Friday. Peet stars as the deceptively sweet Mia, who gets her kicks
by viciously turning the tables on three best friends who spend
their time scamming women into sex and then boasting of their
exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I loved that, that eventually these womanizing pigs got what
was coming to them,'' Peet said.
</P>
<P>
   Tough talk. But it is a fictional comeuppance Peet refers to.
Good thing for Brian Van Holt, who plays one of those womanizing
pigs. Van Holt is Peet's real-life boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Peet does talk tough and bluntly, whether about men and women,
sexual squeamishness by the movie industry's film raters, or the
frustrations early in her career, when she acted in a string of
independent features that never made it to theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those movies are nowhere. You can't find them,'' Peet said in
an interview while sitting on an inflatable sofa at a funky West
Hollywood hotel. ''I really thought I was cursed.''
</P>
<P>
   Peet's sense of bad self-karma became so acute, she warned
''Whipped'' writer-director Peter Cohen about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was like, 'Peter, you should not put me in this movie
because it's never going to go anywhere if you do,''' Peet said.
''He always laughed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, though, Peet might have felt her indie curse was
continuing. Independently financed, ''Whipped'' was shot over a few
weeks in early 1998. Then Cohen was unable to land the sharp satire
at a major film festival, where he had hoped it would catch
distributors' attention.
</P>
<P>
   He used his own money to pay for a finished print to show
distributors, and Destination Films finally acquired the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen laments that had it sold earlier, ''Whipped'' could have
been at the vanguard of a new wave of hip sex comedies, including
''There's Something About Mary,'' ''American Pie'' and the HBO
series ''Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   But the delay could prove beneficial. Peet's profile has risen
dramatically in the last year or so through roles in ''The Whole
Nine Yards'' and ''Simply Irresistible,'' plus her WB network
series ''Jack &AMP; Jill.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Whipped'' now has the appearance of a well-timed coming-out
party for a supporting player stepping into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''You try not to think of things that way,'' Peet said when
asked if ''Whipped'' could be her breakout role. ''You just kind of
do your press interviews and pray for good grosses for the sake of
everybody. I'm proud of this movie, though. I'm proud of it for
personal reasons. It was such a small movie, it's like a Cinderella
story.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker Peet, 28, had a Cinderella-like start after deciding
to pursue an acting career in college at Columbia University. She
landed parts early on in Edward Burns' ''She's the One'' and the
Michelle Pfeiffer-George Clooney romance ''One Fine Day.'' Then
came those movies that went nowhere, such films as ''Origin of the
Species,'' ''1999'' and ''Touch Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I wasn't ready, but I just wanted to work. I had the
philosophy that work begets work,'' Peet said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only way you get better is by working. You cannot do it in
a class, and you cannot do it in the mirror at home, and you cannot
do it by fantasizing. You can watch all the Meryl Streep movies in
the world and all the Katharine Hepburn movies in the world, but
you can't learn to do it until you're up there doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply by making it to theaters, ''Whipped'' has broken Peet's
unlucky streak. Her ''Whipped'' colleagues credit that largely to
Peet's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really proud of her because she cares so much,'' said Van
Holt, who plays a Wall Street sleaze in ''Whipped'' and began
dating Peet six months after the movie was shot. ''She's very
disciplined and works very hard. Of course, she has that natural
talent and beauty, which helps.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend had recommended Peet to Cohen, who was looking for an
actress who could make Mia strong and pitiless yet endearing at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I needed the audience to fall in love with her as well as our
characters,'' Cohen said. ''And I needed someone who was more
unique than the typical Hollywood blond bombshell. It was a strong
female lead and portrayed women where they really kind of win, in
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Peet was instrumental in crafting the movie's ending,
in which Mia and her friends talk brazenly about men, echoing the
male characters' bull sessions earlier. Peet and a friend rewrote
the dialogue to better reflect a female perspective about scamming
men, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue hit too hard with movie raters for the Motion
Picture Association of America, which initially gave ''Whipped'' an
NC-17 rating, which would have barred anyone younger than 17. Cohen
said he repeatedly toned down the dialogue, mostly among the women,
finally gaining an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just were not pleased seeing women talking the way we
did,'' Peet said. ''I think it's totally sexist in that they don't
want to see women talking about sex in a glib way, because women
aren't supposed to be aggressors or really sexualized people.
</P>
<P>
   ''Interestingly, what they were responding to was dialogue.
Everything they responded to was verbal. It's OK for somebody to
shoot somebody. It's OK to show rape and non-loving sex. But it's
not OK to have a satire where a movie makes fun of men trying to be
cruel and fearless and unfazed by sex.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tarsha Vega Aims for Stardom  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Politely but firmly, Tarsha Vega corrects anyone
who wonders how her life will change if she becomes a big music
star.
</P>
<P>
   ''When,'' she says, interrupting a question. ''I deal not in
ifs.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse us. Maybe that attitude is the necessary brash exterior
for someone bred in the Bronx, or simply the self-confidence of a
singer who watched record companies scramble after her in a bidding
war before her first disc was made.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Vega doesn't bother to doubt where she's headed.
Judging by her debut, due out in October, she has the goods to back
it up. Her infectious modern pop is calculated for mass appeal, and
RCA, the record company that launched Christina Aguilera's career,
is giving her a big push.
</P>
<P>
   ''It all happened very fast,'' said Vega, who declines to give
her age. ''It wasn't something I had to struggle for, or knock down
doors. I purposely put it in my brain to be instant, and it
happened that way. If I think about something and I believe in it,
it happens instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   The song, ''Be Ya Self,'' is on the radio now and illustrates
the strategy for world domination. A rapping message of
self-determination to girls, it's built around the hook and key
lyric of Rick Nelson's ''Garden Party'': ''If you can't please
everyone, you've got to please yourself.'' Vega's version urges
listeners to ''be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The song is designed so no one -- mom, dad or daughter -- will be
tempted to change the station when it comes on the car radio.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was important to me,'' she said. ''Why not get parents
and kids to relate to the song? Why not get the black kids and the
white kids to relate to it?''
</P>
<P>
   One claim about her upbringing in the Bronx already sounds like
future legend: When Vega and her mother moved out of her
grandmother's home for a place of their own, they had enough money
for a bed or a stereo system, not both. She said she chose the
music and slept on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother tried to make Vega culturally rounded, taking her to
museums as she grew up. She took drama and dance courses in school,
and was drawn to Manhattan for a variety of experiences: singing
and acting in commercials, working at ''CBS Evening News'' and
modeling.
</P>
<P>
   With some friends who appeared in the off-Broadway musical
''Stomp,'' Vega went out one night and met the duo of Dave Schommer
and Sam Hollander. Known as Pop Rox, they are music producers who
worked on such cuts as Sisqo's ''Thong Song'' and DMX's ''Party Up
in Here.''
</P>
<P>
   She visited them in the studio, and they did a double take when
they heard her voice.
</P>
<P>
   They worked together on a demo tape that quickly caught the
interest of record companies eager to sign anyone who could appeal
to the powerful new youth demographic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I describe my music as intelligent pop, hip-hop and soul,''
she said. ''I made it to be really consciously world music, as
opposed to one specific genre. I'm always thinking on a real
positive level, but not fluffy. I didn't want it to be all pink and
yellow.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being smart and sassy, her album is a name-checker's
delight. Vega references some expected figures, like Bob Marley,
Sisqo and Big Pun. But others she mentions may send her audience to
books, or at least to their parents: Shirley Chisholm, Frank Zappa,
Ben Folds, Katharine Hepburn and David E. Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   She even salutes Seymour Stein, a record company executive who
courted her but lost out to RCA.
</P>
<P>
   ''He discovered Madonna,'' she said. ''He was so cool in his
vibe and was great. He was one of the first people to give me love.
Just because we didn't go with him doesn't mean I don't respect
him.''
</P>
<P>
   At her song publisher's suggestion, she met with RCA last
Thanksgiving. Vega's tape immediately struck RCA executives as
''very current and fresh and very catchy,'' said Jack Rovner, the
company's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she's got the ingredients to have that success,'' he
said. ''She has a very positive approach. She's very endearing --
anybody she has touched so far comes back with a strong feeling
about her.''
</P>
<P>
   One of RCA's first steps was to try to place one of Vega's songs
in a big-budget movie this summer. The good news is they succeeded.
The bad news is the movie was ''The Adventures of Rocky and
Bullwinkle,'' one of the year's biggest flops.
</P>
<P>
   Vega duets on her album with Carole King, a legendary music
figure whose music Vega was familiar with through years of
listening to soft rock radio stations. It was a suggestion that,
oddly, came when one of the producers' wives had a dream about Vega
singing with King.
</P>
<P>
   King was contacted and -- Vega imitates her raspy voice -- said,
''Let me hear the child's music.'' She was impressed enough to fly
east to sing on ''Rooftops,'' and gave Vega an autographed picture
with the inscription, ''U-D-B.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That stands for 'u da bomb,''' Vega translates.
</P>
<P>
   Her song ''Time'' is dedicated to the class of 2001. It is a
blistering indictment of schools with teachers who ''leave ya up
the creek like Dawson.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I love education and think education is extremely important,''
she said. ''But as far as the public school system is concerned, it
needs a lot of work. If anybody can take their kid out of public
schools, do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in school, Vega obviously had her mind on other things. She
is so sure of her destiny that she kept her circle of friends small
and has always avoided having her picture taken with big groups so
there are fewer folks who will one day have evidence that they
''knew her then.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew all my life that I would be an entertainer,'' she said.
''I just didn't know where. So I've always been preparing for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
