<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Works Literary Magic  </HEADLINE>
By PETER MUELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's best-known wizard sits at
his computer, idly pulling on a cigarette and checking his e-mail.
He doesn't part the clouds these days or slip unperceived through a
crowd, though he hasn't forgotten how.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always was and always will be a wizard,'' Paulo Coelho says.
''But those tricks are pretty useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Coelho weaves a more practical sort of magic by
enchanting readers with tales of his quest for spiritual
enlightenment and turning homespun parables into worldwide best
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   With some 28 million books sold in 45 languages and more than
120 countries, Coelho is by far Brazil's most widely read author.
Awards have poured in -- France recently made him a Knight of the
Legion of Honor -- and his fans include Julia Roberts, Madonna and
even President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said Chelsea gave him a book of mine to read, and he loved
it,'' Coelho says with a laugh. ''I asked if I could quote him on
that, and he said, 'Sure.'''
</P>
<P>
   His appeal seems boundless. On a recent visit to Iran, 1,500
fans were on hand to meet his plane -- at 2 a.m. A book signing drew
5,000 people, then was canceled when security agents said they
couldn't control the raucous crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was extraordinary, beyond all my expectations,'' Coelho
says, shaking his head. ''You know where I sell the most books?
Iran and Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   He stares bemusedly out the picture window of the airy,
high-ceilinged apartment on Avenida Atlantica, as if beguiled by
his own success. The long curve of Copacabana Beach stretches away
toward Sugarloaf in the golden afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what the secret is,'' he says finally. ''Maybe
there's no secret. Or maybe it's that I just offer the question,
not the answer, like a direction to find your own way home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before my first book, I thought the spiritual search was
complicated. I thought it was for an elite. But it's just a
question of looking around and perceiving.''
</P>
<P>
   In faded jeans, gray hair retreating into a tiny pony tail and a
butterfly tattoo on his arm, the 53-year-old Coelho looks like an
aging hippie -- which he is. His first fling with fame came in the
1970s, as a lyricist for legendary Brazilian rocker Raul Seixas.
</P>
<P>
   With Seixas, he also had a brush with black magic -- a little too
close. In his book ''The Valkyries,'' Coelho describes his terror
at the mad, bodiless laughter that pursued him and the swirling
black whirlpools that appeared to him in the kitchen floor. He
renounced black magic, lost his job and friends -- and changed his
life.
</P>
<P>
   It was during a visit to the Dachau concentration camp in
Munich, Germany, that he says a spirit appeared and encouraged him
to become a wizard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Coelho made the ancient, mystical pilgrimage along the
500-mile Road of Santiago across the north of Spain. Walking six
hours a day for 70 days along the ''sacred path'' from the Pyrenees
Mountains to the city of Santiago de Compostela, he discovered an
honorary society of wizards, founded in the tiny northern Spain
village in 1492 by a group of magicians. Coelho drew on his travels
to write ''The Pilgrimage'' and ''The Alchemist.''
</P>
<P>
   Success was almost immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Alchemist,'' the tale of a shepherd boy's quest for
spiritual fulfillment -- his ''personal legend,'' as Coelho says --
became a No. 1 best seller in 29 countries. His Web page claims it
is recommended reading at schools in France, Italy, Spain,
Portugal, Taiwan, Brazil and the United States, including the
University of Chicago's graduate school of business.
</P>
<P>
   His newest book is ''Veronika Decides to Die,'' published by
HarperCollins. It is a tale of spiritual growth in a mental
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho again draws on his own experience as a teen-ager, when
his parents -- worried about his rebelliousness and his involvement
with leftist opposition to Brazil's military regime -- placed him in
an institution.
</P>
<P>
   Veronika leads a comfortable life in Slovenia but wearies of the
routine and tries to kill herself with pills. She awakes in a
mental hospital, where she is told she has a week to live. The
hospital and the imminence of death free Veronika from conventions,
and she discovers hate, love, sex and life with fellow inmate
Eduardo -- Coelho's thinly disguised persona.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your destiny is your personal legend -- it is written. But
often we must live the destiny that others impose, like fathers on
their sons,'' Coelho says.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was in the hospital, I asked why God wanted me to go
through all these things. When I learned other people had panic
attacks, it helped me to heal. When you know you're not alone, it
creates a complicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, he sees a positive side to his ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was the first time that I had to confront the
realities of life. There are certain experiences that will either
kill you or make you stronger. That was an experience that made me
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   While readers love the simple tales and upbeat messages, critics
often are less than kind.
</P>
<P>
   ''Critics don't ignore me -- either they are very positive or
very violent,'' Coelho says. ''If the critics weren't so rough I
wouldn't sell so many books. It makes me take a position, and the
reader, too. It means I'm touching a nerve. I'm the vanguard.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho's literary idols are Argentina's Jorge Luis Borges and
Henry Miller, especially for his ''Tropic of Cancer.'' He calls
James Joyce's ''Ulysses'' the ''great lie of the century,''
inspiring generations of imitators to write obscure and difficult
books nobody reads.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays Coelho turns out a book about every two years. He works
intensely, writing 15 hours a day and having a first draft ready in
two to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always write at night when I'm very tired,'' he says. ''Then
there are no blocks, no self-censorship. It's more natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Brazilians, his spirituality is nonexclusive. On his
wrist is a red ribbon, typical of Brazil's African-based spirit
religions, but he remains a devout Catholic and attends mass.
There's a painting of Jesus over the bed and statues of Catholic
saints on the night table, and the Bible next to the computer is
open to the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   Fame has brought a constant demand for lectures and public
appearances, but Coelho finds time to take part in UNESCO's
interreligious committee. Royalties from his books fund the Paulo
Coelho Institute, a nonprofit group that supports underprivileged
elderly Brazilians and helps sponsor the Children of Light Day Care
Center in Rio's Pavao-Pavaozinho shantytown.
</P>
<P>
   On a rare day such as this, he can relax at the apartment he
shares with his wife, artist Cristina Oiticica, or stroll along the
beach, graciously accepting a stream of compliments,
congratulations and occasional requests for money.
</P>
<P>
   He is wary of the pitfalls of success.
</P>
<P>
   ''Defeat and victory can paralyze you,'' Coelho says. He plans
to keep moving forward -- and admits it's been a good life so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''I married the woman I love, wrote the books I wanted, lived
intensely, asked forgiveness of the people I had to -- I did
everything,'' he says. ''I lived a life few people ever do.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   www.paulocoelho.com.br
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1203 </TRAILER>
