<DOCNO> APW20000830.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fall Brings Crop of Beatle Books  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Thirty years after their breakup, and 20 years
after the death of John Lennon, it's time yet again to meet the
Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   In bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine Beatle-related titles are expected this fall, from
the authorized ''The Beatles Anthology'' to a biography of their
late manager, Brian Epstein. Other books include an illustrated
volume of Paul McCartney's paintings, a reissue of Lennon's
collection of verse, ''In His Own Write,'' and a look at the
Beatles' time in India with the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi.
</P>
<P>
   While a generation has been born and raised since the Beatles
were together, they remain a major moneymaker and cultural
presence. The band's albums sold more than 50 million copies
worldwide over the past decade. Dozens of Beatles fans clubs still
exist, from Australia to Russia to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Beatle books have been coming out since the group first started,
but readers apparently still want more. ''The Beatles Anthology,''
an oral history assembled by the three surviving Beatles and
Lennon's widow, Yoko Ono, has advance orders of more than 1 million
and will be published in at least eight languages.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember being at the booksellers convention a couple of
years ago and Linda McCartney was there to promote one of her
vegetarian cookbooks,'' says Constance Sayre, director of Marketing
Partners International, a publishing consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ''The publisher gave a party and you should have seen the lineup
of people to shake Sir Paul's hand. You've never seen such a crowd.
The Beatles are certainly a big deal with booksellers.''
</P>
<P>
   A minor surprise is the reissue of ''Lennon Remembers,''
Lennon's famously bitter, marathon interview with Rolling Stone
publisher Jann Wenner, given just as the group was breaking up.
Lennon had agreed to the interview on the condition that Wenner not
put it out in book form. When he did so anyway, Lennon was enraged
and spoke bitterly about Wenner right until the end of his life.
</P>
<P>
   But the new publication arrives with the approval of Yoko Ono,
who contributed a forward. Material originally edited out has been
restored and some lyrics never recorded will be included.
</P>
<P>
   '''Lennon Remembers' is classic Lennon,'' Ono writes. ''It's not
a sit-back-and-put-your-feet-up read. ... It's a jolt on your
nerves like bad, bad espresso. People with weak stomachs should
close the window before reading. You might just feel like jumping
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Beatles, this fall marks another ongoing publishing
obsession, the Clintons. The titles can almost be divided into
subgenres: attack books, memoirs and policy papers.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the attack genre are ''I Feel Your Pain: The Explosion
and Abuse of Power During the Clinton-Gore Years'' and ''Sell Out:
The Inside Story of Bill Clinton's Impeachment.'' Memoirs include
''Eyewitness to Power,'' by former adviser David Gergen, and
''POTUS Speaks,'' by speechwriter Michael Waldman. (POTUS is
Washingtonian for President of the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Among those sticking to policy are former labor secretary Robert
B. Reich, who critiques e-commerce in ''The Future of Success,''
and former national security adviser Anthony Lake, who reviews
foreign policy in ''Six Nightmares.'' Bob Woodward reviews the
economy in ''Maestro: Inside Greenspan's Fed and the American
Boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Clinton aide Paul Begala looks to this year's
presidential campaign with ''Is Our Children Learning?'' an actual
quote from Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Al Gore, meanwhile, gets
the treatment in ''Al Gore: A User's Manual,'' by Alexander
Cockburn and Jeffrey St. Clair. The true specialist might look for
reissues of books by vice presidential candidates Joseph Lieberman
(''In Praise of Public Life'') and Dick Cheney (''Kings of the
Hill: Power and Personality in the House of Representatives'').
</P>
<P>
   Also this fall, Tom Wolfe comments on contemporary culture in
''Hooking Up,'' Matt Drudge sums up his life -- so far -- in ''Drudge
Manifesto'' and Ted Koppel looks back at recent news events in
''Off Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the market remains tiny, some titles will be available
only as e-books. They include ''Blair Witch: Graveyard Shift,''
which anticipates November's sequel to ''The Blair Witch Project,''
and the science fiction series ''Star Trek S.C.E.'' Stephen King
fans can expect more installments of his online novel, ''The
Plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on paper, King remembers his near fatal car accident in
''On Writing'' and Mary Karr, author of the best-selling ''The
Liar's Club,'' writes about her teen-age years in ''Cherry.'' J.D.
Salinger's daughter, Margaret, reflects on her family in ''Dream
Catcher.'' The McCourt franchise continues with ''Singing Him My
Song,'' Malachy's McCourt sequel to ''A Monk Swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   Memoirs also are due from historian Arthur Schlesinger, Jr., the
late football star Walter Payton, Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli,
Natalie Cole, Jerry Butler, the Neville Brothers, Jerry Stiller,
Tina Sinatra and the pro wrestler Chyna.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bellow'' is James Atlas' highly anticipated biography of Nobel
laureate Saul Bellow. Ian Kershaw, author of an acclaimed history
about Hitler's rise to power, is coming out with the second volume.
David Levering Lewis completes his two-volume series on civil
rights pioneer W.E.B. DuBois. Other biography subjects this fall
include President Franklin D. Roosevelt, Robert Kennedy, George
Orwell and Robert E. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The fiction list seems especially strong, with books expected
from Margaret Atwood, Ha Jin, Carlos Fuentes, William Trevor,
Michael Chabon, John Updike, Kazuo Ishiguro, Jane Hamilton, Caleb
Carr, Alice Walker and Nobelists Gunter Grass and Jose Saramago.
Notable new authors include Bonnie Burnard, Nomi Eve, Allen B.
Ballard and F.X. Toole.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams fans should look for a collection of his
letters and a volume of his early plays. Also expected are the
letters of Dashiell Hammett, essays by Arthur Miller, stories from
Isaac Bashevis Singer and the original, unedited version of Thomas
Wolfe's novel, ''Look Homeward, Angel,'' published upon the
centennial of the author's birth.
</P>
<P>
   Among commercial titles, the biggest seller could well be ''The
Mark: The Beast Rules the World,'' the latest apocalyptic thriller
from Jerry B. Jenkins and Tim F. LaHaye. Other names to look for
include Anne Rice, Tami Hoag, Elmore Leonard, Johanna Lindsey,
Richard Paul Evans, Colleen McCullough, Patricia Cornwall and
Philip Margolin.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the season's more unusual titles could be labeled
detective stories. In ''Author Unknown: On the Trail of
Anonymous,'' handwriting expert Don Foster reveals how he unmasked
''Primary Colors'' novelist Joe Klein. ''The Island of Lost Maps''
follows the cartographic trail of Gilbert Bland, Jr., an antiques
dealer with an unfortunate passion for stealing vintage maps from
research libraries throughout the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ''Island'' has a first printing of about 50,000 and author Miles
Harvey already suspects who some of those readers will be. He
recalls speaking to a gathering of librarians at last June's
BookExpo America. He told a true tale of horror, about Bland and
Gary Menges, a librarian at the University of Washington who had
spent five years trying to save a copy of ''America,'' an
encyclopedia and atlas of the United States from 1672.
</P>
<P>
   ''Menges raised the money by himself to preserve this book,''
Harvey says. ''He even threw in $50 of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ''For months, no one asked about the book. But one day a guy who
identified himself as 'James Perry' walked into the library. Menges
happened to be working at the research desk and when this fellow
requested 'America,' Menges got all excited. He said, 'I sure hope
you like this book.'
</P>
<P>
   ''When I got to the part of the map being dislodged from the
book, there was an audible gasp from all those librarians in the
room. It was extraordinary. I think this book will do very well
with librarians.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Notable books coming out this fall (all dates subject to
change):
</P>
<P>
FICTION
September
</P>
<P>
   ''The Amazing Adventures of Kavalier &AMP; Clay'' (Random House):
comic book heroes and the 1930s are featured in Michael Chabon's
novel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Blind Assassin'' (Doubleday): Margaret Atwood's latest,
featuring a novel within a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dust to Dust'' (Bantam): a police thriller from Tami Hoag.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Golden Age'' (Doubleday): the seventh, and final, American
historical narrative from Gore Vidal.
</P>
<P>
   ''A Friend of the Earth'' (Viking): T.C. Boyle's novel is set in
2025, when global warming has destroyed the biosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Killing Time'' (Random House): a futuristic thriller from
Caleb Carr.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pagan Babies'' (Delacorte): Elmore Leonard's latest covers
genocide in Rwanda and Mafia crime in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ''When We Were Orphans'' (Alfred A. Knopf): Kazuo Ishiguro tells
the story of an orphaned English boy.
</P>
<P>
October
</P>
<P>
   ''All the Names'' (Harcourt): the latest from Nobelist Jose
Saramago.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Bridegroom'' (Pantheon): stories from last year's National
Book Award winner for fiction, Ha Jin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Disobedience'' (Doubleday): in Jane Hamilton's new novel a
high school senior learns his mother is having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't Tell Anyone (W.W. Norton): stories by Frederick Busch
about the American family.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Last Precinct'' (Putnam): the latest mystery from Patricia
Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   ''Merrick'' (Alfred A. Knopf): more witchcraft from Anne Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Night Listener'' (HarperCollins): Armistead Maupin's
latest centers on a radio personality and a telephone caller.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Way Forward Is With a Broken Heart'' (Random House):
autobiographical stories from Alice Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Years With Laura Diaz'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux): Carlos
Fuentes' novel is set during the Mexican Revolution and its
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
November
</P>
<P>
   ''Licks of Love'' (Alfred A. Knopf): stories from John Updike,
including a short sequel to his ''Rabbit'' novels.
</P>
<P>
   ''More Stories From My Father's Court'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux): stories from the late Isaac Bashevis Singer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Too Far Afield'' (Harcourt): Nobelist Gunter Grass writes
about German reunification.
</P>
<P>
NONFICTION
September
</P>
<P>
   ''The Brothers'' (Little, Brown): the Neville Brothers tell
their own story.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Island of Lost Maps'' (Random House): Miles Harvey follows
a trail of cartographic crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''Married to Laughter'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster): Jerry Stiller's
autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never Die Easy'' (Villard): the autobiography of the late
football star Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Second Coming of Steven Jobs'' (Broadway Books): a
biography of the Apple executive by Alan Deutschman.
</P>
<P>
October
</P>
<P>
   ''Author Unknown: On the Trail of Anonymous'' (Henry Holt):
Handwriting expert Don Foster explains how he learned the identity
of ''Primary Colors'' author Joe Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Beatles Anthology'' (Chronicle Books): the Beatles' story,
in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boogie Man'' (St. Martin's): Charles Shaar Murray's biography
of John Lee Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cherry'' (Viking): a coming-of-age memoir from the author of
''The Liar's Club.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Drudge Manifesto'' (New American Library): thoughts from Matt
Drudge, who runs an internet gossip mill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ghost'' (Random House): a memoir by New York Times columnist
and former theater critic Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   ''Greek Fire'' (Alfred A. Knopf): by Nicholas Gage, the story of
Aristotle Onassis and Maria Callas.
</P>
<P>
   ''My Father's Daughter'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster): Tina Sinatra's
autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only the Strong Survive'' (Indiana University Press): the
autobiography of soul singer Jerry Butler.
</P>
<P>
   ''On Writing'' (Scribner): Stephen King reflects on writing and
his near fatal road accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scenes From My Life'' (Warner): memoirs from Andrea Bocelli.
</P>
<P>
   ''Singing My Him Song'' (HarperCollins): more stories from
Malachy McCourt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Troubled Man: The Life and Death of Marvin Gaye'' (Harper/Ecco
Press): by Steve Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ''W.E.B. DuBois: The Fight for Equality and the American
Century, 1919-1963'' (Henry Holt): by David Levering Lewis.
</P>
<P>
November
</P>
<P>
   ''Alistair Cooke: The Biography'' (Arcade): by Nick Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   ''Angel on My Shoulder'' (Warner): Natalie Cole's autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bing Crosby: A Pocketful of Dreams -- The Early Years,
1903-1940'' (Little, Brown): by Gary Giddins.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chyna'' (Reganbooks): the pro wrestler's autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ''A Life in the Twentieth Century'' (Houghton Mifflin): the
first volume of memoirs from historian Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maestro: Inside Greenspan's Fed and the American Boom'' (Simon
&AMP; Schuster): Bob Woodward examines the current economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Making of Robert E. Lee'' (Alfred A. Knopf): a biography
of the Civil War general by Michael Fellman.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Selected Letters of Dashiell Hammett'' (Counterpoint
Press).
</P>
</TEXT>
