<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fall Preview: Verdi Dominates Season  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Come Jan. 27, the music of Giuseppe Verdi will
fill the opera houses and concert halls of the world, celebrating
the 100th anniversary of his death with his ''Requiem'' and
performances of his 28 operas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most human composer after Mozart,'' Sir Georg Solti said a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The music world certainly agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Without Wagner's pomposity, and with more intensity than Mozart,
Verdi created enduring works from 1839-93. The anniversary of his
death has caused opera companies and symphonies to center not only
the 2000-01 season around him, but in many cases 2001-02, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are about human beings, these are about human emotions,
these are about people with which you can be empathetic,'' Donald
Runnicles, music director of the San Francisco Opera, said last
week. ''It's great music, great tunes. It's always music that can
be sung in a taverna or whistled in the streets. There's something
eminently approachable about the characters.
</P>
<P>
   ''That in contrast to a Richard Wagner, who created dwarfs and
giants and larger-than-life characters, mythical figures.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''Requiem,'' which Verdi wrote in 1874 and dedicated to
Italian novelist Alessandro Manzoni, will be played Jan. 27 by the
Berlin Philharmonic (chief conductor Claudio Abbado with soloists
Angela Gheorghiu, Roberto Alagna, Daniela Barcellona and Julian
Konstantinov); the Bavarian State Opera Orchestra in Munich,
Germany (Zubin Mehta conducting Andrea Bocelli, Renee Fleming, Rene
Pape and Dolora Zajick); and the Symphony Orchestra of Madrid,
Spain (Garcia Navarro conducting Silvie Valayre, Alicia Nafe, Johan
Botha and Erwin Schott).
</P>
<P>
   Later in the season, the ''Requiem'' will be played by the State
Opera, Unter der Linden in Berlin (April 13 with Daniel Barenboim
conducting Jane Eaglen, Waltraud Meier, Botha and Eldar Aliev); the
Chicago Symphony Orchestra (April 24, 26, 28 with Barenboim
conducting Deborah Voigt, Violeta Urmana, Botha and Pape); the
Metropolitan Opera Orchestra (April 29 at Carnegie Hall, with James
Levine conducting Fleming, Pape, Olga Borodina and Marcello
Giordani); the Vienna Philharmonic (May 19 at the State Opera with
conductor Riccardo Muti, Urmana, Miriam Gauci, Giuseppe Sabbatini
and Alastair Miles); and the Concertgebouw of Amsterdam at Paris'
Chatelet Theatre (May 31 with Riccardo Chailly conducting Barbara
Frittoli, Violeta Urmana, Acquiles Machado and Orlin Anastassov).
</P>
<P>
   The Concertgebouw, with Inez Salazar replacing Frittoli, repeats
the program the next day in Toulouse, France.
</P>
<P>
   The Teatro La Fenice in Venice, Italy, will perform the
''Requiem'' on Dec. 5, 7, 9, 12 and 14; the Opera de Monte Carlo
will perform it on Jan. 19 and 21; the San Diego Opera on May 19
(Edoardo Mueller conducting Elena Zelenskaya, Marianne Cornetti,
Richard Leech and Kevin Langan); and the Sarasota Opera in Florida
on Jan. 26 and 28.
</P>
<P>
   As for Verdi's staged works, the Metropolitan Opera has a new
''Il Trovatore'' opening Dec. 7. Carlo Rizzi conducts Marina
Mescheriakova, Dolora Zajick, Neil Shicoff, Roberto Frontal and
Dimitri Kavrakos in a production by the controversial Graham Vick,
whose garishly colored ''Falstaff'' last year reopened The Royal
Opera, Covent Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Luciano Pavarotti makes his only scheduled U.S. opera
appearances of the season -- and, perhaps, his last ever -- at the
Met in ''Aida,'' starting Jan. 15, with Voigt in the title role and
Levine conducting. The matinee performance on Jan. 27 will be
broadcast live around the world.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, for the first time since 1960, the Met will stage
''Nabucco.'' Levine conducts a cast that includes Maria Guleghina,
Marianna Tarasova, Fabio Armiliato, Juan Pons and Samuel Ramey in a
new Elijah Moshinsky production.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Met revives ''A Masked Ball'' and ''La
Traviata.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lyric Opera of Chicago has a new Christopher Alden
production of ''Rigoletto'' on Oct. 21, with Fabuo Luisi conducting
Alexandru Agache, Andrea Rost, Ramon Vargas and Jennifer Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   ''Attila,'' not performed with great frequency, is revived for
Ramey in a Moshinsky production that returns to Chicago on Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Opera has a new Francesca Zambello production
of ''Luisa Miller'' opening its season Sept. 9, with Runnicles
conducting Patricia Racette, Elena Zaremba, Giordani and Paolo
Gavanelli.
</P>
<P>
   And a ''new'' David Edwards production of ''Simon Boccanegra,''
borrowed from Covent Garden, opens June 19 with Runnicles
conducting Carol Vaness, Gavanelli, Giordani, Ramey and Nicolai
Putilin. There also is a revival of ''La Traviata.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the smaller companies, the Houston Grand Opera, borrowing
a production from San Francisco, has a strongly cast ''Don Carlo''
starting April 20 (Vargas, Ramey, Racette, Dwayne Croft, Beatrice
Uria-Monzon and Patrick Summers conducting).
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Opera stages ''Falstaff''; the Los Angeles Opera
presents ''Aida'' with Voigt and Botha (in a production borrowed
from Houston); and the Washington Opera stages ''Don Carlo'' (in a
production borrowed from Chicago) and ''Il Trovatore'' (a
co-production with Los Angeles and the Goeteborg Opera in Sweden).
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the New York Grand Opera Company began performing all
28 Verdi operas in the order in which they were composed, a feat
never before attempted. Next summer, Vincent La Selva, who has
conducted all 25 so far, will present ''Aida,'' ''Otello'' and
''Falstaff.'' On Jan. 27, the 100th anniversary of Verdi's death,
La Selva will conduct his ''Requiem'' at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Verdi is celebrated at La Scala in Milan, which opens
its season Dec. 7 with Muti conducting Leo Nucci, Barbara Frittoli
and Urmana in a new Hugo De Ana production of ''Il Trovatore.''
</P>
<P>
   Muti, La Scala's music director, also conducts a new production
of ''A Masked Ball'' and revivals of ''Rigoletto,'' ''La
Traviata,'' ''Macbeth'' and ''Falstaff,'' with the latter
performances at Verdi's hometown of Busseto on April 10 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, the most ambitious tribute is in Austria, where from
Jan. 8-31 the Vienna State Opera presents nightly performances from
among 12 Verdi operas: ''Aida,'' ''A Masked Ball,'' ''Don Carlo,''
''Ernani,'' ''Jerusalem.'' ''Macbeth,'' ''Otello,'' ''Rigoletto,''
''Stiffelio,'' ''La Traviata,'' ''Il Trovatore'' and ''I Vespri
Siciliani''
</P>
<P>
   In Munich, the Bavarian State Opera presents a Verdi festival
from Jan. 16-28, with Mehta conducting a new Eike Gramss production
of ''Falstaff'' starring Bryn Terfel, Elizabeth Futral and Patricia
Risley. Mehta also leads revivals of ''Don Carlo'' and ''Otello,''
while John Fiore conducts ''Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deutsche Oper Berlin presents 16 Verdi performances from
Jan. 7-Feb. 4, staging ''A Masked Ball,'' ''Falstaff,'' ''Luisa
Miller,'' ''Nabucco'' ''La Traviata'' and ''Il Trovatore.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, The Royal Opera stages three revivals -- ''Falstaff,''
''La Traviata'' and ''Otello'' with Argentinean tenor Jose Cura
singing the title role under the baton of Daniele Gatti starting
April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Cura also sings in the Vienna ''Otello'' and in a Juergen Flimm
production at the Chatelet starting March 26 (Myung-Whun Chung
conducting Karita Mattila and Anthony Michaels-Moore).
</P>
<P>
   The Opera de Paris has revivals of ''Nabucco'' and ''Don
Carlo,'' and the Chatelet presents ''Falstaff'' with Sir John Eliot
Gardiner conducting the Revolutionary and Romantic Orchestra and
Jean-Philippe Lafont, Juan Diego Flore, Michaels-Moore and Rebecca
Evans.
</P>
<P>
   The Teatro Real in Madrid has new productions of ''Don Carlo''
(Roberto Scandiuzzi, Neil Shicoff, Dario Volonte, Dmitri
Hvorostovsky and Navarro conducting) and ''Il Trovatore'' (Navarro
conducting Cura, Michele Crider, Carlo Guelfi and Nina Terentieva).
The Gran Teatre del Liceu in Barcelona has a new production of ''A
Masked Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the music labels, a new recording of the ''Requiem'' is
being released by Universal Classics, with Valery Gergiev
conducting the Kirov Opera Orchestra and Bocelli, Fleming, Borodina
and Ildebrando D'Arcangelo. Universal also is releasing a Verdi
disk by Bocelli with Mehta conducting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Aroldo'' (Shicoff and Vaness), ''Jerusalem'' (Giordani) and
''Alzira'' (Mescheriakova, Gavanelli and Vargas) will be released
by Philips, leaving the original French version of ''Les Vespres
Sicillennes'' as the only Verdi opera not available on CD.
</P>
<P>
   As for other composers, the Met has new stagings of Beethoven's
''Fidelio,'' Busoni's ''Dr. Faust'' and Prokofiev's ''The
Gambler.'' The Met season starts Sept. 25 with Levine conducting
Fleming and Terfel in Mozart's ''Don Giovanni.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Sept. 11 sees the opening of Rimsky-Korsakov's
''The Tsar's Bride,'' a co-production with Washington. Also this
season, San Francisco will have its premiere performance of Douglas
Moore's ''The Ballad of Baby Doe''; the world premiere of Jake
Heggie's ''Dead Man Walking,'' with libretto by Terrence McNally;
the San Francisco premier of Handel's ''Semele'' (a co-production
with Covent Garden); and ''Der Rosenkavalier.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has new productions of Tchaikovsky's ''The Queen of
Spades,'' Janacek's ''Jenufa'' and Wagner's ''The Flying
Dutchman,'' and imports the Met's world premiere production of John
Harbison's ''The Great Gatsby,'' which opened to mixed reviews last
December.
</P>
<P>
   Also this season, Voigt sings the title role in Puccini's
''Tosca'' for the first time, at the Florida Grand Opera in Miami,
with Renata Scotto directing. At the Baltimore Opera, Scotto sings
Klytemnestra in Strauss' ''Electra'' for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Flanigan opens the New York City Opera season Sept. 12 in
Donizetti's ''Roberto Devereaux,'' and Futral stars in a a new
''The Ballad of Baby Doe.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Wagner, Placido Domingo will sing the title role in
''Parsifal'' at Washington, Paris, Madrid and the Met. With Voigt,
he has an excellent EMI recording just out with excerpts from
''Tristan und Isolde'' and ''Siegfried.''
</P>
<P>
   Among touring ensembles, the Staatskapelle Berlin and Barenboim
come to Carnegie Hall Dec. 11-17 for performances of all nine
Beethoven symphonies. On May 6 at Carnegie, Levine leads Voigt and
the Met Orchestra in Schoenberg's ''Gurrelieder.''
</P>
<P>
   Other major recordings scheduled for release are Fleming in
Massenet's ''Thais'' (Decca); Cecilia Bartoli and David Daniels in
Handel's ''Rinaldo'' (Decca); Cura in Leoncavallo's ''Pagliacci''
(Decca); Kasarova and Vargas in Donizetti's ''La Favorite'' (RCA);
Gheorghiu and Alagna in Massenet's ''Manon'' (EMI); Bocelli in
Puccini's ''La Boheme'' (Decca); Cura and Eteri Gvazava in Verdi's
''La Traviata'' (Atlantic); and Abbado conducting the Berlin
Philharmonic in the nine Beethoven symphonies (Deutsche
Grammophon).
</P>
<P>
   Decca is reissuing Beverly Sills' performances of Donizetti's
three Tudor queens on CD: ''Roberto Devereaux,'' ''Anna Bolena''
and ''Maria Stuarda.''
</P>
<P>
   EMI is issuing a Duke Ellington CD with Sir Simon Rattle,
Abbado's successor in Berlin, and is putting out a 32-CD set
honoring Domingo's 30th anniversary with the label.
</P>
<P>
   Also, DG will begin to issue operas on DVD for the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
