<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angels, Ogres, Witches in New Movies  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Loads of comedy. Horror. Animation. And all
that serious stuff by movie types hoping to bag an Oscar. This is
Hollywood serving up its usual fall feast.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the crowd of year-end movies, aren't we all really
waiting to hear two catch phrases culled from the small screen:
''Good morning, Angels'' and ''You're a mean one, Mr. Grinch''?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the year's most anticipated movies hit theaters in
November. ''Charlie's Angels'' arrives Nov. 3, with Drew Barrymore,
Cameron Diaz and Lucy Liu starring as the trio of glamorous
detectives in this update of the campy 1970s TV series. Bill Murray
co-stars as office bean counter Bosley, and John Forsythe is back
as the voice of the Angels' wealthy, mysterious boss.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Nov. 17, Hollywood goes Whoville with ''Dr. Seuss' How
the Grinch Stole Christmas,'' starring Jim Carrey as that holiday
ogre with spiders in his brain and a heart full of unwashed socks,
who simply must find a way to stop Christmas. The live-action
adaptation of the children's book and TV chestnut from the 1960s
co-stars Molly Shannon, Jeffrey Tambor, Christine Baranski and
Taylor Momsen as Cindy Lou Who.
</P>
<P>
   ''The great thing about the Grinch is he's a little manic, kind
of a kook, kind of crazy. Jim devised a multidimensional, very
entertaining Grinch that's not just a one-note grouch,'' director
Ron Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Other fall highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Sports: Denzel Washington as a football coach in ''Remember the
Titans''; Robert Redford's golfing fable ''The Legend of Bagger
Vance,'' with Will Smith and Matt Damon.
</P>
<P>
   Horror: Witching time returns with ''Book of Shadows: Blair
Witch 2,'' about thrill-seekers visiting the woods depicted in the
blockbuster first film; ''Wes Craven Presents: Dracula 2000,''
bringing the vampire into modern times; the slasher sequel ''Urban
Legends: Final Cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics: the sex-and-politics drama ''The Contender,'' with
Joan Allen, Jeff Bridges and Gary Oldman; Kevin Costner as a JFK
aide in the missiles of October drama ''13 Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Sci-fi: Arnold Schwarzenegger in the cloning thriller ''The 6th
Day''; Carrie-Anne Moss and Val Kilmer as Mars adventurers in ''Red
Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicals: Nicole Kidman and Ewan McGregor in ''Moulin Rouge,''
set in seamy 1890s Paris; a movie rendition of the long-running
''The Fantasticks,'' featuring Joel Grey; pop singer Bjork and
Catherine Deneuve in ''Dancer in the Dark,'' winner of the Palme
d'Or at the Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Animation: ''Rugrats in Paris -- The Movie''; ''The Emperor's New
Groove,'' featuring the voices of David Spade, John Goodman and
Eartha Kitt; another entry borrowed from Japan, ''Digimon: The
Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup also includes Antonio Banderas and Angelina Jolie in
the steamy ''Original Sin''; Damon again in the adaptation of the
best seller ''All the Pretty Horses''; Glenn Close's return as
Cruella De Vil in ''102 Dalmatians''; ''Bounce,'' with Gwyneth
Paltrow and Ben Affleck in a romance that arises from a plane
crash; and Sally Field's directorial debut with ''Beautiful,''
starring Minnie Driver.
</P>
<P>
   There's ''Get Carter,'' starring Sylvester Stallone as a mobster
investigating his brother's death; Michael Douglas and Catherine
Zeta-Jones in the drug saga ''Traffic,'' directed by Steven
Soderbergh; ''Miss Congeniality,'' with Sandra Bullock playing an
FBI agent undercover as a beauty contestant; Cate Blanchett, Hilary
Swank and Keanu Reeves in the spooky Southern thriller ''The
Gift''; and ''The Yards,'' a crime drama starring Mark Wahlberg.
</P>
<P>
   Also Nicolas Cage in the suburban fantasy ''The Family Man'';
the Cage-produced ''Shadow of the Vampire,'' with John Malkovich
and Willem Dafoe in a dramatization of the making of ''Nosferatu'';
Jamie Foxx in the gold-theft caper ''Bait''; Russell Crowe and Meg
Ryan in the abduction thriller ''Proof of Life''; Jude Law as a
Russian sharpshooter during World War II in ''Enemy at the Gates'';
''Finding Forrester,'' with Sean Connery as a reclusive writer;
Barry Levinson's tale of Belfast toupee entrepreneurs, ''An
Everlasting Piece''; and Spike Lee's satire of network television,
''Bamboozled.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel and Ethan Coen return with ''O Brother, Where Art Thou?'',
a 1930s retelling of Homer's ''The Odyssey'' focusing on three
chain-gang escapees. George Clooney, John Turturro, Holly Hunter
and John Goodman co-star.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Coen's wife, Frances McDormand, is back with a reissue of
the overlooked ''Wonder Boys'' from last winter and a stellar role
in ''Almost Famous,'' the first film by writer-director Cameron
Crowe since ''Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   McDormand plays a character based on Crowe's mother in the
autobiographical story of the director's adventures as a
15-year-old music writer for Rolling Stone in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've read a few mother roles in my life. Ever since I was 25,
I've been offered mother roles,'' McDormand said. ''I haven't done
that many because I'm not interested in generic roles. That didn't
really interest me. But this one, she's full, she's complete. She
quotes Goethe, for God's sake. It was heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long layoff since her Oscar-winning performance in
1997's ''As Good As It Gets,'' Helen Hunt returns in a big way,
appearing in four films.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt co-stars with Richard Gere in Robert Altman's ''Dr. T &AMP; the
Women,'' the story of a gynecologist with lady trouble; with Kevin
Spacey and Haley Joel Osment in ''Pay It Forward,'' the tale of a
scarred teacher's unusual relationship with a boy and his mother;
with Mel Gibson in ''What Women Want,'' about an ad exec who uses
his newfound mind-reading skills to his advantage; and with Tom
Hanks in Robert Zemeckis' ''Cast Away,'' the story of a man
stranded on an island after a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just very busy this past year,'' said Hunt, who took a
year and a half off after ''As Good As It Gets'' and the final
season of her TV series ''Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't really find anything that interested me for a while,
then they all just kind of came in, bang, bang, bang, bang. It was
great because they were all different parts and different kinds of
movies and directors, and needed a different process for each
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert De Niro has two films coming. In ''Men of Honor,'' he
plays reluctant mentor to the Navy's first black master diver (Cuba
Gooding Jr.). In the comedy ''Meet the Parents,'' De Niro is an
ex-CIA profiler casting a cold eye on his daughter's jittery
prospective husband (Ben Stiller).
</P>
<P>
   ''De Niro's on him like only De Niro can get on him,'' director
Jay Roach said. ''He's the sort of guy you'd imagine has fat
dossiers on every single boyfriend who's ever come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director M. Night Shyamalan re-teams with his ''The Sixth
Sense'' star Bruce Willis for ''Unbreakable,'' another flick with
supernatural elements. Willis plays the sole survivor of a train
wreck, who comes through without a scratch. His ''Die Hard With a
Vengeance'' sidekick Samuel L. Jackson plays a stranger offering a
bizarre explanation for his survival.
</P>
<P>
   It's a different game for Shyamalan, with expectations through
the roof after ''The Sixth Sense'' surprised Hollywood by grossing
$300 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to hit it out of the park for people to be happy,''
Shyamalan said.
</P>
<P>
   Has he achieved that with ''Unbreakable''?
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope, man,'' Shyamalan said.
</P>
<P>
   John Travolta faces the opposite situation; anything is bound to
be an improvement over last spring's ''Battlefield Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta returns with a more promising role in the lottery scam
''Lucky Numbers,'' a dark comedy directed by Nora Ephron and
co-starring Lisa Kudrow. The movie is loosely based on a real-life
scheme to rig the lottery. Travolta's character, a TV weatherman,
enlists the help of the station's lotto-ball girl (Kudrow), a woman
with a serious criminal streak, Ephron said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have never seen her do this. She makes Barbara Stanwyck
look sweet,'' Ephron said. ''Lisa's the kind of person who can play
someone sort of pathologically evil and still have you like her.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of evil, the devil gets his due with a slew of demonic
thrillers and comedies. Adam Sandler plays Satan's addlebrained son
in ''Little Nicky,'' a comedy that pits him against his devilish
older brothers. Elizabeth Hurley gives the devil a bombshell body
in ''Bedazzled,'' co-starring Brendan Fraser as a chump who sells
his soul for wealth and fame. There's a new cut of the horror
classic ''The Exorcist,'' plus added footage and improved sound.
''Lost Souls'' stars Winona Ryder as a woman trying to prevent a
satanic conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Lost souls bring us back to the Grinch. The movie features a
score by Oscar winner James Horner (''Titanic'') and two songs from
the TV cartoon including ''You're a Mean One,'' which Carrey's
Grinch sings as a soliloquy on his own wickedness.
</P>
<P>
   In this version, the meanness of the Grinch, a ''sort of
ultimately benign misanthrope,'' stems from deep-seated hurts in
his past, director Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   The film adds some new characters and fills in the back story of
how the Grinch arrived in Whoville, what prompted him to live alone
in a cave and, most important, what stirred his hatred for the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ''We plant the seeds for his outrage at Christmas and his
annoyance with the Whos and show that it's not just a petty thing
with him,'' Howard said. ''It runs deep.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The summer bombast and special-effects blitz
is over. Now Hollywood turns to its prestige season.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the fall slate (release dates are subject to
change):
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   ALMOST FAMOUS: Cameron Crowe's first film since ''Jerry
Maguire'' follows a teen on a rock assignment from Rolling Stone.
Billy Crudup, Frances McDormand and newcomer Patrick Fugit star.
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTAGE: Behind-the-scenes look at hip-hop features Jay-Z,
DMX, Method Man.
</P>
<P>
   BAIT: Jamie Foxx plays a prawn thief used by the feds to track a
master gold thief.
</P>
<P>
   BEST IN SHOW: Christopher Guest directs a comic ensemble of
dog-show contenders, including ''Spinal Tap'' band mate Michael
McKean, and Parker Posey, Eugene Levy and Catherine O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL: Sally Field's directing debut is a buddy flick about
an obsessed beauty contestant (Minnie Driver) who has a
disqualifying secret.
</P>
<P>
   THE BROKEN HEARTS CLUB: Romance and reflection revolving around
a gay man (Timothy Olyphant) and his circle of friends. With John
Mahoney, Nia Long, Dean Cain.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME + PUNISHMENT IN SUBURBIA: Brooding tale of a vengeful teen
(Monica Keena) who enlists her boyfriend in a murder plot. Ellen
Barkin co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   DANCER IN THE DARK: The Palme d'Or winner at Cannes features
Bjork in a musical fantasy as a Czech immigrant saving cash for her
son's sight-saving surgery. Catherine Deneuve co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE PARKED: Comic drama centers on a determined meter maid
(Callie Thorne) struggling for a better life for her sickly son.
</P>
<P>
   DUETS: Gwyneth Paltrow is a Las Vegas showgirl among an ensemble
of karaoke fanatics taking a road trip to a singing contest.
Directed by Paltrow's father, Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   THE EXORCIST: Linda Blair's pea soup has had 27 years to
ferment, but William Friedkin's satanic scare fest still chills.
New sound effects, footage, digital sound.
</P>
<P>
   THE FANTASTICKS: Try to remember when this musical wasn't
playing off-Broadway. The big-screen adaptation stars Joel Grey and
Barnard Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLFIGHT: Co-winner of the Sundance Film Festival top prize,
this gritty feature stars Michelle Rodriguez as a young woman who
finds an outlet for her anger in the boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   INTO THE ARMS OF STRANGERS: Narrated by Judi Dench, this
documentary recounts Britain's rescue of imperiled children from
Germany, Czechoslovakia and Austria just before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT LUGGAGE: Isabella Rossellini and Maximilian Schell co-star
in the tale of a girl who takes a job with a tradition-bound
Hasidic family.
</P>
<P>
   NURSE BETTY: Renee Zellweger plays a waitress on a fantasy quest
to find romance with a soap-opera character, with a pair of violent
criminals (Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock) in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   PARAGRAPH 175: This documentary examines a lesser-known tragedy
of Nazi Germany: persecution of homosexual men.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER THE TITANS: Denzel Washington plays a football coach
who takes over a racially divisive high-school team in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   THE SPECIALS: Second-fiddle superheroes land an action-figure
deal as their personal lives unravel. Rob Lowe stars.
</P>
<P>
   THE TAVERN: Two unfulfilled men test their friendship when they
buy a Manhattan bar. Written and directed by Walter Foote, son of
playwright Horton Foote.
</P>
<P>
   THIS IS SPINAL TAP: The cult classic turns it up to 11 again.
Rob Reiner's ''documentary'' about aging Brit-rockers comes back to
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   TIGERLAND: Joel Schumacher spins the tale of a soldier who
rescues draftees from Vietnam by scamming military discharges.
</P>
<P>
   UNDER SUSPICION: An aging Caribbean cop (Morgan Freeman) grills
a successful ex-colleague (Gene Hackman) who's suspected of murder.
</P>
<P>
   URBANIA: Dan Futterman as a man in turmoil who pegs his
salvation on the pursuit of a stranger spotted in a chance
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN LEGENDS: FINAL CUT: Tall tales provide bloody grist for
the follow-up to the horror hit ''Urban Legends.''
</P>
<P>
   THE WATCHER: James Spader, Marisa Tomei and Keanu Reeves co-star
in a yarn about an FBI agent shadowed by a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   THE WAY OF THE GUN: Two crooks (Benicio Del Toro, Ryan
Phillippe) kidnap a surrogate mother (Juliette Lewis) for ransom.
Taye Diggs, James Caan co-star.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN ON TOP: A wife (Penelope Cruz) flees a lousy marriage in
Brazil to take up a culinary career in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   OCTOBER
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL FACTORY: Steve Buscemi directs Edward Furlong and Willem
Dafoe in a drama about a jailed youth who finds a prison mentor.
</P>
<P>
   BAMBOOZLED: Spike Lee satirizes race and ratings on network
television. Damon Wayans, Jada Pinkett-Smith and Michael Rapaport
star.
</P>
<P>
   BEDAZZLED: Brendan Fraser strikes a deal with Satan (Elizabeth
Hurley) for wealth, fame and talent to win a woman's heart.
</P>
<P>
   BILLY ELLIOT: A British miner's son bucks Dad's wishes and
trains as a dancer in this sweet family drama. Julie Walters
co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK OF SHADOWS: BLAIR WITCH 2: The witch in the woods returns
in the first of two planned follow-ups to the horror blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   BOOTMEN: A hoofer (Adam Garcia) sets out to escape life in the
Australian steel mills by reinventing the art of tap dancing.
</P>
<P>
   BOUNCE: Ben Affleck is an ad man who strikes up a relationship
with the widow (Gwyneth Paltrow) of a man who took his seat on a
doomed airplane.
</P>
<P>
   THE CONTENDER: Joan Allen plays a senator whose nomination for
the vice presidency is jeopardized by a sex scandal. Jeff Bridges,
Gary Oldman and Christian Slater co-star.
</P>
<P>
   DIGIMON: THE MOVIE: An Internet monster threatens the
inhabitants of Digiworld, who get help from real kids in this
animated tale.
</P>
<P>
   DR. T &AMP; THE WOMEN: Robert Altman's latest ensemble tale centers
on a gynecologist (Richard Gere) and the women in his life.
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOWERS: Two white friends are assigned the unpleasant task of
targeting a black buddy for fraternity hazing.
</P>
<P>
   GET CARTER: Sylvester Stallone in a remake of British thriller
about a mobster whose brother's death leads him to revenge and
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   JUST ONE TIME: An engaged couple finds comic mayhem when both
agree to carry out threesome sexual fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   THE LADIES MAN: Tim Meadows stars as a skirt-chaser trying to
track down a mysterious, wealthy ex-lover, while jealous husbands
hunt him.
</P>
<P>
   THE LITTLE VAMPIRE: A boy and his young vampire pal search for a
magic pendant to save a legion of bloodsuckers. Based on Angela
Sommer-Bodenburg's children's books.
</P>
<P>
   LOST SOULS: Winona Ryder teams with a crime writer (Ben Chaplin)
to thwart a worldwide satanic conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY NUMBERS: John Travolta is a cash-strapped TV weatherman
who rigs the state lottery with his station's lotto-ball girl (Lisa
Kudrow).
</P>
<P>
   MEET THE PARENTS: Robert De Niro plays a merciless father who
puts his prospective son-in-law (Ben Stiller) through hell.
</P>
<P>
   THE NIGHTMARE BEFORE CHRISTMAS: Reissue of Tim Burton's animated
tale of Halloween's Pumpkin King, who leads an assault to take over
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   PAY IT FORWARD: Kevin Spacey, Helen Hunt and Haley Joel Osment
in the tale of a teacher who inspires a student to ''pay forward''
acts of human kindness.
</P>
<P>
   REQUIEM FOR A DREAM: Somber drama of a shiftless man, his
girlfriend, drug-dealing buddy and delusional mom. Ellen Burstyn,
Jared Leto, Jennifer Connelly and Marlon Wayans star.
</P>
<P>
   RING OF FIRE: A bull-rider's rodeo career threatens his
relationship with his brother. Kiefer Sutherland, Daryl Hannah,
Molly Ringwald co-star.
</P>
<P>
   A ROOM FOR ROMEO BRASS: Coming-of-age tale about two misfits in
Britain dealing with tough family lives. Bob Hoskins co-stars.
</P>
<P>
   STARDOM: The fast rise of a supermodel (Jessica Pare) chronicles
the pitfalls of fame. With Dan Aykroyd, Frank Langella, Thomas
Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   TWO FAMILY HOUSE: The Sundance audience award winner captures
the romance between a married Italian-American (Michael Rispoli)
and an abandoned Irishwoman (Kelly Macdonald) with a newborn.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND: Friends and family gather on the anniversary of a
loved one's death. Gena Rowlands, Brooke Shields, D.B. Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   THE YARDS: Mark Wahlberg, James Caan and Charlize Theron in a
crime drama set in New York's subway yards.
</P>
<P>
   NOVEMBER
</P>
