<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Author Tells About Bout With Cancer  </HEADLINE>
By MARTHA WAGGONER
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSBOROUGH, N.C. (AP) -- He's a snake-handling ex-Marine who
wears metallic blue nail polish on his big toes, a heavy drinker
who swore off alcohol almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McLaurin is also a man who had lived such a full life that,
until love unexpectedly knocked at the door a few months ago, he
was ready to die.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wondered if my role at that point was that it was time for
me to die (and) to chronicle that in writing, straightforward and
honestly, and I was willing to do that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not many would envy McLaurin his life. But anyone who has ever
waved at the parade instead of leading the band would envy his
courage to not only live it, but revel in it.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up poor, shooting squirrels and birds for dinner, a way
of life chronicled his 1991 childhood memoir, ''Keeper of the
Moon,'' a tribute to a disappearing rural South. He's one of six
children whose father was a machine operator at a bakery and a
part-time farmer and whose mother was a housewife.
</P>
<P>
   The book won a local award for nonfiction and was included on
The New York Times list of the best books of the year.
</P>
<P>
   At 18, he joined the Marine Corps, which he considered his only
chance to see a part of the world other than North Carolina. He's
been married and divorced twice, and has two teen-age children. He
was a Peace Corps volunteer in Tunisia and a traveling snake
showman in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He went to college intermittently, finally graduating in 1985
from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. From grammar
school on, he showed a talent for writing, but he mostly let that
talent lay dormant until college. Author Doris Betts mentored
McLaurin on his first novel, ''The Acorn Plan,'' which won a state
prize for fiction writing.
</P>
<P>
   By the age of 44, both of his hips had been replaced because of
arthritis, a result of treatment for multiple myeloma, a type of
cancer formed by malignant plasma cells. His battle with the cancer
10 years ago, including a bone marrow transplant from a brother,
culminated in a four-day canoe trip down the Neuse River to raise
awareness for the need for bone marrow donors.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, he says, was a way to get back to his real life after
eight months in the sterile world of hospitals. ''It was just total
solitude, and it was just exactly what I needed,'' he says, despite
rain that fell so hard the first day that he had to bail out the
canoe with an empty Spam can.
</P>
<P>
   Less well-known is his bout in the past year with cancer of the
esophagus.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis and treatment required a 15-page epilogue for his
seventh book, ''The River Less Run,'' a chronicle of his life from
June 1998 to June 1999, to be released in September by North
Carolina-based Down Home Press.
</P>
<P>
   It was in November, when swallowing became painful, that he was
diagnosed with esophageal cancer. He underwent two rounds of
chemotherapy and one of radiation. Cancer of the esophagus is a
take-no-prisoners kind of disease: life expectancy beyond five
years after diagnosis is only about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McLaurin's doctors have declared him free of it. The
46-year-old McLaurin again may have beaten death.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't his plan at first. This time, he had wondered if it
was time to die. His children were old enough to have memories of
him, his book was finished, what he thought was his last trip West
was finished and he wasn't involved with a woman.
</P>
<P>
   When a record-setting two feet of snow fell on North Carolina in
January, he took it as an omen. He had always dreamed of such a
snowfall and thought it might have foretold his death. More than
anything, he was simply tired.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just didn't want to deal with the hassle of being sick. I
didn't want to deal with being poked and prodded and that loss of
privacy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   What turned him around was the arrival of Carol Quaine, a friend
of a friend who says she felt called to McLaurin's door.
</P>
<P>
   Even she fits in with McLaurin's contradictory life. By
profession, she does free-lance statistical analysis and is
finishing her doctorate in business. By calling, she's a healer
trained in Reiki, a healing technique developed in Japan by a
Buddhist monk in the late 1700s and early 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived one day in mid-February and offered the touch of her
healing hands.
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin says the first time she placed her hands on his chest,
he thought she was using a heating pad. ''Almost everyday for three
weeks she returned and placed her hands upon me, wafted fragrant
smoke upon my body, lit candles and rang bells,'' he wrote in a
newspaper story. ''She told me that sometimes when I talked to her,
leaves and feathers fell in a shower from above my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Her love and trust made him rethink his reluctance to fight. ''I
started thinking maybe your story isn't to end right here, to tell
people how to die. Maybe you've got other stories to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither credits Quaine alone with saving McLaurin's life. She
says he was cured ''by some of the best Western medicine and some
of the deepest love.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaurin wants to memorialize his survival by having a phoenix
tattooed on his chest where he received radiation. The bird will
join tattoos of family names, flowers and animals that adorn his
right arm and the snakes and birds on his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   The toenails are a simpler matter. The first time, a young
visitor painted his two big toenails a metallic blue, a color
favored by halter-topped teens. Since then, he and Quaine have
repainted them a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kind of like it,'' McLaurin says. ''Some people might look
at it and think it's weird, but I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a child, McLaurin was willing to be the odd man, to
question what he was told. He was taught that snakes were to be
feared and killed. But when he chopped up a harmless rat snake, he
felt guilty enough to read about snakes, learning that most of what
he had been taught was a myth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Snakes,'' he says, ''represent a way of overcoming ignorance
and fear. And overcoming ignorance in small steps is a way to fix a
lot of what's wrong with the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he finds comfort in the world he and Carol have made in
Hillsborough with McLaurin's bulldog, Roy Lee, his red-tail boa,
bull and Gaboon viper snakes and an African spur-footed tortoise
named George.
</P>
<P>
   He smokes two cigars a day -- 45-cent Phillies Blunts that he
prefers to Cuban cigars. ''I don't see that big a difference,'' he
says. ''Maybe I cropped so much tobacco growing up that I'm immune
to the finer qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't do anymore is drink. He went on an epic drunk in
November 1998 that landed him in the hospital. He says it was
deliberate -- one last blowout so he could walk away from the bottle
once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used that part of my life up until it was dust in my palm
and I could blow it away and it was gone,'' McLaurin says.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes his children live their lives as he has, with a sense
of adventure, a courage to look death in the eye without flinching
and to walk away with the will to live.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope they want to travel and seek and explore -- I hope they
make it to the moon,'' he says. ''I always thought that during my
lifetime, I'd make it to the moon -- that by the age of 46, there
were Pan-Am excursions to the moon. But we stopped going to the
moon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1204 </TRAILER>
