<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Solidarity Has 20th Birthday  </HEADLINE>
By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   GDANSK, Poland (AP) -- Solidarity union members gave a standing
ovation to founder Lech Walesa at a congress Wednesday marking the
20th birthday of the former East Bloc's first independent labor
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity sprang up in 1980 in a wave of strikes that began the
demise of communism. Wednesday's congress gathered more than 2,000
former and present union members, including Walesa and other
leaders of the historic strikes as well as advisers like Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, Poland's first post-communist premier.
</P>
<P>
   Walesa was cheered by the crowd as he entered the one-day
congress, held at a Gdansk sports hall. He took a front-row seat
along with Marian Krzaklewski, his successor as union chairman --
and rival long-shot candidate in this fall's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In a message read by Gdansk Cardinal Tadeusz Goclowski,
Polish-born Pope John Paul II gave thanks for ''all the good which
those two decades brought to our homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity toppled the communist system in 1989 and has held
power since then except for a 1993-97 hiatus. The movement has
carried out democratic and market reforms to transform Poland from
an inefficient communist country into a modern, Western-style
nation.
</P>
<P>
   However, the reforms, which filled stores with consumer goods
and brought $40 billion in foreign investment, also caused
dissatisfaction among many social groups. Growing unemployment and
a shrinking social safety net have resulted recently in a sharp
decline in public support for Solidarity, which itself is now
plagued by divisions and internal feuding over power and influence.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech, Walesa stressed how much Solidarity activists had
accomplished. He urged them to stay united and ''on the side of
Poland.''
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic strike leader who became Poland's first
post-communist president avoided directly addressing Solidarity's
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   A much more dramatic analysis came from Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek, a Solidarity activist. He appealed for a return to historic
Solidarity ideals in the face of opinion polls showing President
Aleksander Kwasniewski, an ex-communist, could easily get
re-elected in the Oct. 8 balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity has tenuous control of Poland's parliament, but
Kwasniewski looks likely to keep his hold on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a lack of responsibility for the country if we
ignored clear signs that today this force (ex-communists) is even
closer to a monopoly of power,'' Buzek said. ''The way to avoid it
is unity.''
</P>
<P>
   The congress is a part of three days of festivities marking the
anniversary. The celebration began Tuesday with the opening of the
exhibition ''Roads to Freedom'' at the historic Gdansk shipyard,
where Solidarity was born in August 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight comes Thursday with commemorations marking the
signing of the so-called Gdansk Agreement. That pact, meant to
bring more freedom and better conditions for workers, ended a
two-week nationwide strike and marked Solidarity's beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements were signed by Walesa, then a little-known
shipyard electrician who led the strikers, and communist Deputy
Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Jagielski. But Poland's communist rulers
backed away from the deal in December 1981 and tried to crush the
union with martial law. It took eight more years of steady
resistance before Solidarity toppled the regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1205 </TRAILER>
