<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 70; Nasdaq Gains 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of brokerage companies surged Wednesday
following news that Credit Suisse had agreed to buy Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, but the overall market was mixed in lackluster
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was off 69.55 to 11,145.55 in
midday trading. The Nasdaq composite index was up 2.94 at 4,085.11,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.56 at 1,505.28.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages and financial services stocks gained after Credit
Suisse Group said it was buying DLJ for $11.5 billion, sending DLJ
shares up $4.375 to $88.375 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in other brokerages rose on anticipation of further
consolidation in the industry, including Lehman Brothers, up $3.25
to $143.25 and JP Morgan, up $4 at $153.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, off $2.813 at $130.063, was leading some computer shares
lower in some profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the Nasdaq, Amazon rose $3 to $42.625 following some
bullish comments from a Goldman Sachs analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a narrow margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 388.02 million
shares, up from Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.51 at 530.14.
</P>
<P>
