<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 92; Nasdaq Adds 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of brokerage companies surged Wednesday
following news that Credit Suisse had agreed to buy Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, but the overall market was mixed in lackluster
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was off 91.75 to 11,123.35 in
midafternoon trading. The Nasdaq composite index was up 2.99 at
4,085.16, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 8.32 at
1,501.52.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages and financial services stocks gained after Credit
Suisse Group said it was buying DLJ for $11.5 billion, sending DLJ
shares up $4.50 to $88.50 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in other brokerages rose on anticipation of further
consolidation in the industry, including J.P. Morgan, up $3.75 at
$152.75. Shares of Lehman Brothers rose initially but were down
12.5 cents at $140.38 by midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, off $23 at $129.88, was leading some computer shares lower
in profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the Nasdaq, Amazon.com rose $3.38 to $43 following some
bullish comments from a Goldman Sachs analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a narrow margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 555.91 million
shares, up from Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.49 at 530.12.
</P>
<P>
