<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Online Cancer Diary Draws Attention  </HEADLINE>
By JOE McDONALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- After painful surgery and doses of
radiation failed to stop the tumor growing in his neck, Lu Youqing
decided he'd suffered enough.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old real-estate developer halted his treatment and
prepared to die. But instead of retreating into privacy to await
death, Lu made his story public by creating a diary on a Shanghai
Web site chronicling his final weeks.
</P>
<P>
   His ''Diary of Death'' has become a minor literary sensation.
Lu's candid account of his failing health, bouts of depression and
sense of loss have attracted thousands of Web surfers a day and
touched off a debate about death.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to awaken the concern and love of society toward
cancer patients,'' Lu said in an interview. ''I think I have the
responsibility to speak out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lu posted his first entry Aug. 3 and said he expected to live no
more than 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   An operation and six radiation treatments had failed to stop the
spread of a malignant tumor on a salivary gland in front of his
right ear. He said he halted treatment in February against his
doctor's advice.
</P>
<P>
   Coming six years after Lu lost 80 percent of his stomach when
surgeons removed a separate cancer, the new treatment left him weak
and emaciated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt the routine treatment method wasn't helping my illness,
but I still had to suffer terrible physical and spiritual pain, as
well as paying a lot for it,'' Lu said. ''I have the right to
choose the way I want to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Lu begins his day at 6:30 a.m., settling into a sofa in his
bedroom to write on a laptop computer. A 2,000- to 3,000-word entry
takes four to five hours, and he sometimes nods off from fatigue.
He posts a new entry every two to three days.
</P>
<P>
   Lu no longer has the energy to work at the real-estate company
where he is assistant general manager. His wife has quit her
teaching job to care for him. The couple have a 10-year-old
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lu said he already has lived longer than his doctors predicted.
He gives some of the credit to a new sense of purpose the diary has
given him.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people are surprised at how he managed to live so
long,'' said his wife, Shi Muyan. ''Supported by his strength of
will, we have managed to travel this far. I think every day he
lives is a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Lu's way of dying has drawn mixed public reaction in letters to
newspapers and comments on Web sites. Some praise Lu's composure,
while others appeal to him to fight death.
</P>
<P>
   ''A really brave person ... should battle unfair fate and take
responsibility for his family. He should receive 36, even 60,
radiation treatments,'' a reader wrote to the Shanghai Youth Daily
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In his diary, Lu reminisces about childhood and talks about his
family and love of singing. Though he says the diary is meant to
lift readers' spirits, he also writes frankly about his sorrow at
seeing his life cut short.
</P>
<P>
   ''God gave me less than 40 years of life, probably only half the
time he gives to others. Even if he has shown me the most beautiful
paintings of living, I still have the right to complain that I
don't get enough time to appreciate them,'' says one entry.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his occasional flashes of dark humor, Lu writes that
he wished he died in the Concorde jetliner crash July 25 outside
Paris. Death would be quick, he says, and Air France would pay his
family compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Diary of Death'' appears on the Shanghai-based literary
Web site www.Rongshu.com. It shares the site with more traditional
artistic fare such as poetry, Chinese painting and a series of
photographs by American artist Cindy Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   The diary, which is in Chinese, gets 2,000 to 3,000 readers a
day, said Jin Jun, Lu's editor at Rongshu.com. He said that number
was limited by the site's slow Web access, and could be much higher
without such technical constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Rongshu.com is considering publishing the completed diary as a
book, Jin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a terrific story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------	   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Site, in Chinese, http://www.rongshu.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
