<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Sept.
3-9:
<TEXT>
<P>
   80 years ago: D.W. Griffith's movie ''Way Down East'' opened.
The film starred Lillian Gish and Richard Barthelmess. Gish was
shot drifting away on an ice floe, trailing her hand in freezing
water.
</P>
<P>
   75 years ago: ''The Phantom of the Opera'' starred Lon Chaney.
The film was remade several times.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Pretty Ladies'' was released, starring ZaSu Pitts. Three
of the bit players in the film were Norma Shearer, Joan Crawford
and -- in her film debut -- Myrna Loy.
</P>
<P>
   65 years ago: The Hoboken Four, which included 19-year-old Frank
Sinatra, appeared on the radio program Major Bowes' Amateur Hour.
This first big break for Sinatra led to a $50-a-week job with the
show.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Tumbling Tumbleweeds,'' Gene Autry's first Western
feature, was released. It cost $18,000 to shoot and grossed $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   60 years ago: Carole Lombard -- teasing director Alfred Hitchcock
for calling actors ''cattle'' -- brought three heifers to the set of
''Mr. and Mrs. Smith.'' Each heifer was tagged with the name of an
actor in the film.
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: An ad in Variety announced auditions for the
Monkees, a rock quartet that starred in a youth-oriented TV comedy
series. The show ran for two years. The Monkees simultaneously had
a successful record career.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Gerard Depardieu was named best actor at the
Venice Film Festival. He won the award for his tough-guy
performance in the French film ''Police.''
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: Robert Wagner and Stefanie Powers, stars of the
1979-84 TV series ''Hart to Hart,'' announced they would make their
London stage debuts in ''Love Letters,'' a play by American A.R.
Gurney.
</P>
<P>
   The 25th annual Jerry Lewis muscular dystrophy telethon moved to
Los Angeles after 17 years in Las Vegas. The telethon raised $44.1
million. Lewis began the telethon in New York and moved to Las
Vegas in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Blues singer-guitarist B.B. King became the 1,917th star on the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And Clint Eastwood said he would make no more ''Dirty Harry''
films. He had made five.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: Vanessa Williams canceled a fall singing tour to
appear in ''Eraser,'' an Arnold Schwarzenegger movie.
</P>
<P>
   And John Lennon's marijuana pot was sold for $8,370 at an
auction in London. His kimono from a Beatles trip to Japan brought
$27,000.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: Lauryn Hill was the big winner at the MTV awards.
Her ''Doo Wop (That Thing)'' won four awards, including video of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken one year ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Eddie Fisher must have been in another world when he
wrote his book. Have you ever noticed that he is the only
ex-husband I don't talk about?'' -- Elizabeth Taylor, referring to
Fisher's tell-all book, ''Been There, Done That.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
