<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profit sharing proposed in merger unlikely  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) - If Connecticut Light &AMP; Power makes
bigger profits after the proposed merger with Consolidated Edison,
the company promises in its merger application to share some of the
wealth with shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But CL&AMP;P's parent company, Northeast Utilities, acknowledges in
paperwork before state regulators that such increased profits are
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   NU chief executive Michael Morris told the Waterbury
Republican-American the profit-sharing proposal may never come into
play. But he said the profit-sharing offer is a risk the utilities
are willing to take to make the merger better for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan ''may or may not materialize, but we need to work hard
on that to make sure we deliver as much as we can to our
customers,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the deal for regulators, the company also has pledged
to freeze rates until the end of 2005 - two years longer than
mandated by law - and write off $50 million in old debts.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who has been vocal in his
opposition to the merger, claims the profit-sharing proposal and
other offerings for consumers will make little difference.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Utility Control is poring over reams of
paperwork on the proposed merger, which would create the largest
electric and gas distribution company in the country. The agency is
scheduled to issue a draft decision on the merger Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Under the profit-sharing proposal, CL&AMP;P would share 40 percent
of the profits it takes in over a certain amount of profits after
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Under state regulations, CL&AMP;P can only earn up to a 10.3 percent
profit off its net revenues. NU has proposed sharing any profits
above 12.3 percent of net revenues after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said this profit-sharing proposal was made to
address concerns that CL&AMP;P may see a sudden windfall after the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   But in Aug. 11 filings with the DPUC, company officials say ''it
is unlikely that CL&AMP;P will experience earnings higher than 10.3
percent as projected in its budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit the companies have proposed for consumers is a
$50 million reduction in the amount of stranded costs consumers
will have to pay under the state's deregulation law.
</P>
<P>
   Stranded costs include old utility debts from building power
plants under state regulations that would not otherwise get paid
off under deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said the offer is so small as to be insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Think of it as a $100,000 mortgage: If you reduce that by
$5,000, you'd pay it off a few years earlier, but you would
continue to pay it virtually unchanged until that date. The
question is, how many consumers care about reducing the stranded
costs by a few years sometime so far in the future?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the offer amounts to real savings for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they say it's not really a $50 million guarantee to
customers, it's an artistic way of twisting around something that's
real,'' Morris said. ''That is a real $50 million that consumers
wouldn't be able to save without this merger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1506 </TRAILER>
