<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A cautionary state report about dormitory fire safety  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Within a report on fire safety at college
dormitories in New York are some findings that you don't need a
baccalaureate degree to recognize as troubling.
</P>
<P>
   FACT: There are more than 1,000 buildings used as residences at
public and private colleges in New York which do not have either a
complete smoke detection-alarm system or a full sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   FACT: Only 15 percent of the college dormitories in New York
have full sprinkler systems.
</P>
<P>
   FACT: Campuses reported an average of more than 300 fires in New
York college dormitories per year over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The task force which compiled these numbers was appointed by
Gov. George Pataki in response to a dorm fire in another state. In
January, three students at Seton Hall University in New Jersey died
and 58 others were injured in a blaze.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey responded to the tragedy in July when Gov. Christie
Whitman signed into law a bill requiring all colleges in that state
to install dormitory sprinkler systems within four years. The
legislation made a $93 million loan pool available to help colleges
pay for the fire safety improvements.
</P>
<P>
   As the New York task force pointed out, New Jersey's program
will provide water sprinklers for 9.5 million square feet of
college dorm space. The task force figured that New York's private
and public colleges have about 37 million square feet of
unsprinklered dormitory footage, all of it built before tougher
building codes went into effect in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The task force did not recommend that the state adopt a
hard-and-fast deadline like New Jersey's on the ''retrofitting'' of
existing dorm buildings with sprinklers. But it did say that,
eventually, the safest course will be to outfit all residence
buildings with sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will this process be expensive - the task force never
does venture a cost estimate - but it will also be disruptive to
the campuses where the work is being carried out, the panel
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the task force recommended taking a range of
measures to enhance fire safety, such as stepping up fire
inspections of dorms, better educating students about fire dangers
and more severely punishing students who disable fire alarms or set
off false alarms.
</P>
<P>
   But the state would only be marking time with steps short of
mandating proper fire alarm and sprinklers, said the chairman of
the state Assembly's higher education committee, Manhattan Democrat
Edward Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eventually, and I think as soon as possible, we are going to
have to have all dormitories sprinklered,'' Sullivan said. ''There
is no point fiddling with it.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is not alone in moving toward getting sprinklers in
more dormitory buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, sprinklers and more advanced fire-alarm systems
were installed in public universities as part of a statewide effort
to make the dorms safer following a 1998 fire at Murray State
University which killed one student.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, officials said dozens of dormitories on state
university campuses still lack sprinkler systems despite a 1996
fraternity house fire that killed five students at the University
of North Carolina's Chapel Hill campus.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts and Pennsylvania officials each announced plans
this year to install sprinklers in dormitories on public college
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, the discussion about mandated sprinklers barely
got going in 2000. Pataki has promised to build a legislative dorm
fire safety agenda in 2001 around the task force's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proposals will attract little or no opposition. But
when hundreds of millions of dollars are involved - as they would
be with a sprinkler mandate - fierce political battling can be
expected.
</P>
<P>
   If taxpayers pick up the tab for sprinklers throughout the State
University of New York system, the question will undoubtedly arise
whether it is then fair to make private colleges or the students
who attend them pay for the same improvements. Democrats in the
Assembly seem to be receptive to providing special state aid to the
state's private colleges to make the sprinkler upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   And Sullivan said the situation could get even more complicated
and expensive should the state extend the sprinkler requirements to
the off-campus housing so many college students call home during
their academic careers.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
