<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 96; Nasdaq Gains 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of brokerage companies surged Wednesday
following news that Credit Suisse had agreed to buy Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, but the overall market was mixed in lackluster
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was off 95.82 at 11,119.28 in
late afternoon trading. The Nasdaq composite index was up 4.15 at
4,086.32, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 7.09 at
1,502.75.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in market where a lot of people are already leaving for
the long weekend,'' said Al Goldman, chief investment strategist at
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. ''Business is thin and nobody
wants to take a big stance. There's just a lot of boredom on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages and financial services stocks gained after Credit
Suisse Group said it was buying DLJ for $11.5 billion, sending DLJ
shares up $4.56 to $88.56 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in other financial companies rose on anticipation of
further consolidation in the brokerage industry, including J.P.
Morgan, up $3.94 at $152.94. Shares of Lehman Brothers rose
initially but were down 6.2 cents at $140.44 by 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, off $2.75 at $130.13, was leading some computer shares
lower in profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the Nasdaq, Amazon.com rose $3.31to $42.94 following
some bullish comments from a Goldman Sachs analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a narrow margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 555.91 million
shares, up from Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.56 at 530.19.
</P>
<P>
