<HEADLINE> S. Africa Theft Suspect Assaulted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUIS TRICHARDT, South Africa (AP) -- A 14-year-old girl
suspected of shoplifting underwear was painted white by a security
guard, police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who is black, had picked some underwear and brought it
to the shop's counter Tuesday afternoon when the clerk accused her
of trying to steal the goods, worth about 40 cents, police said.
The clerk, who is black, called the store's white manager, who in
turn called the black security guard.
</P>
<P>
   The three brought the girl to a back room, where the manager
ordered the security guard to paint the girl with white paint,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her blouse was taken off and her stomach, chest, back, neck,
arms and head were painted white,'' Northern Province police
spokesman Phuti Setati told the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   The three store employees -- manager Thelma Strydom, clerk Julia
Munyai and security guard Albert Mbedzi -- then allegedly took $18
from the girl before she was allowed to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to describe the incident as racist. All three
store employees were charged with theft. Strydom also was charged
with assault, while Mbedzi faces indecent assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   The managing director of Pep Stores, the franchise to which the
store belongs, offered an apology Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If these allegations are proved to be true, we want to
apologize sincerely to the girl and her parents for what has
happened, whatever the provocation,'' Andri Labuschaigne said.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Trichardt is located 250 miles northeast of Johannesburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
