<HEADLINE> Death Concerns War Crimes Tribunal  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Prosecutors at the Yugoslav
tribunal voiced concern Wednesday that the apparent murder of a
potential witness would have a chilling effect on people
considering testifying against war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Milan Levar, a former Croat soldier who provided evidence on
comrades suspected of murdering Serbs, was killed Monday in an
explosion outside his home in Gospic, Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will no doubt have an impact on other witnesses,'' said
Deputy Prosecutor Graham Blewitt. He said the U.N. tribunal ''will
continue to do everything possible to provide adequate protection
for all of our witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt confirmed that Levar was interviewed ''during 1997 and
1998 in relation to investigations being conducted by the
tribunal,'' formally known as the International Criminal Tribunal
for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   No indictment has so far been served as a result of Levar's
evidence, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted the Croat had rejected the tribunal's offer of
protection, choosing instead to give details of his allegations to
Croatian media.
</P>
<P>
   ''He obviously took the view a couple of years ago that his best
protection was by going public,'' the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Levar claimed that military leaders Tihomir Oreskovic and Mirko
Norac were responsible for a murderous campaign against Croatia's
Serbian minority, and some Croats, during Croatia's war of
independence against Serb-dominated Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Levar's allegations shocked many Croats, who generally view
themselves as victims of Serb aggression.
</P>
<P>
   A Croatian investigative judge told state-run television on
Tuesday that ''Levar died a violent death.'' And a leading Croatian
human rights organization criticized both the tribunal and the
Zagreb government for failing to provide Levar with proper
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt also said Wednesday that chief war crimes prosecutor
Carla Del Ponte will tour countries surrounding Bosnia and Serbia
this fall in an attempt to tighten the screws on indicted suspects.
</P>
<P>
   He said the campaign is partly aimed at turning up the heat on
the U.N. tribunal's most-wanted men -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's being done to reinforce in President Milosevic's mind and
in Karadic's -- in fact in the minds of all fugitives -- that they
really are prisoners within their own borders,'' Blewitt told a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her campaign, Del Ponte will visit Bulgaria and
Romania in September, and Greece and Cyprus later this year,
Blewitt said. She recently visited Macedonia, Slovenia, Hungary and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt said several countries have already agreed to implement
measures to help capture suspects wanted by the tribunal. He
declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been indicted for war crimes against Kosovar
Albanians which provoked NATO's 78-day air campaign against Serbia
last year. Karadzic and his military chief Ratko Mladic are wanted
for genocide in the 1992-95 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Even if NATO peacekeepers stationed in the Balkans fail to
arrest the Serb leaders, prosecutors want their international
isolation to continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1627 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spraying scheduled for Nassau, lower Manhattan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A 52-year-old Staten Island man has tested
positive for the West Nile virus, the sixth human case of the
potentially deadly disease this year, city officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was not identified, is at home recovering, said
city health commissioner Neal Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the other people infected with West Nile have recovered,
while an 87-year-old Brooklyn woman remains hospitalized in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, state agriculture commissioner Nathan Rudgers
said that a horse on Staten Island had been euthanized Aug. 20
after it contracted the virus, and the city announced that two more
birds in Queens had also tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   Pesticide spraying is scheduled for the next three nights in
portions of Manhattan, Queens and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County also ordered its first mosquito spraying of the
year for Bethpage, Farmingdale, Massapequa and Massapequa Park,
using the pesticide Scourge. County health officials said infected
mosquitoes were found in two pools of water in Bethpage State Park
and north of the Sunrise Mall in Massapequa. Spraying will take
place Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials had earlier called spraying unnecessary because no
Nassau county mosquitoes had tested positive for the virus. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani criticized the decision, saying failure to act
could be harmful to public health.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people in the metro area, including one from Nassau
County, died from virus-related symptoms in 1999 and scores more
were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Long Island environmental group said an unusual
die-off of a large number of blue claw crabs may be tied to last
year's spraying program in Great South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Smith, a spokesman for Fish Unlimited, said area fishermen
have been taking a count of the crabs and collecting samples for
testing by an independent laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   He says an unusual die-off of lobsters occurred in Long Island
Sound a year after pesticide spraying in north shore areas.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County has been spraying the pesticides Resmethrin and
Sumethrin, both deadly to marine life, Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
