<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents upset about sex offender housing in school neighborhood  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - Parents and city leaders are upset that
the state is housing two convicted sex offenders in the
neighborhood of a Roman Catholic elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services said
Wednesday it is reviewing the housing arrangements for the two men
following complaints about their proximity to St. Joseph's School.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make sure the interests of both the clients and
community are met,'' said agency spokesman Dr. Wayne Dailey.
</P>
<P>
   The men, Cale R. Campbell, 19, and Christopher A. Czyzewski, 20,
wear electronic monitors on their ankles and have 24-hour
supervision, but some parents believe they pose a threat to
students and the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's too close to home,'' said Cindy Terry, whose two
children attend St. Joseph School. ''It's definitely too close to
the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Some city leaders also say they will fight to move the men away
from the school.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an absolutely a horrendous place to put such a
facility,'' City Councilor Reid Burdick said.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are in compliance with the terms of their probation and
with Megan's Law, which requires convicted sex offenders to
register their whereabouts with state police, said Ginny Apple, a
spokeswoman for the state Judicial Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was convicted in March 1999 of third-degree sexual
assault and risk of injury to a minor. His probation expires in
March 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Czyzewski was convicted in September 1998 of indecent assault
and battery. His probation expires in August 2001.
</P>
<P>
   They are in the Young Adult Services program, which helps
clients over age 18 make the transition between the Department of
Children and Families and the Department of Mental Health and
Addiction Services.
</P>
<P>
   The state probation office reviews housing for the people it
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coyne, the chief probation officer for New London, would
not comment on the cases because of confidentiality rules. But he
said his office carefully reviews housing options and an offender's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not all sex offenders are the same. We will assess each
offender and see how they accessed their victims and their history,
and if they do pose a risk to a particular location, such as a
school,'' Coyne said.
</P>
<P>
   No homeless shelters in southeastern Connecticut accept single
young men, and there are few places to put offenders where they
would not be near some youths, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The primary importance to us is that offenders receive any
support they can from us, and that offenders not live in the
community homeless, with no means of support and no one to
supervise them,'' Coyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Cote, principal of St. Joseph's School, said Tuesday
she is waiting to hear more and does not want to alarm the school
community.
</P>
<P>
   ''As any school parent or teacher would be, I'm somewhat worried
about the issue,'' Cote said. ''I believe it poses a danger to our
students - if not a physical danger, then an emotional one when
parents understand what's going on in our neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
