<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seagram CEO testifies he thinks MP3.com purposefully violated copyrights </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Seagram Chief Executive Officer Edgar Bronfman
Jr. testified Wednesday that he believes MP3.com purposefully
violated the copyrights of record companies to build an online
catalogue of 80,000 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman's testimony in a civil trial in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan was brief because Judge Jed Rakoff decided that the
executive's opinions were not relevant to deciding whether MP3.com
intentionally infringed on copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   Before the reluctant witness finished his testimony, he said he
doubted MP3.com ''accidentally bought 80,000 CDs'' to load into a
service that allows customers to access favorite music from
anywhere once they prove they own the CD.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, I do believe it was a willful disregard of the law,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Music Group and Interscope Records, the music arms of
Seagram, are the last plaintiffs in a lawsuit brought by the
recording industry against the San Diego-based fledging Internet
music company.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent fiscal quarter, MP3.com set aside $150
million for legal costs, including the price of settlements with
four other major music makers - Warner Music Group, BMG, EMI and
Sony Music Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com had hoped to settle with Seagram prior to the trial but
believed it was unable to do so because Seagram wanted to compete
in the Internet music space itself, the judge said as he stopped
the questioning of Bronfman.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told courtroom spectators that lawyers for MP3.com had
revealed earlier during a private conversation that they were
questioning Bronfman to expose Seagram's ''competitive motives for
pursuing this lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to the court that that is completely irrelevant to
any issue before the court,'' the judge said. ''No one is obliged
to settle a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff said it was common that money and competitive motives are
at the root of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Bronfman's testimony would be irrelevant to whether
he decides MP3.com purposefully violated the copyrights or whether
stiff penalties must be imposed to warn others against violating
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge rules against the company, MP3.com could face
penalties of up to $150,000 for each of an estimated 5,000 Seagram
CDs it put in its online music collection. Such a penalty could
approach three quarters of a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he dismissed Bronfman because the continued
questioning of him would be ''not only a colossal waste of time but
also a misuse of a court proceeding for the airing of hard feelings
that understandably exist between the defendants and the remaining
plaintiffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he feared the trial otherwise could turn into ''a
publicity circus and we are not about to have that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
