<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sixth victim of West Nile found, spraying scheduled for Nassau, three city boroughs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A 52-year-old Staten Island man has tested
positive for the West Nile virus, the sixth human case of the
potentially deadly disease this year, city officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was not identified, is at home recovering, said
city health commissioner Neal Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the other people infected with West Nile have recovered,
while an 87-year-old Brooklyn woman remains hospitalized in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, state agriculture commissioner Nathan Rudgers
said that a horse on Staten Island had been euthanized Aug. 20
after it contracted the virus, and the city announced that two more
birds in Queens had also tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   Pesticide spraying is scheduled for the next three nights in
portions of Manhattan, Queens and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County also ordered its first mosquito spraying of the
year for Bethpage, Farmingdale, Massapequa and Massapequa Park,
using the pesticide Scourge. County health officials said infected
mosquitoes were found in two pools of water in Bethpage State Park
and north of the Sunrise Mall in Massapequa. Spraying will take
place Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials had earlier called spraying unnecessary because no
Nassau county mosquitoes had tested positive for the virus. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani criticized the decision, saying failure to act
could be harmful to public health.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people in the metro area, including one from Nassau
County, died from virus-related symptoms in 1999 and scores more
were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Long Island environmental group said an unusual
die-off of a large number of blue claw crabs may be tied to last
year's spraying program in Great South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Smith, a spokesman for Fish Unlimited, said area fishermen
have been taking a count of the crabs and collecting samples for
testing by an independent laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   He says an unusual die-off of lobsters occurred in Long Island
Sound a year after pesticide spraying in north shore areas.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County has been spraying the pesticides Resmethrin and
Sumethrin, both deadly to marine life, Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
