<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venice Festival Honors Eastwood  </HEADLINE>
By CANDICE HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy (AP) -- When Clint Eastwood came to Italy to make
the ''spaghetti'' Western that would catapult him to stardom, he
was so unknown that director Sergio Leone didn't bother to meet him
at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   That was 36 years ago. On Wednesday, the 70-year-old actor and
director was honored with a Golden Lion for lifetime achievement at
the Venice Film Festival's gala opening.
</P>
<P>
   The award was accompanied by the European premiere of ''Space
Cowboys,'' a movie about four old geezers who still have the
''right stuff,'' and a documentary tribute to Eastwood.
</P>
<P>
   It was a triumphal return by any standard and Eastwood seemed to
be savoring every moment. At a news conference with his fellow
''cowboys''-- Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland and James Garner --
Eastwood said making movies keeps him young.
</P>
<P>
   ''Acting is like being a child,'' he said. ''It's great fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Famously laconic on film, Eastwood is easy and articulate in
real life. Asked if the award had made him reflect on his legacy,
Eastwood said he didn't feel he was close enough to the end of a
career to have one.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always felt I was in the middle of it, not the end,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, reflect on the irony of a Hollywood actor
getting his first break abroad. The movie was ''A Fistful of
Dollars,'' the first of three ''spaghetti'' Westerns that Leone
directed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a little bit strange,'' Eastwood admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was made on such a shoestring budget that Eastwood
even recycled his old costume from the TV series ''Rawhide.'' But
''A Fistful of Dollars'' led to a fistful of hits. Eastwood became
a Hollywood star with enough clout to realize his true desire,
directing. His 1992 Western ''Unforgiven'' won four Oscars,
including best movie and best director. There were flops along the
way as well, but Eastwood has persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Space Cowboys'' is a hit in the United States. It doesn't
pretend to be great art, but it's full of charm and funny jokes
about old guys. Eastwood and his co-stars all said they had a huge
amount of fun making it.
</P>
<P>
   The gala opening of the festival was the big night for Hollywood
in Venice. The next nine days will be devoted to a potpourri of
more than 150 movies from around the globe, including 20 in
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the competitors -- a dozen -- are from Europe, although
one of America's most stalwart independent filmmakers, Robert
Altman, is in the race with ''Dr. T and the Women,'' a comedy
starring Richard Gere as a gynecologist trying to juggle the women
in his life. The other U.S. entry is Julian Schabel's ''Before
Night Falls,'' starring Johnny Depp.
</P>
<P>
   The French presence is heavy this year, perhaps a sign that the
French film industry is serious about challenging Hollywood's
global domination. Two French films and six French co-productions
are in competition.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which was snubbed by the Cannes Film Festival, is also
amply represented this year on the Lido. Four Italian films were
chosen for the competition, some say in reaction to the Cannes
snub.
</P>
<P>
   Also competing are films from Portugal, Britain, China, South
Korea, Australia, Iran, India and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The Venice Film Festival, the world's oldest, fancies itself
more artistic than the glitz-packed Cannes. Winning a Golden Lion
in Venice rarely brings commercial success, but it can endow a
filmmaker with considerable prestige.
</P>
<P>
   The festival also can serve as a good launching pad for movies,
like last year's ''Being John Malkovich,'' which won favor with
audiences and critics here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1646 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firefighters, family mourn man killed in shooting spree  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) - Connecticut native Dennis Page traveled
eight hours from Virginia on Wednesday to join hundreds of fellow
firefighters paying last respects to Jaime Quinones, a Waterbury
firefighter killed in a weekend shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know anyone here. It's just a big brotherhood,'' said
Page, who grew up in Killingly, graduated from the University of
Connecticut and now works as a firefighter and paramedic in
Henrico, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black bands across their badges, the firefighters lined
the street outside the Immaculate Conception Church as Engine 10
carried the coffin of Quinones, 38, beneath crossed aerial ladders.
An American flag was suspended from the ladders.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of others - including residents who said they knew
Quinones - looked on as a police motorcade led the procession. The
Connecticut Fire Fighters Pipe Band escorted the engine, which had
its lights draped in black cloth. Color guards stood outside the
church as members of the city department lined the central steps.
</P>
<P>
   Quinones' family asked the Rev. John Blackall, pastor of another
city church, to celebrate the funeral Mass. Blackall had baptized
Quinones, a Waterbury native.
</P>
<P>
   ''The death of a fireman on duty is always an occasion for
showing the meaning of bonding,'' Blackall said. ''This bonding is
a particularly beautiful witness to the lives of firefighters.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting Fire Chief James Trainor praised Quinones for his 11
years as a Marine and 6 years on the city department.
</P>
<P>
   ''He served to protect our freedom to live in this country and
he served to protect our lives and homes,'' Trainor said of the man
he affectionately called ''Q.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the mourners were representatives of the Worcester, Mass.,
fire department, which lost six of its own members fighting a
warehouse fire in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a brother in the service, and when we lose a brother we
send him off fittingly,'' said Worcester Lt. Ed Ryan. ''This man,
though I've never met him, is our brother.''
</P>
<P>
   No estimate was available on the number of firefighters at the
funeral Mass, which was followed by a procession en route to a
burial service at Calvary Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Quinones was collecting money from motorists for the Muscular
Dystrophy Association ''Fill the Boot'' campaign Saturday when he
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The rampage that began when Mark Cote, 29, got into an argument
with his neighbor, Brian Miller, remains under investigation. Cote
shot Miller, 30, twice and then stole his car.
</P>
<P>
   Cote then drove to the intersection where Quinones was killed.
Police said Cote fired at least eight shots at Quinones, then
traveled to the home of an ex-girlfriend and shot her mother,
40-year-old Maria Hernandez. Police said Cote let the ex-girlfriend
and her three children go before turning the gun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   During the Mass, Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano asked for a
moment of silence for the other victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1653 </TRAILER>
