<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Heat a Worry For Wine Growers  </HEADLINE>
By GIOVANNA DELL'ORTO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy's grape pickers are working 12- to 15-hour
days to complete the earliest wine harvest in memory, hurried along
by torrid summer heat that threatens to turn the crop to raisins on
the vine.
</P>
<P>
   July rains followed by two weeks in the high 90s could make for
a great year of high-alcohol, full-bodied wine -- or grapes of wrath
if the harvest isn't in soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to pick the bunches that aren't too sunburned,''
harvester Barbara Chiarolanza said Wednesday on a day of picking
that started at 8 a.m. in Tuscany's Col D'Orcia vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're managing to save a lot of them. But all the vineyards
are in the sun, so we pray that from time to time we get a cloud,''
Chiarolanza said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing hats and long pants to protect against cuts, she and the
rest of her 50-member crew are selecting, cutting, and filling
33-pound crates with the Sangiovese grapes that make what many
consider Italy's finest red wine, Brunello di Montalcino.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what's hotter -- the sun or the ground,'' the
27-year-old Chiarolanza exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   For the vineyard's wine expert, it's an unprecedented -- and
unsettling -- experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been working in this territory for 20 years and
certainly this is the earliest harvest,'' Col D'Orcia oenologist
Pablo Harri said. ''Brunello in August just doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Tuscan hilltop town of Montalcino down south to the
island of Sicily, Italy's wine growers are rushing harvesters to
scorched fields.
</P>
<P>
   ''The heat is dehydrating rather than maturing the grapes now,
so it's harvest time for everybody,'' said Giuseppe Genna with
Sicily's regional wine and vine institute in Marsala.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we can't keep harvesters working around the clock ...
Otherwise we get them withered too,'' said Enrico Viglierchio of
the Banfi winery at Montalcino, which produces Brunello along with
Merlot, Sauvignon, Chardonnay and Pinot Grigio.
</P>
<P>
   This year's harvest will end around the middle to the end of
September, its usual starting date.
</P>
<P>
   The heat and accelerated ripening mean red grapes will have a
higher sugar -- and thus alcohol -- concentration, while white grapes
risk losing a bit of their aroma.
</P>
<P>
   ''August's sun has burned the product a bit,'' said Ezio
Rivella, an internationally known wine expert. ''Quantitatively,
the harvest is meager. Qualitatively, it's good, if not great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Col D'Orcia's Harri said the Sangiovese grapes in his
vineyard appear worth the rush -- ''exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern Italian vineyards also are gearing up for an early
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   There, the harvest is expected to be good unless vineyards get
too much rain, said Beppe Veglio, an oenologist with a large wine
cooperative in the northern region of Piedmont. Piedmont produces
Barolo, which vies with Brunello as one of Italy's finest red
wines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 1653 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0106 </DOCNO>
