<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramapo College delays opening by a week due to water contamination  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAHWAH, N.J. (AP) - Ramapo College of New Jersey will delay the
start of its fall semester after bacteria were discovered in the
school's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The college will pump large doses of chlorine through its pipes
and is advising people not to drink water from the system until the
problem is cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   Classes originally scheduled to begin on Sept. 6 will instead
begin Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination was discovered after tests were conducted as
part of the school's application for a certificate of occupancy in
the newly constructed Maple Hall.
</P>
<P>
   After the chlorination is finished, new tests will be done to
ensure the bacteria are gone.
</P>
<P>
   College spokeswoman Bonnie Franklin said Mahwah officials told
the school such contamination often occurs with new construction.
The college gets its water from Mahwah's municipal water system,
which draws it from wells, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the college and municipal officials don't know how the
coliform bacteria got into the pipes, but said the contamination
could have occurred while pipes were exposed outdoors before being
installed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may never know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the college said, drinking fountains have been
turned off and bottled water is being provided. The Mahwah Health
Department has determined the water is safe to use for all
nondrinking purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman orientation and move-in is now scheduled for Sept. 9,
and upperclassmen are to move in the following day.
</P>
</TEXT>
