<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Readies Clinton Security  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombian troops and police mounted
one of their biggest security operations ever for President
Clinton's visit Wednesday, posting snipers on rooftops and along
the stone wall around this colonial city.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton coming to cement a $1.3 billion U.S. aid package to
fight drug trafficking and rebels who protect drug crops, Colombian
security forces were prepared for any attack.
</P>
<P>
   Two Colombian warships patrolled the azure Caribbean waters off
Cartagena, and police helicopters buzzed the city. Military divers
clad in wetsuits searched Cartagena's bay and port for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   On highways approaching the city, soldiers had days earlier
erected roadblocks and frisked motorists and bus passengers for
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the precautions, police dismantled in a Cartagena
neighborhood what they described as a small homemade explosive
device meant to scatter rebel leaflets denouncing Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Troops were on edge, ready to respond to any threat.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, a half-dozen Colombian marines posted at the city's
clock tower went onto the alert when someone heard an electronic
beeping sound from under a wooden cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that it might be a bomb, the soldiers anxiously peered
under the cabinet. They saw that the beeping was coming from a
cheap wristwatch whose alarm had gone off.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5,000 Colombian police and soldiers participated in the
operation to protect Clinton, the military said. They were
augmented by hundreds of U.S. personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But the Colombians took pains not to make this city, declared a
World Heritage Site by UNESCO and which was first settled in 1533,
not to appear like an armed camp.
</P>
<P>
   Many security members wore civilian clothes and mixed in with
the crowds who greeted Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of security, but we're not drawing attention to
ourselves,'' said Colombian marine corporal Carlos Martinez, one of
the troops stationed at the clock tower. ''Our objective is to be
unseen.''
</P>
<P>
   Above him, barely visible, was a sniper peering through his
scope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
