<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Labor Department orders Pepsi to pay overtime and release records </HEADLINE>
By LORI HINNANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Department of Labor has ordered
Pepsi Bottling Group to pay overtime and interest to 13 workers and
to turn over wage records for other employees at its four New
Jersey facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, released Wednesday, followed five years of
litigation and will affect more than 300 Pepsi employees in New
Jersey, according to James L. Linsey, an attorney at the law firm
Cohen, Weiss and Simon, which represented the employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Somers, N.Y., company plans to appeal, according to
spokesperson Kelly McAndrew.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that the commissioner of labor has erred in a
number of issues in this decision,'' McAndrew said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case, a group of 13 employees involved in shelving Pepsi
beverages and maintaining the stock at large grocery stores and
small delicatessens claimed they were due overtime wages for time
worked in addition to their regular 40-hour week.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi claimed the employees served as sales representatives and
were exempt from New Jersey wage laws.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Labor upheld a previous ruling by an
administrative law judge in deciding that the 13 employees in the
original case were not sales representatives and were entitled to
overtime pay and interest dating to 1993. It also ordered Pepsi to
begin paying all other such employees overtime.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Wednesday decision also demanded that the
company turn over wage records dating back to 1993 to determine if
other employees are eligible for past overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative law judge's decision did not require
interest, nor did it request wage records for other employees.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith, a spokesman for the state Department of Labor, said
the Wednesday decision affirms that the employees ''are hourly
workers and that they're covered under New Jersey's wage law.'' The
wage records, he said, will allow the department not only to see
which other employees might be affected by the decision, but also
''to see what the pattern is what the workers are doing and how
they're being paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Linsey said the number of other employees that could be affected
is more than 300 in New Jersey and added that the decision, which
he estimated could cost Pepsi as much as $20 million, has national
implications both for Pepsi and similar companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe their system for manufacture and distribution
in New Jersey is unique,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Linsey said he was not concerned about the possibility of an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each time Pepsi's appealed something,'' he said, ''it's gotten
worse for them, not better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1737 </TRAILER>
