<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury begins deliberating in officer shooting case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAYVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - Jurors on Wednesday began deliberating the
case of a Jamestown man accused of shooting and critically wounding
an undercover police officer last September.
</P>
<P>
   James Lewis Jr., 19, is charged with two counts of first-degree
attempted murder for allegedly shooting Police Officer David
Mitchell in the face and then shooting at his partner, Officer R.
Scott DePietro.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell lost an eye and some of his hearing in the shooting but
has since been promoted to detective in the Jamestown Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments Wednesday, defense attorney Ned Barone
told jurors there was no evidence to convict Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ballistics came back negative, the fingerprints came back
negative. There was no actual testing of the blood on any of the
objects,'' Barone said. ''There was no physical evidence,
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney James Subjack disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the gun, we have the clothing. We have a description
of the clothing. We have a description of him,'' he said. ''There's
plenty of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to attempted murder, Lewis is charged with one count
each of aggravated assault on a police officer, attempted
aggravated assault on a police officer and criminal use of a
firearm.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, he could face 50 years to life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
