<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compromise Sought in Burundi Talks  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYNE SAMBIRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- Four Tutsi political parties who
refused to sign a Burundi peace agreement without a cease-fire said
Wednesday they were ready to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi President Pierre Buyoya signed a power sharing accord
Monday, paving the way for ending a 7-year civil war, with
President Clinton, mediator Nelson Mandela and 12 African leaders
looking on in the Tanzanian city of Arusha. The Tutsi-led
government and army as well as Hutu and Tutsi political parties
also signed.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutu rebels and four out of 10 Tutsi parties refused to sign
the document, despite pressure from Mandela who promised to obtain
the cease-fire later.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not saying that we will not sign. But we have put
forward conditions and we're waiting,'' said Joseph Nzeyimana,
leader of the Raddes party. ''We are going to put a lot of pressure
on Mandela, just like he did on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela had criticized the four parties for refusing to sign the
agreement, which would create an ethnically balanced army,
government and parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya said the peace process was incomplete and warned he would
struggle on against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the rebels continue to refuse to negotiate, we will ask the
region, the international community and all the others to help us
fight the rebels until they realize they will not get anywhere with
violence and massacres,'' Buyoya told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II on Wednesday said Burundi had been ''bloodied
by seven absurd years of civil war,'' and implored the combatants
to commit to a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask you to pray so that the populace's desire for
reconciliation will come to be realized by all the interested
parties and the neighboring states, so that a lasting and stable
peace can be reached quickly,'' John Paul said at his summer
retreat at Castel Gandolfo. About two-thirds of Burundi's people
are Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the four balking Tutsi parties said they wanted
changes in the document to ensure that rights for the minority
Tutsis be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Tutsis dominate the army and economy of Hutu-majority Burundi.
Civil war broke out in 1993 upon the assassination of Burundi's
first and only democratically elected president, a Hutu. Fighting
since then has killed 200,000 people in the nation of roughly 6
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
