<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $adv04  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Xerox is going trendy.
</P>
<P>
   The business machine maker has just launched the most expensive
advertising campaign in its history featuring Blue Dog, the popular
pup with bright yellow eyes who has a cultlike following.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Blue Dog - the subject of popular paintings by New
Orleans artist George Rodrigue - is no accident for a manufacturer
often seen as a stodgy, Old Economy company.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of more than $200 million, Xerox hopes the ads will
spread the word that it makes high-tech inkjet printers for the
small and home office market for as little as $149.
</P>
<P>
   The company's outdated image - it is best known as a maker of
old-style, high priced copiers - is just one of the problems at
Xerox, once considered a symbol of corporate success.
</P>
<P>
   Its products were so popular in the 1960s and '70s that it
fought to ensure that ''Xerox'' did not become a generic verb for
photocopying.
</P>
<P>
   But profits are down sharply, a botched sales force
reorganization has alienated customers and its stock price has
plummeted to one-third of its value a year ago. The stock has
hovered around $16.50 a share, near its recent low of $14.56 and
far below its high of $50.12&AMP;frac12; a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the company announced it would slash 5,200 jobs and
close manufacturing plants to reduce its cost structure so it could
stay competitive with companies such as Hewlett-Packard, Canon and
Ricoh.
</P>
<P>
   And both the company and the Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission
are investigating accounting irregularities involving its Mexican
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The last year was not supposed to be a nightmare for Xerox. In
April 1999, the company made Rick Thoman its chief executive.
Thoman was a former IBM executive credited with helping to engineer
that company's turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman, who had joined Xerox in 1997, had already been
instrumental in the company's push to sell its digital products in
low-end retail outlets such as Staples and Office Max.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Xerox was already struggling to reduce costs as it
shifted from old-style copiers that operate with lenses and lights
to multipurpose digital models that can be upgraded to print, scan
and fax documents when connected to personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The company was also in the midst of cutting 9,000 jobs, or just
under 10 percent of its worldwide work force.
</P>
<P>
   But the sales force realignment was executed clumsily and slowed
productivity and sales. The idea was to reorganize the sales force
by industry, rather than the traditional geographic organization
used by Xerox for years.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman was fired in May, just 13 months after he took the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Allaire, who Thoman had replaced as CEO, agreed to come
back on a temporary basis. The company elevated Anne Mulcahy to
President and Chief Operating Officer and made it clear she was
being groomed for the CEO job.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Xerox had to report embarrassing problems in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company was initially vague about the problems, it
later disclosed that several senior managers had collaborated to
circumvent Xerox accounting policies. They allegedly created false
product orders to inflate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a $78 million charge against second-quarter
earnings to cover bad debt and unrecorded liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox fired several top Mexican executives, including the
general manager and finance director.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican charge, coupled with a revenue decline for certain
products, helped push second-quarter earnings down 68 percent to
$145 million, or 19 cents per share, compared with $448 million, or
62 cents per share in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In July, during a conference call with analysts, Xerox
executives were surprisingly candid about the extent of the
company's problems.	   Allaire warned analysts to lower their expectations for
the
second half of the year. And Mulcahy said things had gotten so bad
that, ''Xerox people have lost confidence in management.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a feeling the company has lost its sense of
direction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, she said, employees had grown increasingly frustrated
with the company's slow reaction to the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our issues kept us focused internally instead of on the market
and the competition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mulcahy said the reorganization of the sales force is now
complete and the turnover rate for salespeople has dropped. She
said the company hoped to keep its strongest producers through
pumped-up salaries and bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Both Allaire and Mulcahy declined requests for interviews for
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the company's internal problems are really just
symptoms of a larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cause of their problems really has to do with the fact
that they're caught between a rock and a hard place,'' said Shebly
Seyrafi, an analyst at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons. ''Their core market is
the copier market and that copier market is in decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is down in part because many workers prefer to use
printers linked to their computers rather than copying machines.
</P>
<P>
   In the digital copier market, Xerox has been No. 1 for two years
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the company had 37 percent of the market, followed by
Sharp, at 18 percent, and Canon, at 11 percent, according to
figures provided by IDC, formerly known as International Data
Corp., a market research and consulting company based in
Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But in the total copier market - analog and digital - Canon led
in 1999, with 31 percent, followed by Xerox, 29 percent, and Sharp,
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is in the small and home office market that Xerox really lags
behind its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the inkjet market of multifunction machines - those that can
copy, fax and print all from a computer - Hewlett-Packard is
crushing Xerox and other competitors. H-P had 52 percent of the
market in 1999, compared to only 8 percent for Xerox. Canon came in
second with 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox has tried to make inroads in the small and home office
market. In March, the company announced a $2 billion alliance with
Sharp and Fuji Xerox to develop and manufacture inkjet products for
small and home offices.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox has also formed a partnership with Dell Computers under
which that company will sell Xerox laser printers.
</P>
<P>
   The new Blue Dog advertising campaign is aimed at showing
customers that this one-time maker of old-style copiers now also
makes products for small and home offices.
</P>
<P>
   In new television commercials, brightly colored paintings of
various small businesses are featured in an art gallery, with the
Blue Dog prominent in each, while an announcer extolls the virtues
of a $149 Xerox printer. ''They're just a smarter breed of inkjet
printer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Always faithful to its owner,'' reads a print ad showing Blue
Dog watching over a printer.
</P>
<P>
   But will the new campaign work?
</P>
<P>
   ''The market sees them as this purveyor of antiquated or older
technology and the market has moved on. Copying was big in the
'60s; printing has been big for 10 years,'' said Seyrafi.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have praised the company's decision last year to
purchase the color printing division of Tektronix Inc., a move that
makes Xerox second only to Hewlett-Packard in the office color
printing market.
</P>
<P>
   But they say it may be a while before Xerox can pull out of its
recent slump.
</P>
<P>
   ''They may be coming out of it, but if they do they are going to
be coming out of their problems in the 2001 time frame, not anytime
this year,'' said Seyrafi.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kmetz, a director at IDC, said Xerox will be able to turn
things around, but not in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're too much of a major player and a dominant provider of
products to just crumble and die,'' Kmetz said. ''I would expect to
see Xerox rally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1745 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notorious art dealer faces more than seven years in prison  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A notorious art dealer convicted of threatening
to kidnap a lawyer's 4-year-old daughter was sentenced to seven
years and one month in prison Wednesday after apologizing to his
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Crispo, 55, told U.S. District Judge Alvin K.
Hellerstein, ''I deserve my punishment and I am ready to accept
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crispo, a prominent art and antiques dealer, was convicted by a
jury of attempted extortion and obstruction of justice after he
threatened to kidnap the 4-year-old child of an attorney, Sandy
Mayerson, who worked on his bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Hellerstein ordered the prison term and required Crispo to pay
$45,000 in restitution to the mother of the child he threatened and
another $45,000 in fines. After the sentencing, Mayerson declined
to comment to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I accept full responsibility for my actions and have no ill
will for the victims of this matter,'' Crispo told Hellerstein.
''My character's been bared before this court, both good and bad,
and I am ready to accept my fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellerstein urged Crispo to mend himself in prison so that he
can return to his profession and contribute to society.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a life after prison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He imposed a sentenced harsher than what federal sentencing
guidelines would normally require because of what he called the
''extreme psychological injury'' he caused on his victims.
</P>
<P>
   Crispo's latest legal troubles arose after he filed for
bankruptcy in May 1996 and a trustee was appointed to overlook his
estate, which included several businesses, a Manhattan penthouse
and a multimillion-dollar Charleston, S.C., mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged Crispo made numerous threats to Mayerson,
who worked for a law firm that was helping administer his estate.
</P>
<P>
   The threats grew especially serious on May 21, 1999 when Crispo
became angry that a check was not ready for him, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   He then told a paralegal that he would kidnap Mayerson's
4-year-old daughter, saying he knew what park she played in and
that he had photographs of her, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, investigators found a book in Crispo's
apartment entitled, ''Missing, Stranger Abduction, Smart Strategies
to Keep your Child Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat to kidnap the child was taken seriously because of
Crispo's prior threats and because he was believed to have arranged
to have the girl photographed as she played in Central Park two
years earlier, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Crispo grew up in a Philadelphia orphanage before gaining
prominence in his career and then attracting notoriety in the 1980s
when he was implicated but never charged in a Rockland County
murder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, one of Crispo's employees was convicted in the killing
of a Norwegian fashion student whose body had been found in
Rockland County wearing only a mask used in sadomasochistic
rituals. He was partially burned with two bullet holes in the back
of his head.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant accused Crispo of ordering the killing at the end
of a sexual encounter. Crispo was never charged and he was
acquitted in 1988 of charges of torturing another man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
