<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate president wants increases in prescription drug plan  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey Senate President Donald T.
DiFrancesco wants more seniors and disabled residents getting
state-funded discount prescription drug programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican lawmaker announced his $60 million prescription
plan at a news conference Wednesday in Newark, a day after he said
patients should have the right to sue HMO companies for medical
malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, DiFrancesco, who is considering a run for governor
next year, announced a $400 million property tax rebate program.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription plan would give coverage to seniors and
handicapped residents who can't get existing state programs,
DiFrancesco, R-Union, said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is designed to provide a safety net for middle-class
seniors and the disabled who are truly falling between the cracks
of prescription coverage,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's share of the national tobacco settlement will cover
the tab, DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ''Senior Gold'', the program would cover approximately
100,000 residents 65 or older or those receiving Social Security
benefits. Single people earning up to $28,588 and couples with an
income of up to $32,791 would qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Prescriptions would be filled at any pharmacy. Each prescription
would costs users a $15 co-payment plus 50 percent of the drug's
cost. Those with more than $3,000 in expenses a year would have all
of their drug costs covered with just the co-payment.
</P>
<P>
   The program's cost is the largest single price tag in the
package of bills DiFrancesco proposed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   All the other proposals would cost state taxpayers roughly $60
million if they became law.
</P>
<P>
   The largest items include funding for hospital charity care
programs that would increase by $30 million. Medicaid
reimbursements to physicians would jump by $7 million. Another $4
million would go to establish emergency room clinics in urban
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco also called for changes in state law that he said
would benefit health care consumers. Those included the ability to
sue HMO insurance carriers, require arbitration and mandate
financial accountability
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman offered similar proposals Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said DiFrancesco's suggestions ''dovetail nicely'' with
her legislative proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''What he did today and what he outlined today means that we
share the focus on these issues and that means we stand a very good
chance of getting these things through,'' Whitman said at an
appearance in Mount Laurel.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for DiFrancesco said the prescription program
would be funded annually through the tobacco settlement payment.
</P>
<P>
   ''This gives us a solid program for at least the next two
decades,'' spokeswoman Rae Hutton said. The remainder of the
programs would be funded by state budget surpluses, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
