<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ and Pentagon promise cheaper, quicker base cleanups  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - New Jersey environmental officials and U.S.
military officials promise quicker, cheaper cleanups of
contaminated land at bases throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   State Environmental Commissioner Robert Shinn Jr. and
representatives of the Army, Air Force, Navy and Defense Logistics
Agency signed an agreement Wednesday that will allow the Pentagon
to address cleanups at more than 500 sites as a package rather than
one installation at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agreement is important because it's going to help us
clean up military sites in New Jersey faster, better and cheaper,''
said Sherri W. Goodman, deputy under secretary of defense for
environmental security.
</P>
<P>
   It means, she said, ''cutting red tape.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department oversees and pays for the cleanup
projects, with the state acting as regulator.
</P>
<P>
   Through its Environmental Restoration Program, the Department of
Defense is responsible for cleaning up more than 27,000 sites at
over 8,500 military installations and properties, including active,
closing, and realigning bases and formerly used defense sites.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has 567 contaminated sites at 29 military
installations, some of which have been partially or fully shuttered
in past rounds of base closings. Seventy-five additional
contaminated sites are on ''formerly used defense sites'' that the
military no longer owns, but is responsible to clean.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely contaminated installation appears to be
Picatinny Arsenal in Morris County, home to 175 of the state's 567
contaminated sites.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise, Shinn said, since use of Picatinny by the
military traces back to the Civil War. Back then, he said, disposal
strategy was little more than ''find a site and bury it.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimated cost to clean up all the New Jersey sites is $370
million. Goodman said the agreement could save $50 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive individual project in New Jersey, according
to the Pentagon, is a $19.8 million cleanup at a formerly used
defense site in Cape May. Next, at $17.2 million, is a cleanup
project at Fort Dix.
</P>
<P>
   Not covered by the agreement are the most seriously contaminated
properties that are already part of the federal ''Superfund''
program.
</P>
<P>
   Properties that fall under the agreement include the Bomarc
missile site near McGuire Air Force Base, where the soil was
tainted 40 years ago when plutonium spilled from a nuclear warhead,
and the Warren Grove Bombing Range in Burlington County, where
dummy warheads dropped for target practice must be collected and
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, cleanups will no longer be handled on a
case-by-case basis, with base commanders forwarding a request
through several layers of bureaucracy. Different branches of the
military will work cooperatively if each has a cleanup project at a
given base.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good for us because we're going to do a lot more cleanups
a lot more rapidly,'' Shinn said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is similar to one struck in 1997 between the
Defense Department and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials said talks are under way with Virginia, West
Virginia, Maryland, New York, Illinois and North Carolina about
reaching similar agreements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1830 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiFrancesco pushes bills that sound like campaign planks  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state constitution says he's the acting
governor when the elected governor is out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Many say Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, is
acting like a governor now, nearly 15 months away from when voters
will be asked to choose Gov. Christie Whitman's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, DiFrancesco talked health care reform. Last week,
it was property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   The talk after his announcements: His news conferences seemed
more like campaign stops than legislative proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Will it bother me? Yes. Will I handle it? Yes,'' DiFrancesco
said Wednesday. ''I expect it. It's not going to deter me from
doing what I have been doing for these years as Senate president.''
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco repeatedly denounced all charges that his proposals
were designed to help put him in the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for his $400 million in property tax rebates came after
talks with residents around the state all demanding relief,
DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   Work on his $60 million prescription drug offering and $60
million more in health care initiatives began in January, the
senator said.
</P>
<P>
   But still the talk that DiFrancesco is walking a candidate's
walk follows.
</P>
<P>
   ''You tend to ignore it. You laugh it off,'' DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You say that's beside the point. These are things we're
planning to do anyway. These are things the majority should be
doing, the Legislature should be doing in these good times.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman is barred by state law from seeking a third term.
Republicans looking to succeed her include DiFrancesco or possibly
Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey will likely be the
Democratic challenger. McGreevey thwarted a primary challenge from
U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   That battle grabbed attention, and possibly pushed McGreevey
into the public mind nearly a year before the gubernatorial primary
in June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democrats have momentum in New Jersey and McGreevey can
piggyback on Gore and Lieberman,'' Rider University political
science professor David Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see that, he said. To pre-empt McGreevey and his
family-friendly agenda, Republicans are moving forward with plans
that get beyond tax cuts, Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment and crime statistics are low. The economy is riding
high. Republicans in the Statehouse need to be seen doing more than
just helping the upper middle class, Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do these good Republican numbers translate into electoral
success in 2001? Probably not unless Republicans get ahead and onto
these other important issues that people see as affecting them,''
Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest boost to a GOP candidate could be the current
Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman this week outlined her plans for health care
legislation, a proposal in her word that ''dovetailed'' with
DiFrancesco's offering.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also wants her plan made into law by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''It helps a lot. It will help her with her last year. These
will be things she can point to as her legacy,'' DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has that last say unless she supports that. Regardless of
what we say, she has the last say when she signs the bill. She can
point to it as hers and we can point to it as well. It helps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
