<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Pacific showing 10 mills to prospective buyers  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) - Georgia-Pacific Corp. has told about 2,700
employees at 10 paper mills that it plans to sell those plants and
has begun offering potential buyers tours of the facilities, as
part of the company's massive restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials began notifying the employees in eight states
last week about the tours, but stressed that it has accepted no
offers for any of the properties, company spokesman Ken Haldin said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had discussions with potential buyers, but we have not
yet made any final decisions,'' Haldin said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific, which makes Angel Soft bathroom tissue and
Sparkle paper towels, announced July 17 that it will buy
Illinois-based Fort James Corp. in a $7.8 billion merger that would
create the world's largest paper-products manufacturer.
Georgia-Pacific also would assume about $3.5 billion in Fort James
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Fort James makes brands such as Quilted Northern, Soft 'N
Gentle, Vanity Fair, Dixie, Brawny and Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Georgia-Pacific said it would divest
250,000 tons of production capacity throughout its extensive,
80-plant pulp and paper-products manufacturing system, as well as
other ''non-strategic businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Fort James announcement, Georgia-Pacific sold
its timber business to a Seattle-based real estate investment trust
for $3 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The plants for sale are three pulp mills in Brunswick, Ga., New
Augusta, Miss., and Baileyville, Maine; as well as seven tissue
production plants in Alsip, Ill; Brattleboro, Vt.; LaGrange, Ga.;
Flagstaff, Ariz.; Gary, Ind.; Greenwich and Plattsburgh, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the plants employ 2,715 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a major transformation underway at the company,
transferring our portfolio of assets to focus on higher-margin
business that focus on the customer,'' Haldin said.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees at Georgia-Pacific's tissue plant in LaGrange
have expressed concern for their jobs if the operation is sold, but
company officials have told workers they expect the plants won't be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just someone else's paycheck,'' said John Hodges, manager
of the LaGrange, Ga. plant, which will be toured Friday by a
potential buyer. He declined to reveal who has expressed interest
in buying the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific employs about 2,000 people at its three
Baileyville, Maine properties. Besides the pulp mill, the company
has two wood-products operations which are not currently for sale,
Haldin said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Georgia-Pacific told employees at the Plattsburgh
plant that negotiations have begun with a potential buyer. That has
made many workers ''very uncomfortable,'' said Timothy Barnard,
president of Paper Allied Chemical and Energy Local 387, which
represents about 350 plant employees.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is Plattsburgh's second-largest employer, with a
payroll of about $25 million, the Albany Times Union reported.
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Georgia-Pacific Corp., http://www.gp.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1908 </TRAILER>
