<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers say if DEP does not change sewer rules, they will  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Lawmakers of both parties said Wednesday
they would use the Legislature's oversight power to nullify sewer
regulations that environmental groups fear will permit too much
sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial regulations, which are in a review phase,
would change how development is managed by taking into account the
health of waterways. In the past, most attention was paid only to
sewage treatment capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But groups like the Sierra Club have condemned the proposed
rules as too loose by failing to place limits on sewer plant
expansion, which in turn paves the way for more housing. They also
say too little emphasis is paid to improving polluted waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Builders have complained about the rules as well, claiming that
new requirements to prevent too much rainwater runoff would add too
much to the cost of homes.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Legislature has the authority to pass resolutions
unilaterally that nullify or rewrite the regulations imposed by
state agencies if lawmakers conclude the agencies were not being
faithful to bills they passed.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Leonard Lance, R-Hunterdon, chairman of the Assembly
Budget Committee, called on the state Department of Environmental
Protection to revise the sewer rules to make sure water pollution
is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, if the DEP fails in this regard, I am confident that
the Assembly will move aggressively forward to override this
rule,'' Lance said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a news release, Sen. John Matheussen, R-Gloucester,
chairman of the Senate's oversight committee, promised prompt
action if the DEP does not change the proposal on its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
