<HEADLINE> Teen hit and killed; friends say it was a game of dare  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VOORHEESVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - Friends of a 14-year-old killed by a
train Wednesday morning said he may have been playing a game of
dare.
</P>
<P>
   Albany County police said Matthew J. Savoie of Slingerlands
acknowledged the CSX train was approaching, even making eye contact
with the conductor, yet remained on the train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   He was hit by the v-shaped cowcatcher on the front of the train
and thrown some 30 feet with such force his shoes were knocked off.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he was probably trying to see how close the train
would come before he jumped off,'' said Chad Puglia, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   CSX officials called the incident a ''senseless'' reminder that
people should not be on or near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany County Sheriff's Department, along with CSX Corp.,
are continuing the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
