<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State police take aim at I-95  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - With accidents up nearly 10 percent and
complaints from drivers reaching a ''crescendo,'' state police on
Wednesday promised a tough new crackdown on aggressive drivers on
I-95 in Fairfield County.
</P>
<P>
   Public Safety Commissioner Arthur Spada said traffic enforcement
in recent years has become ''a neglected stepchild'' as state
police have focused many of their resources on gangs and narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Spada said state police cannot reconfigure I-95 to make it safer
or reduce the heavy volume of traffic, but can deter aggressive
driving by having a ''plethora'' of state police cruisers on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will stay as long as necessary to reduce the mayhem on our
highways,'' Spada said at a news conference at the Troop G state
police barracks in Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown, dubbed ''Operation Putnam,'' or Patrol Uniform
Troopers Noticing Aggressive Motorists, will target I-95 drivers
from Greenwich to Bridgeport. Motorists who speed, make erratic
lane changes, follow too closely or commit other reckless driving
acts will be targeted and given summonses, Spada said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, state police have four patrols per shift on the
Greenwich to Bridgeport stretch of I-95, plus another two during
peak traffic hours.
</P>
<P>
   Under Operation Putnam, they will post three cruisers on spots
along the highway in Stamford, Norwalk and Bridgeport during peak
hours. They also plan to have three or four additional troopers
patrolling that stretch of highway at any given time, said Major
Edward J. Lynch, commanding officer of the Western District of the
state police.
</P>
<P>
   State police said accidents have increased 9.5 percent on I-95
in Fairfield County in one year. In 1998, state police investigated
3,132 accidents. In 1999, that number jumped to 3,429.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic volume on the highway has increased dramatically in the
last decade. State police provided figures that show daily traffic
volume on I-95 in Norwalk, traveling eastbound and westbound, has
grown from 113,000 cars per day in 1990 to 134,000 per day in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I-95 is heavily traveled by Connecticut-New York commuters,
shoreline visitors and vacationers traveling along the Boston-New
York corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Spada drew chuckles from the assorted state police and state
representatives assembled at the news conference when he made a
veiled reference to a traffic stop he made himself.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Spada ordered his state police driver to pull over a
car from Massachusetts when it sped past them on Interstate 91,
just north of Middletown.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be substance to this campaign, even if I have to be
on the highway myself,'' Spada said.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Putnam is similar to two other crackdowns done in
Windham and New London counties.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is named after General Israel Putnam, a
Revolutionary War general who stemmed the British advance into
Greenwich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1912 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changing demographics are potential pitfall for future politicians  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Politicians seeking future office may find that
the melting pot known as New York City's diverse population might
burn them if they're not careful.
</P>
<P>
   Experts and political junkies say statistical data released
Wednesday by the U.S. Census Bureau show that politicians must mix
the needs of not only whites and blacks, but Hispanics and Asians.
They had better, they say, because the voices of the groups that
once were the minority are getting stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the number of non-Hispanic whites living in New York
has fallen about 12 percent, while Hispanic and Asian populations
rose steadily. Hispanics have passed the black population, which
has remained roughly stable, to become the city's largest minority
group.
</P>
<P>
   The population estimates are based on births, deaths and
migration. The numbers are separate from Census 2000 data, which is
not yet available.
</P>
<P>
   ''The job of a politician in New York is more complex, and
because of that you can't just represent one group,'' said Prof.
Mitchell Moss, director of New York University's Taub Urban
Research Center. ''No way does a politician get elected unless they
are able to forge alliances between the groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The changing face of New York's 7.4 million population is
similar to trends found throughout the United States. It's just
happening faster in New York than everywhere else, other than in
California where whites are no longer the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Considering demographic projections, New York is headed the same
way. In 1999, there were about 2.1 million Hispanics in the city, a
16 percent increase since 1990. They made up about 28 percent of
the city population. The Hispanic population has grown steadily
each year in all five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Hispanics will elect more public officials and probably a
mayor in the not-too-distant future,'' said former Mayor Ed Koch,
who said he foresees State Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez as the best
bet. But Koch wouldn't discount Bronx Borough President Fernando
Ferrer in the 2001 mayoral election, even though Koch backs City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Koch said he's already finding elected leaders are
acting differently, noting, ''You see more judges appointed who are
black and Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's Asian residents are expected to eventually be another
force in New York politics. There are about 700,000 Asians in the
city, an increase of 200,000, or 40 percent, since 1990. Asians
made up about 9 percent of the city's 1999 population. Like
Hispanics, the increases were significant in all five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   That's in stark contrast to whites, whose population fell in
each borough other than Staten Island. Whites make up about 37
percent of the city's 1999 population, just over 2.7 million
people. Black populations, amounting to about 1.8 million people,
declined in the Bronx and Brooklyn, but grew slightly in Manhattan,
Queens and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   The data doesn't surprise most demographers, who've watched the
trend actually stretch back to the early 1980s. The population of
white residents has fallen through the years - seen as far back as
the 1970s when the term ''white flight'' was first penned after
700,000 fled the city seeking refuge in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, immigrants from across the globe have surged into New
York. About 970,000 immigrants have come to the city since 1990,
said Joseph Salvo, the director of the population division for the
Department of City Planning.
</P>
<P>
   For years, it was Eastern Europeans and people from Central and
South America. More recently, those numbers have been boosted by
Chinese, immigrants from the former Soviet Union, and the West
Indies, Salvo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's really amazing is we don't get immigrants from one part
of the world,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Writer Sharon L. Crenson performed the computer
analysis for this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-30-00 1914 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
