<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.L. Bean To Pay For Recall Delay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retailer L.L. Bean has agreed to pay a
$750,000 civil penalty to settle allegations it violated federal
law in delaying a report that two of its backpack child carriers
were defective and have caused injuries, the government said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission alleges that L.L.
Bean, Inc. of Freeport, Maine, delayed in reporting that children
can work their way out of the harness and fall through a leg
opening or topple out of the top of the carriers. L.L. Bean knew of
39 incidents involving the two carriers before reporting the
defect, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   One child suffered a concussion and fractured wrist in a fall
from the backpack, and six children suffered contusions,
lacerations, bumps or bruises. Also, four children became entangled
in the carrier's shoulder straps, creating a risk of strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   The model number W695 backpack child carrier is teal green with
gray harnesses and a kickstand. The company sold about 13,000 of
these carriers for about $95 from January 1993 through March 1995,
and recalled them in April 1999. The model number AC25 carrier is
forest green and has gray harnesses with a kickstand. L.L. Bean
sold about 11,800 AC25 carriers for about $95 from January 1997
through October 1998, and recalled them in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Both carriers were sold through the company's Web site, in
catalogs and at retail stories in Maine, Oregon, New Hampshire and
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to pay the civil penalty, L.L. Bean denied that it
violated the Consumer Product Safety Act or any other law.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. Bean characterized the delay as a misunderstanding of the
commission's rules. The company did not fight the fine because it
agrees with the commission's goal to reduce risk to children,
spokeswoman Mary Rose MacKinnon said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company initially thought some customers may have been using
the backpacks improperly because company product testers did not
experience any problems, MacKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said consumers who have either of these carriers
should stop using them immediately and contact L.L. Bean at
1-800-555-9717 or visit the company's Web site at
www.llbean.com/recall for return and refund information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2003 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilians Caught in Colombia's War  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW SELSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NELSON MANDELA BARRIO, Colombia (AP) -- By the thousands,
civilians caught in Colombia's war have been fleeing their villages
and winding up in huge squatter camps like Nelson Mandela Barrio,
outside Cartagena.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sight President Clinton isn't seeing Wednesday during
his visit to the charming Spanish-colonial city of nearby
Cartagena: children walking barefoot in the mud past ramshackle
huts, their bellies distended from malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   The squalid scene underscores the desperation millions of
Colombian civilians face as the war widens and opposing sides gain
strength.
</P>
<P>
   While leftist guerrillas and rival right-wing paramilitary
groups have gotten stronger by profiting from the narcotics trade,
government security forces are receiving a huge injection of aid
from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say civilians are being abused by all sides
-- which is apparent in listening to the horrific experiences of
residents of Nelson Mandela Barrio, or neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''A group of 10 armed men entered my house, tied us up and
dragged away my son,'' said Juan de Dios Llorente in an interview
in his hut, made of burlap sacks strung along branches and
furnished only with two hammocks.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen were members of the country's biggest rebel group,
the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, de Dios Llorente said,
and they accused his son of being an informant for the army.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, a friend told de Dios Llorente that his son's
body was on a nearby farm. De Dios Llorente retrieved the body. He
had been shot three times in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the climate of fear among Colombia's war victims that de
Dios Llorente would only tell his story in the relative privacy of
his shelter.
</P>
<P>
   So far, death squads have not come to Nelson Mandela Barrio,
many of whose residents are black and who respect the South African
leader for his fight to free blacks from apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   The squatter camp, located in a hilly green area a few miles
outside Cartagena, is only five years old but already holds 45,000
people. Some 95 percent have been displaced by the war, aid workers
say.
</P>
<P>
   There is no system to care for the war refugees, and most are
left to find food and shelter on their own. Only the most
malnourished children are fed by humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is mirrored throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2 million Colombians have fled their homes over the past
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The number of displaced people is growing annually -- last year
alone, 288,000 people were displaced, according to a private
monitoring group, the Consultancy for Human Rights and
Displacement.
</P>
<P>
   Another 148,000 fled during the first six months of this year,
the group reported, and officials say as many as 40,000
coca-growing farmers could be uprooted when a U.S.-backed anti-drug
offensive gets underway in southern Colombia next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Rome-based World Food Program on Wednesday called for more
aid for Colombia's displaced, saying an appeal for $9 million worth
of aid has only resulted in about one quarter of the assistance
required.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the war refugees sought out President Clinton in
Cartagena on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Arroyo, 29, spent more than eight hours in Cartagena hoping
to pass Clinton a letter in which she beseeched his help for her
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''Two years ago, the war between paramilitaries and rebels cost
the lives of humble campesinos who were brutally killed and their
humble homes destroyed and burned,'' the letter said. ''Terror
overcame us and we had to flee to save our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo's six siblings and two elderly parents, who had been
rural farmers, now sell goods on the street, work as maids and take
other menial labor. ''Sir, we need your help,'' the letter added.
</P>
<P>
   Benigna Blanco left her village of Maria la Baja two months ago,
joining dozens of her neighbors in the northern town who had fled
in previous months.
</P>
<P>
   She finally joined the stream of refugees because her six
children, the youngest eight years old, were becoming traumatized.
</P>
<P>
   ''Paramilitaries would come at night with lists of names in
their hands and shoot people in their homes,'' Blanco said.
</P>
<P>
   Misael Munoz, 34, surveyed the expanding Nelson Mandela Barrio,
ankle deep in mud after a torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz left his hometown of Santa Marta along the Caribbean coast
two months ago after heavily armed men stormed into a neighbor's
house and shot three people dead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know who the killers were, but even if I did I would
not say,'' Munoz said. ''I'm still very unnerved by what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Munoz has now uprooted his whole life. As men nearby banged
branches together with hammers to create frames for their shacks,
he considered his situation. As grim as it was, he was alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is better to be here in the mud than in a pretty casket,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Dios Llorente, meanwhile, prays that eventually his village
of Curulao will become safe enough for him to return.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want peace,'' he said. ''It's the only thing I want.
Peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2003 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Inspector: Ready To Work in Iraq  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The chief U.N. weapons inspector for Iraq
said Wednesday he was ready to send teams to Baghdad to start up
new arms searches -- despite the flat refusal by Iraqi authorities
to allow inspectors in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Blix, executive chairman of the U.N. Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission, said in a report that his
new agency had hired the core staff and recruited and trained the
required inspectors needed to deploy teams.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, he said, ''could plan and commence a number of
activities in Iraq which would be necessary to prepare for
monitoring, verification and inspection envisaged by the Security
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz made clear
that Iraq would not allow a new weapons inspection team to enter
Iraq and said the country remained firm in its refusal to cooperate
with the Security Council resolution that established the new
inspection agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, known as UNMOVIC, was created in December to replace
the U.N. Special Commission, which oversaw the destruction of
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction in the aftermath of the 1991
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors from the Special Commission left Iraq in December
1998 ahead of U.S. and British airstrikes, launched to punish Iraq
for failing to cooperate with arms searches. Iraq has barred any
U.N. inspectors from returning.
</P>
<P>
   Blix also reported on a recent meeting of his advisory panel in
which commissioners discussed the inspection of so-called
''sensitive sites,'' in Iraq. Inspections on such sites led to a
crisis in arms searches two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some commissioners called for guildelines and operating
procedures for the controversial searches of presidential palaces
and other sensitive areas, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Reasons To Deal Kemp for Cavs  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Shawn Kemp's waistline and contract both got
too big for the Cleveland Cavaliers -- that's why he was sent to
Portland on Wednesday in a three-way trade.
</P>
<P>
   One other factor: Kemp wanted out of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was looking to hopefully go somewhere else,'' Cavs general
manager Jim Paxson said at a news conference. ''And that was made
very clear to us last spring.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Cavs made it very clear to Kemp that they're not going
to cry now that he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Kemp, a six-time All-Star coming off his worst
pro season, the Cavs got forwards Clarence Weatherspoon and Chris
Gatling plus a future first-round draft pick and cash from Miami.
They also got 36-year-old guard Gary Grant from Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers re-signed free agent forward Brian Grant and sent
him to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the short term we have depth, we have a lot of players
fighting for time and positions,'' Paxson said. ''In the long term,
we have some flexibility that could create a chance to be able to
improve the roster.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was finalized a few weeks ago, but under league rules
the teams were prohibited from announcing the package until the end
of the month because Gatling had been traded within the past 60
days. Also, Portland president Bob Whitsitt was out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, who signed a seven-year, $98 million contract after coming
to the Cavs in a three-way trade in 1997, will join a Blazers' team
that nearly beat the eventual NBA champion Los Angeles Lakers in
the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are hoping a return to the Pacific Northwest will
motivate Kemp, who began his career in Seattle where he worked with
Whitsitt.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp had a great first year for Cleveland -- he was an All-Star --
and was selected to the Cavaliers' 30th anniversary team. But he
has reported to training camp 50 pounds overweight the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The added weight grounded Kemp, who used to be one of the most
ferocious dunkers in the league. Too often last season he was
forced to adjust his shot or just had it blocked. He finished the
season averaging 17.8 points -- his lowest total since 1992-93-- and
with a career-low 41.7 field-goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp was also a liability on the defensive end, leading the
league in personal fouls and finishing third in turnovers -- a
remarkable stat for a frontline player.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old was a bigger headache off the court. He
regularly arrived late for home games, team meetings and flights,
failing to be the type of role model the Cavs wanted for their
young players.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a coach it's tough for me to see a guy leave who gave me 18
points and eight rebounds,'' Cavs coach Randy Wittman said. ''But
on my team, my best players have to be players that the other
people look up to and want to follow and emulate, and that didn't
always happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season ended, Kemp promised the Cavs that he would not
only work hard during this off-season, but that he would stay in
contact with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We never heard from him,'' said Wittman, who estimated the
club unsuccessfully tried to call Kemp 25-30 times. ''But it wasn't
uncommon at his other stops. A lot of things that went on here went
on in Seattle. I had a whole thing mapped out for him and it wasn't
able to be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Wittman said he wasn't sure if Kemp could ever shed the weight
and become a dominating player again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to say he won't,'' Wittman said. ''But the
weight affected his play last year. His ability to really explode
to the basket was hurt. The shots that he was getting blocked were
baskets for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxson and Wittman stressed that there were a lot of reasons the
Cavs dealt their only big-name player.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever you're considering trading, every factor comes into
it. To say strictly done for financial reasons, no. Strictly done
for the weight reasons -- everything factors in,'' Paxson said.
</P>
<P>
   After the season, Kemp asked the Cavs to see if they could work
out a trade. The prospects seemed slim since Kemp's contract calls
for him to make $71 million over the next four years, including
$46.5 million in the final two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It strictly wasn't just a money issue, but at the same time,
because of the back end of his contract, the flexibility of being
able to do anything to improve this team was greatly limited,''
Paxson said.
</P>
<P>
   Money isn't an issue for the Blazers with owner Paul Allen's
money and a burning desire to win an NBA title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2015 </TRAILER>
