<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Finally Get Backup QB  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- After being booed and kicked out of
Philadelphia, Doug Pederson will get the red-carpet treatment in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson, a seven-year veteran released by the Eagles on Sunday,
will be the Browns' backup quarterback for Tim Couch this season.
Cleveland has offered the 31-year-old Pederson a two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns have been looking for a backup QB since losing Ty
Detmer, who tore an Achilles' tendon during an exhibition game
against Chicago and is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Spergon Wynn is currently Cleveland's No. 2 QB with
rookie Kevin Thompson the No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson, who has also played for Green Bay and Miami, was
expected to arrive Wednesday night and will take a physical
Thursday morning. Barring any problems, he'll practice with the
Browns by afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson had initially turned down an offer to come to
Cleveland, saying he wanted to spend some time with his family
following his release by the Eagles and a tumultuous '99 season in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson started nine games for the Eagles, before being benched
in favor of rookie Donovan McNabb. Earlier Wednesday, Browns coach
Chris Palmer said he thought Pederson had been left ''emotionally
scarred'' after being treated harshly by fans and media in Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were prepared to go with the two young backups,'' said
Dwight Clark, Cleveland's director of football operations.
''Personally, you feel more comfortable with someone who has
experience just in case Tim were to go down for whatever reason.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it'll take two or maybe three weeks for Doug to get up
to speed with the offense. I would anticipate he will be inactive
for a while until he learns the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pederson was Green Bay's third-string quarterback when the
Packers went to the Super Bowl in 1996 and '97. He has completed
137 of 259 passes for 1,445 yards and nine touchdowns in his
career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2048 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Cops Arrest Drug Runner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Police have arrested a convicted drug
trafficker for allegedly hijacking a Brazilian airliner carrying 72
people and fleeing with $3.3 million in stolen funds, authorities
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson Palermo, 43, who has two drug convictions, was arrested
late Tuesday in downtown Sao Paulo, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He used to be one of the biggest drug runners in Brazil,''
said federal police officer Gilberto Tadeu.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Palermo led four men armed with handguns in
hijacking the plane Aug. 16, forcing it to land at an isolated
airstrip in southern Brazil and fleeing in a waiting car with $3.3
million taken from the cargo hold. The money belonged to the
state-owned Bank of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 66 passengers aboard the Vasp Airline jet were
tourists from Italy, France and Japan returning from the famous
Iguacu Falls on the border with Argentina. They and the six crew
members were all unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers on the hijacked plane identified Palermo from photos
shown to them by investigators, Tadeu said. Detectives then traced
Palermo to a location near Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   No other arrests have yet been made in the case, and no cash has
been recovered, Tadeu said.
</P>
<P>
   Palermo was being held in the southern Brazil city of Londrina,
some 210 miles west of Sao Paulo, near where the airliner was
forced to land, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Palermo was a pilot and was raised in the area,
factors they claimed helped him in planning the robbery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2052 </TRAILER>
