<HEADLINE> Press: Peru Press Needs Freedom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Despite the appearance of a free press, Peru
needs to take steps to ensure against media interference by its
intelligence agency, a delegation of U.S. and Latin American
newspaper publishers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of several recommendations presented by a two-day
mission from the Inter American Press Association to President
Alberto Fujimori, the IAPA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, led by Houston Chronicle Publisher Tony
Pederson, president of the association, met with Fujimori on
Tuesday for about two hours in the Government Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is freedom of the press in Peru, but there are threats
in motion,'' Pederson told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said after the meeting that he recognized
''imperfections'' and that ''certain acts are committed that could
be considered attempts against press liberty.'' But he called those
cases ''isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's critics contend that the National Intelligence
Service controls the editorial content of Peru's cheap tabloid
newspapers, which frequently launch coordinated smear campaigns
against government opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups also have long complained that journalists
are routinely subject to death threats and other forms of
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson said the organization offered to work with Fujimori's
government to improve conditions for journalism, but that ''it is
difficult to comprehend (the government's) intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's difficult to be optimistic,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
