<HEADLINE> Vermont man pleads guilty to videotaping young girls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. (AP) - A Starksboro, Vt., man will spend up to
25 years in federal prison after he admitted sneaking into an
elementary school locker room to videotape young girls.
</P>
<P>
   George E. Hall, 62, pleaded guilty Wednesday to three counts of
felony burglary and one count of possessing a sexual performance by
a child. As part of the plea bargain, 10 other counts were
dismissed but Hall agreed to stand in a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is expected to receive 8 1-3 to 25 years in a federal
penitentiary when he is sentenced Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   If he is identified in the lineup, he may face other charges
including sexual abuse, according to Warren County District
Attorney Sterling Goodspeed. Those charges are not believed to be
connected to the taping of the elementary school girls.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also faces federal weapons charges in Vermont. He had three
prior felony convictions for lewd conduct with a child in Vermont
and one previous conviction for lewd conduct and indecent assault
on a child in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was arrested in March after he was reported acting
suspicious wearing a wig in a Queensbury elementary school. Police
said they found video tapes in Hall's car revealing what are
believed to be images of sexual contact with girls.
</P>
<P>
   Queensbury is 50 miles north of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
