<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Affirms Palestinian Claim  </HEADLINE>
By SARAH EL DEEB
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Egypt (AP) -- Egypt's foreign minister said his
country was firm in its support for Palestinian sovereignty in
Jerusalem Wednesday after a meeting between President Hosni Mubarak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting in Alexandria was the sixth time since the collapse
of the Camp David talks last July that the two leaders met. Neither
spoke with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''As there is Israeli sovereignty over west Jerusalem there
should be Palestinian sovereignty over east Jerusalem. This is the
logic of justice ... and of international agreements,'' Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak has emerged as a key mediator after the U.S.-brokered
Camp David summit between Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak collapsed over their rival claims to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton underlined Egypt's importance a day before,
when he stopped in Cairo to talk with Mubarak following a three-day
trip to Africa. U.S. and Egyptian officials stressed they will
continue their drive to achieve peace, but that there were no signs
of a breakthrough following the Clinton-Mubarak meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak said Tuesday the Egyptians were working to help the
Israelis and Palestinians draft a framework agreement to guide
their negotiations. Moussa added Wednesday that Jerusalem was not
the only issue to be ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   With little apparent flexibility on Jerusalem, it was difficult
to predict progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no concessions or ambiguities regarding the position
on east Jerusalem as a capital for the Palestinian state,'' Moussa
said. East Jerusalem was captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast
war.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, Israeli Foreign Minister Schlomo Ben-Ami
urged Arafat to respond to new ideas put forward by Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Berlin after discussing the peace
process with his German counterpart, Joschka Fischer, Ben-Ami said
that he welcomed Egypt's efforts to mediate an end to the
half-century-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''As to Mubarak's proposals, they need to be studied and we need
to see what is forthcoming from the Palestinian side,'' Ben-Ami
said. ''If we are to start considering new ideas, we have to know
if Arafat is also interesting in contemplating them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released later by the Israeli Foreign Ministry,
Ben-Ami said Germany must tell Arafat in the clearest possible way
''that the moment of truth has arrived, and he can no longer evade
fateful decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians have set a Sept. 13 deadline for
concluding peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
