<HEADLINE> Tex., Va. Execute Convicted Killers  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GRACZYK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A paroled burglar was executed
Wednesday for beating and stabbing his parents and sister to death
12 years ago. Also Wednesday, a man was executed in Virginia for
crushing the skulls of his neighbor and her young daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery Henry Caldwell, 37, was the sixth Texas inmate given a
lethal injection this month and the 32nd this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy final statement, he expressed love for his family,
including two brothers who had testified during his punishment
phase that he remained a threat to society.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can forgive you all but you must ask for forgiveness from
God,'' Caldwell said. ''I leave now to join my parents and my only
sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell was on parole and had previous convictions for burglary
and robbery when the killings occurred. He told police that his
parents, Henry and Gwendolyn Caldwell, and his 19-year-old sister,
Kimberly, had run into his knife during an argument over money in
their Dallas home.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, in an interview on death row, Caldwell blamed the
fatal attacks on a Jamaican mob angry because he had stolen some of
their drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, Russel W. Burket, 32, who had been given a last
minute stay by the Supreme Court two months ago, also was executed
by injection Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Burket's attorney, Anthony A. Protogyrou, had argued that his
client was mentally disabled and wasn't thinking correctly when he
pleaded guilty in 1994 to killing his neighbor, Katherine Tafelski,
and her 5-year-old daughter, Ashley, by crushing their skulls with
a rusty crowbar.
</P>
<P>
   Protogyrou also had sought more tests on a washcloth found at
the crime scene with traces of semen. Previous testing matched the
DNA to about 8 percent of all white men, including Burket and his
brother. Lester Burket Jr. was questioned by police about the 1993
slaying but was never charged.
</P>
<P>
   Russel Burket's execution originally was set for June 21, but
the Supreme Court granted him a stay 75 minutes before he was
scheduled to die. Eight days later, the court refused to hear his
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Burket made no final statement from the death chamber Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bobby West said Burket was in a ''good frame of mind''
before the execution and understood what was about to happen. ''He
has repented all his sins,'' West said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
