<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Confirms Fighting in Congo  </HEADLINE>
By ARNAUD ZAJTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Rebel and government forces exchanged
attacks in northern Congo, U.N. officials said Wednesday, in the
first fighting since the government unilaterally suspended a
cease-fire a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan-backed Congolese Liberation Movement rebels fired shells
at government soldiers near the town of Emate in Equateur province,
U.N. observer squadron leader Pete Riley told journalists at a
press conference in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, President Laurent Kabila's forces bombed the
rebel positions at the town of Lokutu, west of the Congo River port
city of Kisangani, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, which ended a two-week lull in fighting, likely
occurred in recent days. But few details are available, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Congo broke out in August 1998 when rebels,
backed by Rwanda and Uganda, accused Kabila of corruption and
harboring Hutu militiamen who fled Rwanda after committing genocide
there in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and his allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- signed a
cease-fire agreement last year with Rwanda, Uganda and the rebels.
But the fighting has continued.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government announced its unilateral decision to
suspend the cease-fire deal amid mutual accusations of violations.
</P>
<P>
   That announcement came one day after the Congolese government
gave permission for U.N. peacekeeping forces to deploy throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council has proposed a monitoring force of
5,537 observers and troops to oversee the peace accord but say it
is waiting for all sides to respect the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The council said Wednesday that even though Congo has approved
the deployment, it still must clarify whether it intends to abide
by the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The council members, meeting at U.N. headquarters in New York,
said they hoped the upcoming Millennium Summit of world leaders
would give the warring sides in Congo a chance to recommit
themselves to the agreement and advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats have expressed doubts about how the United Nations
could deploy a peacekeeping force to monitor a cease-fire agreement
that Congo is not participating in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2139 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0176 </DOCNO>
