<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressTatiana Riabouchinska:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Russian-born ballerina Tatiana Riabouchinska,
an internationally celebrated star in the 1930s and 1940s who
taught dance in Southern California for a half-century, died Aug.
24 of heart failure. She was 84.
</P>
<P>
   She won renown for her classical performances, including the
title role of ''Giselle,'' but was most identified with a part she
didn't actually dance: the hippopotamus ballerina in Walt Disney's
1940 animated movie ''Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney animators sketched her at rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Riabouchinska studied ballet with Alexander Volinine
and Mathilde Kschessinskaya.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographer George Balanchine later recruited her for the
Ballets Russes de Monte Carlo, then based in France. At age 15,
Riabouchinska was the oldest of three publicized by the company's
as its ''baby ballerinas.''
</P>
<P>
   She was later featured in ''La Concurrence,'' ''Cotillon,''
''Jeux d'Enfants,'' ''Les Presages,'' ''Cendrillon'' and
''Paganini.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2145 </TRAILER>
