<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Aid To China In Peril  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China's stepped-up naval activities near Japan
imperil aid from Tokyo, Japan's foreign minister said Wednesday,
urging both sides to settle their differences and improve ties.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo is committed to helping China's economic development, but
opposition in Japan is forcing a more critical look at that aid,
Foreign Minister Yohei Kono said in a speech to the Chinese
Communist Party's main training institute.
</P>
<P>
   Future economic cooperation with China ''hinges more than ever
upon receiving the full understanding and support of both the
Japanese and Chinese peoples,'' Kono told scholars at the Central
Party School.
</P>
<P>
   His speech pinpointed areas of mistrust -- Chinese missile
buildups and fears of resurgent Japanese militarism.
</P>
<P>
   But he offered lengthy suggestions for opportunities to
cooperate, among them a Northeast Asian security forum involving
Japan, North Korea, South Korea, Russia, China and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Japan gives China more than $3.6 billion in economic aid
annually, widely seen as a form of compensation for Japan's brutal
wartime occupation of much of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers from Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party
postponed approval of $160 million in low-interest loans last week,
reflecting worries over the Chinese navy's increased
intelligence-gathering near Japanese waters, sometimes under the
guise of conducting oceanic surveys.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kono said he and Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan
took a ''meaningful step forward'' this week by agreeing to inform
each other of scientific expeditions around each other's waters.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese worry about China's increased military spending and
growing arsenal of missiles, Kono said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, in a meeting Wednesday with Kono,
said he wanted to promote trust by meeting public and government
figures during his planned visit to Japan in October.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly China-Japan ties ''are hard won'' and should be
treasured ''so as not to cause misunderstanding and unfriendly
voices,'' China's official Xinhua News Agency reported Zhu as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Central Party School scholars have been highly critical of the
U.S.-Japan alliance and have at times accused Tokyo of secretly
harboring ambitions of military expansionism.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently seeking to allay those suspicions, Kono said Japan
would never allow a return to a militarist state and called a
competitive military expansion by either China or Japan ''utterly
unfathomable.''
</P>
<P>
   China's Communist Party drew much of its early support from
resistance to Japanese invaders and deep antipathy toward Japan
endures among many politically active Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The government and the state-controlled media help keep memories
of Japanese wartime aggression and atrocities fresh. The southern
city of Nanning was to hold a day of mourning Wednesday for more
than 360 residents who died in a 1938 bombing of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese President Jiang Zemin -- apparently seeking to smooth
concerns in Tokyo over Chinese naval activities -- said Tuesday that
there was ''no change'' in his country's friendly attitude toward
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kono and his Chinese counterpart, Tang Jiaxuan, have agreed that
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji would visit Japan from Oct. 12-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2145 </TRAILER>
