<HEADLINE> Giants 2, Pirates 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Russ Ortiz won his sixth consecutive start and
Barry Bonds hit his 484th career home run as the San Francisco
Giants beat the Pittsburgh Pirates 2-0 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz (11-10) allowed four hits in seven innings and matched his
career high with 12 strikeouts. He was 6-0 with a 1.31 ERA in
August.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates loaded the bases with one out in the sixth, but
second baseman Ramon Martinez made a leaping catch of Warren
Morris' liner and Emil Brown struck out on a 95 mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz left for a pinch-hitter in the eighth after throwing 113
pitches. He improved to 5-0 with a 1.39 ERA in seven career
appearances against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Robb Nen pitched a perfect ninth for his 32nd save. The NL
West-leading Giants have won 11 of their last 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' home run was his 39th of the season and came in the
fourth off Jimmy Anderson (4-7). Bonds doubled with two outs in the
sixth and scored on Ellis Burks' single.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds has 89 homers at Three Rivers Stadium, second only to
Willie Stargell's 147.
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker expects to give Bonds the day off
Thursday, meaning this might have been the All-Star outfielder's
final game at Three Rivers, where his major league career began in
1986 with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson lost his third consecutive start.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, who beat the Giants 8-0 on a one-hitter Tuesday,
have not won consecutive games since they defeated San Diego at
home on July 28-29.
Notes: Bonds has passed Stan Musial, Stargell, Dave Winfield and
Carl Yastrzemski on the career home run list this year. His next
target is No. 17 Lou Gehrig at 493. ... The Pirates are guaranteed
of a single-digit win total this month. They're 8-20 this month
with one game left. ... Ortiz's other 12-strikeout game came
against Houston on June 25.
</P>
