<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Brings Aid To Colombia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia (AP) -- In a country beset by decades of violence,
President Clinton delivered a $1.3 billion U.S. package today which he said
would help Colombia defeat its drug traffickers without getting the United
States into a Vietnam-like quagmire. ''We will not get into a shooting war''
with Colombian guerrillas, he said, standing alongside Colombian President
Andres Pastrana. During Clinton's half-day visit to Cartagena, police said they
discovered and deactivated a 4.4-pound bomb found five blocks from a
neighborhood Clinton planned to tour.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lieberman Says ADL Misunderstood
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman said today that the Anti-Defamation League misunderstood him earlier
this week when he advocated a greater role for faith and religion in American
public life. He said the response to his remarks at a black church in Detroit on
Sunday and an interfaith breakfast in Chicago on Monday was ''a bit of an
overreaction.'' After those speeches, the league urged Lieberman, the first
Orthodox Jew on a national party ticket, to tone down his references to
religion.
