<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in Train Derailment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKINGS, S.D. (AP) -- Authorities have arrested a man they
suspect tampered with a rail switch, causing a train derailment
that killed one man and seriously injured another, federal
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Goltz, 20, was arrested Tuesday night. He is to be
arraigned Thursday in Sioux Falls on a charge of willful derailment
or damage to a train involved in interstate commerce, U.S. Attorney
Ted McBride said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Saturday incident, the Dakota, Minnesota &AMP; Eastern
Railroad train was diverted to a side track and plowed into parked
rail cars. One crew member died and the train engineer was
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   According to an affidavit by FBI agent Douglas Heilman, Goltz
admitted that he broke a lock off the switching mechanism, moved
the switch to direct the train off the main track and covered a
warning reflector with a plastic garbage bag.
</P>
<P>
   ''Goltz claimed to have committed these acts as a 'prank,'''
Heilman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Goltz was being held without bail Wednesday night in the
Minnehaha County Jail, and jail officials declined to allow him to
be interviewed. It was not clear whether he had hired an attorney
or whether one had been appointed for him.
</P>
<P>
   Goltz has no connection to the DM&AMP;E nor any group opposed to the
railroad's $1.4 billion plan to renovate some tracks and build a
new line into the Wyoming coal fields, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law stipulates a punishment of life in prison or the
death penalty if the crime results in death. The Justice Department
will make a recommendation to Attorney General Janet Reno on
whether to seek the death penalty for a conviction, McBride said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
