<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suharto's Trial Attendance Unsure  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Ex-President Suharto is too ill to
attend the opening of his corruption trial Thursday, one of the
former dictator's lawyers said following a medical exam.
</P>
<P>
   Security concerns surrounding the trial were heightened when a
small bomb exploded late Wednesday inside an empty bus less that
300 yards from the venue of the hearing. No one was injured and
damage was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not possible,'' said Denny Kailimang, a member of the
eight-man defense team, replying to a question on whether Suharto
would go to court. He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Kailimang's comments came after a medical team that had been
examining Suharto left his central Jakarta residence in a four-car
convoy.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's lawyers claim that 2&AMP;frac12; years after student protesters
dislodged him from power, Suharto, 79, has become a frail old man,
brain-damaged by strokes and unable to understand simple questions.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesian Attorney General Marzuki Darusman said the former
leader must attend and that recent medical tests, including brain
scans, by state doctors say that he can.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prosecutors will do all they can to bring Suharto before
the court for the opening session,'' Darusman said.
</P>
<P>
   If Suharto doesn't come to court Thursday, a panel of judges
that is deciding the case is expected to order government
physicians to examine him before deciding how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto is charged with stealing $583 million of state funds,
according to a copy of the indictment obtained by The Associated
Press. He had denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is seen as a key test of Indonesia's determination to
stamp out corruption and deal with the excesses of decades of
authoritarian rule. President Abdurrahman Wahid, however, has said
he will pardon Suharto if he returns ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-page indictment alleges that Suharto enriched himself,
his family and cronies with state money through tax-free charitable
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges Suharto, who ruled the world's fourth
most populous nation with an iron hand for 32 years, issued
presidential decrees to pilfer the public purse.
</P>
<P>
   It alleges he skimmed 2 percent of the country's income tax
revenue, took funds from sales taxes and snatched a percentage from
the monthly paychecks of civil servants and military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,200 police are guarding the Agriculture Ministry,
where the trial is to be held in a converted conference room able
to hold hundreds of spectators and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Judges and prosecutors have been assigned bodyguards and bomb
squads are on standby.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Wednesday night's blast, which damaged the interior
of the bus, was a message to the trial's participants.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an act of terror to intimidate people before the trial
starts,'' Jakarta's chief detective, Col. Hari Montolalu, said.
</P>
<P>
   Some students complain the charges against Suharto are not broad
enough -- that he stole billions not just millions and that he
should also be prosecuted for human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is excellent that he is being forced to stand
trial,'' said Gina Ariyani, 23, a college student. ''But his people
are playing games and attempting to destabilize the country. They
still have power and money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2241 </TRAILER>
