<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Laments State of Military  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Dick Cheney said Wednesday a military made strong
in the 1980s by GOP-led defense spending is now low on morale,
weapons and soldiers because of ''eight years of neglect and
misplaced priorities'' by the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the former defense secretary and now GOP vice
presidential candidate, said troops that were victorious in the
Persian Gulf War have been hurt by spending cuts that have gone
''far beyond any careful weighing of the national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A commander in chief leads the military built by those who
came before him,'' he said in a speech to the Southern Center on
International Studies. ''That is why we were able to win the Gulf
War -- because we were commanding a military rebuilt in the 1980s,''
said Cheney, who was defense secretary under President Bush during
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The speech came one week after Cheney was called on to defend
the military cuts that he had overseen as Pentagon chief, many of
them related to the end of the Cold War. Cheney said Wednesday he
cut ''what was no longer needed and nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   The military budget began dropping after 1985, the high point
under President Reagan. It continued to decline under the Bush
administration and through most of the Clinton administration,
although it has been up in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate,
responded to Cheney's speech by pointing out recent budget boosts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the strongest military in the world and we reversed
the decline of the Bush-Quayle years,'' Gore told reporters as he
was flying to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said the buildup under Reagan enabled President Clinton
and Gore to send troops on overseas deployments, missions he said
have left them stretched to the limits. He said today's military is
''still the most formidable in the world'' but is woefully
underfunded, putting troops at higher risk if the country were to
have to fight wars.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, George W. Bush will review overseas deployments, pay
soldiers more, improve schools for soldiers' children and keep the
''faith with our veterans ... treating them with dignity and ...
earning their trust in return,'' Cheney said, drawing applause.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell, who was chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff during the Bush administration, supported Cheney's
observations on the state of the military.
</P>
<P>
   ''Readiness has declined, investment has declined, maintenance
has declined, training has declined,'' said Powell, who serves as
an informal adviser to Bush on military matters and is widely
viewed as a likely secretary of state in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign accused Cheney of twisting the facts and said
Gore wants to use part of the budget surplus for defense, while
Bush wants it for tax cuts that will benefit the wealthy
</P>
<P>
   ''By twisting facts about our military for partisan gain,
Governor Bush has demonstrated that he is not ready to be America's
commander in chief,'' said spokeswoman Kym Spell.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore want to spend more on defense. Gore has
proposed a 10-year, $127 billion defense package that includes the
3.7 percent military pay increase enacted this year, investments to
modernize equipment and more funding for veterans hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed $1 billion a year more for military pay over
the next five years and $310 million to fix schools on military
bases.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier speech, Cheney quoted ''one observer'' as saying.
''Our military faces readiness problems.'' That observer, he said,
was Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, Gore's vice presidential
running mate, a statement that sent a murmur running through the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign accused Cheney of taking Lieberman's words out
of context. They provided the text of the Feb. 24, 1999 speech in
which, after citing readiness problems, Lieberman immediately
added, ''The Department of Defense deserves credit for highlighting
these problems. The administration deserves credit for increasing
the budget to address them. And our colleagues who have crafted
this bill deserve credit for bringing these issues into clear
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign also cited a Lieberman speech three months
later, in which the senator said he was ''pleased and proud that we
reversed the 14 years of declining defense dollars and added the
money to readiness and procurement to fix the most urgent,
near-term readiness problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just the latest regrettable incident of the Bush
campaign resorting to false and negative attacks,'' said Gore
spokesman Mark Fabiani.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said Lieberman's full
remarks did not absolve the administration of the fact that
problems existed for years under Clinton-Gore. ''He's saying that
the problem still exists. He's giving the administration credit for
finally addressing the problem, and that is not leadership by any
measure,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2246 </TRAILER>
