<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebels Release 5 Captives  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- A Sierra Leone rebel faction on
Wednesday released five British soldiers held captive in the
country's jungle interior since last week, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The troops were ''in British hands and on their way towards
Freetown,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Tony Cramp, the British forces
spokesman. ''They were all in very good condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Six others were still believed held by the small rebel group,
known as the West Side Boys, and their status was not immediately
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are delighted with this development but obviously our
thoughts and concerns still remain with those being held,'' Cramp
said. ''Talks are continuing and we hope for early release of the
remainder.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramp declined to reveal details of where and how the five were
released or whether a deal had been struck with the captors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have others in detention,'' Cramp said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the British military force and the U.N.
peacekeeping mission to this West African country have been in
radio contact with the captive soldiers as well as with leaders of
the West Side Boys. There have also been face-to-face talks, the
British Ministry of Defense has said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, a British Foreign Office
spokesman said Wednesday the five were released with the help of
the U.N. and specifically the Jordanian contingent of Sierra
Leone's U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for the release of the other hostages would
continue first thing in the morning, the Foreign Office spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, members of the 1st Irish Regiment, were stationed
at Benguema, about 25 miles east of Freetown, where British
instructors are training Sierra Leonean army recruits under a
bilateral agreement.
</P>
<P>
   They disappeared Friday in an area occupied by the West Side
Boys, who have fought with both the government and the rebels in
this war-ravaged country. In recent weeks, the West Side Boys --
known for their brutality and ill-discipline -- have broken away
again from the Sierra Leone army and appear to be acting on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone's main rebel group, the Revolutionary United Front,
reignited the West African country's nine-year civil war in May by
seizing about 500 U.N. peacekeepers and keeping 233 others
surrounded for 2-&AMP;frac12; months. The move embarrassed the United Nations
and prompted a reassessment of the U.N. mission here.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Britain circulated a draft resolution at the United
Nations Wednesday to increase the 13,000-strong U.N. peacekeeping
force in Sierra Leone to 20,500.
</P>
<P>
   The draft parallels recommendations made last week by
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and, once adopted, would signal a
major new commitment by the Security Council to reassert U.N.
authority in Sierra Leone following the embarrassing seizure of 500
U.N. peacekeepers by rebels in May.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution is expected to be in negotiation for several
weeks -- primarily because the United States needs to give Congress
at least two weeks notice before signing off on any costly increase
in peacekeeping forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2254 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Autopsy: Ark. Student Shot Teacher  </HEADLINE>
By MELISSA NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A student who had just been dropped
from a graduate program bought a box of bullets less than an hour
before walking into his adviser's office at the University of
Arkansas, shooting him three times and killing himself, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy results released Wednesday determined that James Easton
Kelly killed English professor John Locke on Monday and then shot
himself in the heart.
</P>
<P>
   A receipt for a 50-round box of ammunition was discovered
Wednesday in Kelly's rental car, parked near the English
department's offices.
</P>
<P>
   The receipt was stamped 11:27 a.m. by a Wal-Mart 10 miles from
the Fayetteville campus. Police were summoned to Kimpel Hall at
12:14 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''He went immediately to campus,'' university police Chief Larry
Slamons said.
</P>
<P>
   Slamons said the bullets purchased at that Wal-Mart were the
same ones used in Kelly's .38-caliber revolver and the same bullets
that killed Locke. An attache case found in the office contained
the rest of the bullets and 46 additional rounds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't say whether other professors could have been
targets.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot speculate at this time about the other professors,''
Slamons said. ''He had the ammunition. In the event he had left
that building, it would have been available to him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the car rental records, Kelly rented the car on
Aug. 21, the same day he was notified of the graduate school's
decision to dismiss him. Kelly had been taking graduate classes at
the university for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, Kelly's adviser, was also chairman of the committee that
voted to deny his reinstatement to the comparative literature
program. Locke abstained from the vote, but he likely was the one
who notified Kelly of the decision, Slamons said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was the most visible and he was giving him the bad news,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting between Locke and Kelly wasn't listed in the
professor's appointment book, and Locke had previously told a
colleague that he was apprehensive about meeting with Kelly in
private.
</P>
<P>
   In the attache case found after the shootings, police discovered
five letters addressed to Kelly -- including the one telling him he
could no longer take classes for credit toward an advanced degree.
</P>
<P>
   English professor Brian Wilkie said Kelly had been dismissed
from the graduate program because he was not making satisfactory
progress toward his doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   The university said Kelly had enrolled in, then dropped, English
department classes several times over the past three years. He was
enrolled as a non-degree student for the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   After the first shot rang out in Kimpel Hall on Monday, graduate
student Bethany Edstrom said she heard someone say: ''I didn't do
anything.'' Slamons said the shot through Locke's hand indicated he
raised his arm in a futile attempt to defend himself, Slamons said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers responding to at least three 911 calls said a man
behind Locke's office door said he had been hurt but that they
shouldn't enter. Slamons said the Locke and Kelly may have
struggled, with Locke perhaps landing a blow before being fatally
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, they heard Kelly kill himself with the final of
four shots. Two bullets remained in the revolver when officers
finally entered the cluttered office, Slamons said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Kelly had no criminal record and there was no
indication of discipline problems on his university record.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   University of Arkansas: http://www.uark.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 7, Expos 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks gave Randy Johnson
plenty of offensive support.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson pitched a five-hitter to win his 17th game and
Steve Finley homered twice to lead the Arizona Diamondbacks to a
7-0 win over the Montreal Expos on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (17-5), coming off his first no-strikeout game in 11
years, struck out 10 in his third shutout of the season and 28th of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like every time I got our offense back out there, we
were able to get a few more runs,'' Johnson said. ''As a starting
pitcher, when you go out there and get runs, it's a lot easier to
go out there and feel like you can make a mistake, if it should be
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also pitched shutouts in a 1-0 win over Pittsburgh on
April 9 and a 6-0 win in Chicago on April 30.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew we were in trouble after he threw the first fastball
tonight,'' Expos manager Felipe Alou said. ''Some of the young guys
really struggled out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley hit a two-run homer off Felipe Lira (3-5) to cap a
four-run first. He added a solo homer in the fifth -- his 33rd -- for
his third two-homer game of the season, the 17th multihomer game of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Johnson) had a rough outing his last start,'' Finley said.
''He doesn't have too many of those a year, so he came back tonight
and redeemed himself and pitched a great ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez hit his career-best 27th homer homered leading off
the third to put Arizona ahead 5-0. Gonzalez hit 26 homers last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Lira allowed seven hits and five runs in 2 1-3 innings as the
Expos lost for the 16th time in their last 20 games to finish a 2-4
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm running out of explanations,'' Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   The win was Johnson's first in five starts against Montreal, the
team he made his major league debut with in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a very good team,'' Johnson said. ''I've watched them
the last two nights. They're a team that kind of lays low. When you
score a few runs on them, they come right back and string some hits
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson retired the first eight Expos he faced -- five on
strikeouts -- before reliever Mike Johnson lined a single to left
with two outs in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ''You give Randy Johnson one run in the first inning and you're
in trouble,'' Alou said. ''We gave him four so the game was decided
in the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller's sacrifice fly in the sixth drove in Arizona's
seventh run.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Johnson has 2,981 career strikeouts. ... Finley's last
two-homer game was on May 2 at Milwaukee. ... 3B Matt Williams,
1-for-20 on the Diamondbacks' current road trip, didn't start.
Craig Counsell started at third base. ... The Expos lineup featured
five switch-hitters, the third time Montreal has had that many
switch-hitters in their batting order this season. The Expos had
Wilton Guerrero batting leadoff, Milton Bradley batting second,
Jose Vidro hitting third, Geoff Blum in the fifth spot and Fernando
Seguignol batting sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
