<HEADLINE> Brewers 3, Dodgers 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Richie Sexson hit a game-winning single in the
bottom of the ninth inning as the Milwaukee Brewers snapped a
three-game losing streak with a 3-2 win over the Los Angeles
Dodgers on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Adams (6-7) gave up a bloop single to Geoff Jenkins
leading off the ninth. Shortstop Alex Cora raced out to get the
ball in short left field and threw wildly over the head off second
baseman Mark Grudzielanek, allowing Jenkins to go to second on
Cora's error.
</P>
<P>
   Sexson followed with a line-drive single to center, scoring the
winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Ray King (1-1) earned his first major league win by pitching a
perfect ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort allowed four hits and two runs
in eight innings. He walked one and struck out a career-high 11.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed solo homers to Jenkins in the first and Tyler
Houston in the fifth as Milwaukee took a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers starter Jamey Wright allowed two runs, six hits and
seven walks in eight innings. Wright has not won since July 28,
when he defeated Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Wright walked Tom Goodwin, Grudzielanek and Shawn Green to open
the first. Eric Karros followed with a sacrifice fly. After a
groundout put runners on second and third, Adrian Beltre hit a
grounder toward shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The ball hit Green as he was running to third and second base
umpire Jeff Kellogg called him out. Beltre was credited with a
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' tied the score at 2 in the sixth inning on an RBI
double by Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Karros' sacrifice fly in the first was his team-leading
ninth of the season. ... Jenkins is tied with Jeromy Burnitz with a
team-leading 24 homers. ... Wright's double in the third was his
first of the season and seventh of his career. ... Dreifort's
previous strikeout high was 10 on July 25, 1998 against Arizona.
</P>
