<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obese Kid Said at Risk With Parents  </HEADLINE>
By MARY PEREA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE (AP) -- The parents of a 120-pound, 3-year-old girl
put her ''at grave risk'' by repeatedly feeding her solid foods
while she was on a doctor-ordered liquid diet, a social worker said
in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Anamarie Martinez-Regino's parents say they lost custody of the
toddler last Friday because they couldn't control her weight. The
child is living in a foster home, and her parents were allowed to
visit her for an hour Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Adela Martinez and Miguel Regino said Wednesday their child has
been on a liquid diet since June 10, except for one time when a
relative accidentally fed her solid food.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said her daughter ''seemed to be doing OK'' during
their visit Wednesday. As her parents were getting ready to leave,
Anamarie ''started to (cry) but we said, 'We're going to see you
again,''' Martinez said. The mother said she was told her daughter
had lost 4 pounds since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A social worker's affidavit for a custody order reviewed by The
Associated Press on Wednesday said Anamarie's doctor recommended
the child be removed because of life-threatening concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The parents admitted giving their daughter solid foods while she
was on a strict liquid diet limited to 550 calories a day, Liza
Perez said in the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Family attorney Troy Prichard said, ''There's obviously a lot of
factual allegations in that affidavit, some of them are true some
of them are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Anamarie was born April 11, 1997, and weighed 6 pounds, 13
ounces, the affidavit said. By March 31, 1998, she was 50 pounds, 9
ounces, and her height was 33 inches. She was placed on a diet and
referred to endocrinologists.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999, she weighed 97 pounds and slept sitting up
because she was unable to breathe while lying down, the affidavit
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time she was taken, she weighed 120 pounds and was 3&AMP;frac12;
feet tall -- three times heavier and 50 percent taller than an
average 3-year-old, according to the girl's physician.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says Anamarie has been tested for a variety of
conditions but doesn't specify the cause of the weight gain. Her
family says the problem has medical roots and is not caused by
overeating or bad nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   A custody hearing is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Hartz, the head of New Mexico's Department of Children,
Youth and Families, said she could not comment specifically on the
case. But she said the department removes children from their
parents only when abuse and neglect are involved.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main issue is not weight, the main issue is safety,'' she
said. ''That's all we would be concerned about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2320 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000830.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Send Parrish to Rochester  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles optioned slumping rookie
left-hander John Parrish to Triple-A Rochester on Wednesday night
and activated reliever Alan Mills off the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish (2-3) started off well with the Orioles after being
recalled from Rochester on July 24, but was shelled in his last two
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a loss to Chicago in which he walked five and gave up
five runs in 1 2-3 innings, Parrish was touched for six runs in 2
1-3 innings Tuesday night in a 12-2 loss to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   He threw 68 pitches, half of them outside the strike zone, and
walked off the mound with a 6.23 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a chance for him to catch his breath,'' said manager
Mike Hargrove, who announced the move after the Orioles' 5-1
victory over Detroit. ''This gets him out a pressure situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish will pitch Sunday for the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ''For lack of a better term, it's a tuneup,'' Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jay Spurgeon will take Parrish's place in the Orioles'
rotation and start Sunday in Cleveland, Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   In his debut with the Orioles last month, Parrish had nine
strikeouts in seven innings against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In his next start, the left-hander allowed only four hits in six
innings against Cleveland to earn his first major league victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a month later, Parrish is looking like a 22-year-old rookie
who never pitched above the Double-A level before this season.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what he is.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think John is a 22-year-old pitcher, and sometimes he
pitches like a 22-year-old pitcher,'' Hargrove said before
Wednesday's game. ''He's got good stuff, and he needs to learn how
to trust that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish will rejoin the Orioles in Minnesota on Tuesday,
Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Mills has been sidelined since Aug. 4 with inflammation in his
right shoulder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
