<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Baseball Game Notes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Indians-Rangers:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Jim Thome entered Wednesday night 228 career homers,
all with the Indians, No. 2 in club history behind Albert Belle's
242. ... The Indians completed a July 28 trade with Milwaukee by
sending minor league second baseman Marcos Scutaro to the Brewers.
Scutaro hit .275 with five homers and 54 RBIs in 124 games for
Triple-A Buffalo this season.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: All-Star C Ivan Rodriguez returned from in Puerto Rico to
have his broken right thumb examined by team Dr. Bobby Wroten.
Wroten said the thumb is healing normally. Rodriguez is wearing a
cast that extends from his thumb to past his wrist, but expects to
have a splint in two weeks. ''It's healing but it's still weak,''
Rodriguez said. Team medical personnel still estimates it will take
3-5 months for the thumb to heal. Rodriguez sustained the injury on
July 24. ... LHP Darren Oliver will make his fifth and final rehab
start with the Rangers' Triple-A Oklahoma affiliate on Thursday.
Oliver has been on the DL since July 31 with weakness in his left
shoulder.
Red Sox-Devil Rays
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: 1B Brian Daubach returned to Boston after hyperextending
his left elbow during Tuesday's bench-clearing brawl. ''It's not
fractured, that's all I know,'' Daubach said. He will undergo
additional tests in Boston. ... 3B Lou Merloni was released from a
hospital after undergoing observation for a concussion he received
during the first-inning brawl. ''I feel all right now. I've just
got a headache and a real stiff neck,'' Merloni said. ''It's no big
deal.'' ... The Red Sox were greeted by the song Kung Fu Fighting
when they started batting practice. Other BP musical selections
included Macho Man and See You in September. The Red Sox close out
the regular season Sept. 29-Oct. 1 at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays sent a tape of Tuesday's first-inning
brawl to the commissioner's office. After the game, the Devil Rays
accused Boston 1B Brian Daubach of throwing sucker punches in the
pile. ''Brian Daubach did not conduct himself in a professional
manner,'' Tampa Bay general manager Chuck LaMar said. ''The action
of Mr. Daubach led to most of the ejections.'' Tampa Bay had five
players, two coaches -- who were serving an acting managers -- and
manager Larry Rothschild all ejected. ... It was just the second
time in major league history one team had three managers ejected in
one game. The other occurred on Aug. 12, 1984, when San Diego
manager Dick Williams, along with acting managers, coaches Ozzie
Virgil and Jack Kroll were thrown out. Current Yankees' manager,
then Atlanta skipper, Joe Torre was also ejected. It appears
Tuesday was the first time one team had eight ejections while their
opponent had none. ... LF Greg Vaughn, who has been limited to DH
duties since Aug. 7, will have his ailing right shoulder examined
Friday. ... Tampa Bay extended its working agreement with
Charleston (S.C) of the South Atlantic League through 2004.
Tigers-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: LHP Steve Sparks has a 1.69 ERA in August, tops in the
AL for the month. ... OF Wendell Magee is 8-for-20 as a pinch
hitter. ... RHP Jeff Weaver's victory Tuesday was his ninth of the
year, matching the total he reached last year as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: OF Luis Matos will be sidelined for a few days with a
bruised left shoulder, an injury that occurred Tuesday night during
a play at first base. ... After Thursday's home game against
Detroit, the Orioles depart on their longest road trip of the year.
They will play 13 games in 13 days in four cities. ... Baltimore
relievers have only three blown saves since June 28.
Twins-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins activated C Chad Moeller from the 15-day DL
and sending C Danny Ardoin to Triple-A Salt Lake City. The Twins
lost their last four of the season to the Royals and lost the
season series to Kansas City 7-5. Redman's ERA rose from 4.46 to
4.78.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Sweeney reached the 100-RBI mark this season faster
than anyone else in team history. Another team record in jeopardy
is Steve Balboni's 36 home runs, set in 1985. Jermaine Dye is at 31
with 30 games to go. ... Jerry Spradlin was released a few minutes
after giving up three runs and not recording an out in the ninth
inning of the Royals' 8-7 victory. He was replaced by LHP Scott
Mullen, whose contract was purchased from Triple-A Omaha.
White Sox-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: RHP Jon Garland, sidelined since Aug. 18 when a line
drive struck him just below his right elbow at Tampa Bay, was
impressive in a rehab start at Double-A Birmingham. Garland struck
out 10 in six shutout innings, giving up four hits and one walk
Wednesday. ... Also with Birmingham, Olympics-bound pitcher Jon
Rauch threw a two-hitter Tuesday in a 2-0 win over Huntsville.
Rauch is 4-0 with a 1.50 ERA over his last five starts, recording
42 strikeouts in 36 innings. Rauch, 21, will join the U.S. baseball
team on Sept. 2 to began preparation for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: 1B Jason Giambi had a cortisone shot in his sore left
shoulder after Wednesday's game and is expected to miss Friday
night's opener of a three-game series at Toronto. ... Oakland sent
RHP Jon Ratliff back to Triple-A Sacramento and called up 1B Mario
Valdez. Ratliff spent four days with the Athletics and did not make
an appearance. ... SS Miguel Tejada had 62 pairs of spikes around
his locker before one game this week, but not to keep him stocked
up. Tejada has the shoes shipped back to his native Dominican
Republic for children who can't afford spikes.
Blue Jays-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: David Wells, going for his major league-leading 19th
victory Wednesday, has a shot at his first 20-win season. Pitching
coach and assistant GM Dave Stewart, the last major leaguer with
four consecutive 20-win seasons, has enjoyed watching Wells go
after his first one. ''Winning 20 is not easy,'' Stewart said. ''It
takes maturity, it takes skill and it takes luck -- being in the
right place at the right time. But for Boomer, the time is right.''
... The Blue Jays, vying for their first postseason appearance
since winning the 1993 World Series, will play 26 of their final 33
games against teams with a realistic shot at a division title or
wild card berth. ''With our schedule, we've got to face all the
first-place teams and all the wild card teams we're up against. So
for us, every game is a playoff game,'' reliever John Frascatore
said. ... Toronto needed five home runs to break the club record of
221, set in 1998. ... Leadoff hitter Shannon Stewart has hit safely
in 21 of 23 games and is hitting .398 over that span, raising his
average to .341.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels' who led the majors with 41 home wins
entering Wednesday, play only nine of their final 29 games at
Edison Field. But that doesn't bother rookie manager Mike Scioscia,
whose team is seven games under .500 away from home. ''This club is
playing consistently right now and doing the things we're capable
of doing, so it doesn't matter where we're playing,'' Scioscia
said. ''Just because we're going to be on the road, it doesn't mean
that there's some kind of intimidation factor where we don't have
the confidence to win those games.'' ... Tim Belcher will make
another rehab start Friday at Class-A Lake Elsinore, and is cleared
to make 100 pitches. But whenever he is activated, he will have to
serve a three-game suspension stemming from his June 27 ejection by
plate umpire Mike DiMuro. Belcher had a heated argument with DiMuro
after a balk was called against him that allowed a run to score in
the Angels' 5-3 loss at Seattle. ... The Angels claimed RHP Ben
Weber off waivers from San Francisco's Triple-A Fresno club, then
assigned him to Triple-A Edmonton.
Yankees-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: 2B Chuck Knoblauch's sore elbow might sideline him for
the remainder of the season. ''Our plan has to be that we're not
going to have him,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ''To start
counting on him isn't healthy for me. There's been no improvement
in his elbow.'' Knoblauch has been on the DL since Aug. 3 because
of tendinitis in his right elbow. Knoblauch is in Tampa, Fla., on a
rehabilitation assignment. ... RF Paul O'Neill was back in the
Yankees' lineup after missing six straight games with a right hip
pointer. ''It feels better every day,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: 1B John Olerud missed the game because his wife, Kelly,
gave birth to have the couple's second child, a girl. Jordan Marie
Olerud weighed in at 7 pounds, 1 ounce. With Olerud absent, manager
Lou Piniella started Raul Ibanez at 1B. ... In the first inning, LF
Rickey Henderson was forced to leave because of lower back spasms.
... The Mariners expect to have RF Jay Buhner back for the Boston
series this weekend.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Padres-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: RHP Donne Wall has a sore shoulder which acted up
after he threw one inning Tuesday. His status was day to day. ...
3B Phil Nevin's streak of games in which he reached base via a hit
or a walk ended at 49. ... RHP Brian Tollberg has walked two or
less batters in 10 of his 14 starts. He had not allowed a run in 10
innings but the Cubs ended that streak with a run in the first. The
team season high was 11 innings set by Adam Eaton. ... The Padres
are 26-19 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Manager Don Baylor and some of his coaches took part in
a clinic at 9 a.m. Wednesday despite playing a 4-hour, 48 minute
game the night before that ended just before midnight. ''In this
game, you learn to sleep fast,'' Baylor said. ... Because of the
lateness of Tuesday's game, 1B Mark Grace said he didn't get a
chance to talk to his agent Barry Axelrod about contract
discussions with the Cubs. Grace will be a free agent at season's
end. ... SS Ricky Gutierrez is nursing a sore quadriceps but was
expected to return to the starting lineup Thursday. ... RF Sammy
Sosa posted his first Wrigley Field multihomer game since Aug. 21
last year. In 69 games at Wrigley, Sosa has 20 home runs. He has
hit 25 in 63 road games.
Cardinals-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: OF Jim Edmonds returned to the lineup after getting a
day off Tuesday. Edmonds, whose average dipped below .300 for the
first time since opening day, was in an 0-for-19 slump and batting
just .220 since Mark McGwire left the lineup July 6. ... The Cards
play 17 of their remaining 29 games at home.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: OF Mark Kotsay, who fouled two balls off his shin
Tuesday and left in the eighth inning with a bad bruise, did not
start Wednesday's game: ''If he had start, he could. I just didn't
think he would be able to walk today,'' manager John Boles said.
... Rookie RHP Chuck Smith (3-5, 3.55 ERA) has left quite an
impression on the Marlins, especially after giving up four hits and
