</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Tony Eusebio's 24-game hitting streak, which ended
Tuesday, matched the fifth-longest for a catcher since 1900,
trailing only Benito Santiago (34 games for San Diego in 1987),
Sandy Alomar Jr. (30 for Cleveland in 1997), John Flaherty (27 for
San Diego in 1996) and Brian Harper (25 for Minnesota in 1990).
Mike Piazza (Mets, 1999) and Gabby Hartnett (Cub, 1937) also had
24-gamers.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: LHP Al Leiter felt better Wednesday, manager Bobby
Valentine said, a day after the pitcher left after three innings
with a strained muscle in his right buttocks in an 11-1 loss to the
Astros. ... OF Derek Bell felt better, but was still a day or two
from playing. He did, however, laugh repeatedly while watching
''Judge Judy'' in the clubhouse before Wednesday's game. ... A day
after joining the Mets and pitching two innings in his major league
debut, RHP Jerrod Riggan was optioned to Binghamton of the Double-A
Eastern League. New York filled the spot by purchasing the contract
of OF Timoniel Perez from Norfolk of the Triple-A International
League.
Rockies-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Has Brent Mayne's pitching heroics rubbed off on other
Rockies? Before batting practice on Wednesday, 1B Todd Helton and
3B Jeff Cirillo were working on their windups while playing catch.
Cirillo used a conventional motion while Helton appeared to be
emulating LHP Mike Myers' swooping sidearm approach. Mayne, a
catcher, became the first position player to record a win in 32
years when he beat Atlanta on Aug. 22. ... Buddy Bell returned
after serving his two-game suspension. ... Colorado will play its
final 30 games on grass. ... Friday's starter Pedro Astacio (11-8,
5.15 ERA) has 186 strikeouts and is on pace for 226. He established
the club record of 210 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Manager Terry Francona said he didn't even check
on 3B Scott Rolen's condition before deciding to sit him Wednesday.
''That decision was made before he even got to the clubhouse,''
Francona said. ''It's the best thing for him.'' Rolen is suffering
from a sore back and he believes the artificial turf has
re-aggravated the injury. He had played eight straight games on
turf before sitting out Tuesday. ... RHP Wayne Gomes and his wife,
Melissa, became parents of a son, Miles, on Tuesday. ... Tug McGraw
and Sam Chapman were inducted into the Philadelphia Wall of Fame.
McGraw won 49 games and saved 94, including the World Series
clincher in 1980 -- the Phillies lone championship in their 117-year
history. Chapman compiled 1,273 hits, 174 homers and 732 RBIs
during an 11-year career with the Philadelphia Athletics from
1938-41; 1945-51.
Reds-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The Reds went into Wednesday having beaten the
Braves four times in a row, the first time that's happened since
1996. ... Cincinnati also clinched its first season series victory
over the Braves since 1990, when the Reds went 10-8 with their last
World Series-winning team. ... Juan Castro's run-scoring single in
the second inning assured the Reds of their 133rd consecutive game
without being shut out this season. The club record is 141 straight
games, which ended with last year's 5-0 loss to the New York Mets
in a one-game playoff to determine the NL wild card. ... Cincinnati
relievers had pitched 418 1-3 innings before Wednesday, most in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: The Braves held a closed-door meeting in the clubhouse
after batting practice, perhaps to address the team's woes over the
past week. Atlanta came into Wednesday night's game having lost
four in a row and five of six on the current homestand, dropping
their record to 13-14 in August. ... RHP Kevin Millwood, who was
supposed to miss Thursday's scheduled start because of a broken
nose, will pitch against the Reds after all. Millwood broke his
nose and suffered a deviated septum when struck in the face by a
ball while bunting in the indoor batting cage prior to Monday's
game. ... 1B Andres Galarraga expects baseball to hear his appeal
in Atlanta sometime next week. Galarraga was suspended three games
for charging the mound against Colorado Aug. 22. Galarraga believes
the suspension should be reduced because he was provoked by Rockies
RHP John Wasdin. ''He got two days and I got three. Why?''
Galarraga asked. ''He started the fight.'' ... NASCAR Winston Cup
car owner Richard Childress attended the game as a guest of Braves
third-base coach Ned Yost, a rabid racing fan and close friend of
Childress and his star driver, Dale Earnhardt. Childress strolled
around the field during batting practice with two cameras, snapping
pictures like a awestruck fan.
Dodgers-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Chan Ho Park's 14 strikeouts Tuesday were the most
by a Dodgers pitcher since Hideo Nomo struck out 17 Marlins in
April 1996. ''This year he's a complete pitcher,'' manager Davey
Johnson said. ''He was strictly a thrower last year. He overthrew a
lot. Now, when he's in a that groove, he can get good hitters out.
It gets like he's playing catch and it's fun to watch.'' ... The
Dodgers entered Wednesday with an 8-1 record without Gary
Sheffield, who is in L.A. recovering from the flu. ... The Dodgers,
who have 184 home runs this season, are on pace to hit a
club-record 226 homers. The record in L.A. is 191 in 1977 and the
franchise record is 208 in Brooklyn in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Slumping 2B Ron Belliard (.262) wasn't in the
starting lineup Wednesday. He has a sore back that may require
offseason surgery. ''My understanding is that if he does have
surgery, he would be ready for spring training,'' manager Davey
Lopes said. ... INF Jose Hernandez, also with a bad back, is
completing a short rehab assignment in Triple-A Indianapolis and
may rejoin the Brewers on their road trip that starts Friday in
Colorado. ''If everything feels fine, he's available for our first
game in Colorado,'' Lopes said. ... The Brewers acquired INF Marcos
Scutero from Cleveland as the player to be named in the
seven-player deal July 28 that brought Richie Sexson to Milwaukee.
Scutero will report to Indianapolis on Thursday.
</P>
