<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivory Coast Junta Postpones Vote  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Ivory Coast's military junta on
Wednesday postponed elections to restore civilian rule amid rising
tensions in one of Africa's most prosperous nations.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential ballot was originally scheduled for Sept. 17.
Information Ministry official Venance Konan said the military
regime decided to delay it until Oct. 22. A second round of voting,
if necessary, would follow in November, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the postponement were murky. Konan said the decision
was taken in part because of a shortage of funds and other
''problems affecting the work of the electoral commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivory Coast was considered a bastion of stability in volatile
West Africa before junta leader Gen. Robert Guei came to power in a
Dec. 24 coup d'etat that toppled the elected government of Henri
Konan Bedie.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover was initially popular among many Ivorians, who had
grown tired of corruption and ethnic favoritism under Bedie. But
many have become disillusioned with the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled soldiers have mutinied twice over bonuses and perks
they say they were promised for supporting the coup. Many believe
Guei's policies are fueling the same ethnic and political tensions
that divided the country under Bedie. There has also been no
improvement in the declining economy, which is one of the world's
largest cocoa and coffee producers.
</P>
<P>
   Konan says the vote was also delayed because the electoral body
needs time to assure the vote is carried out fairly and to register
18 to 21 year-olds who have only recently been granted voting
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''The international community needs to be assured that there is
fair play. If we had held the vote on Sept. 17, it could have
affected the credibility of the vote,'' he told The Associated
Press without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen candidates have applied, including Bedie and Guei, who
is standing as an independent candidate despite concerns about his
military position and influence.
</P>
<P>
   Both the United States and France, the country's former colonial
ruler, have discouraged Guei from running.
</P>
<P>
   The eligibility of a popular opposition leader, Alassane Dramane
Ouattara, is in question under a new constitution adopted following
a referendum in early August. A last-minute constitutional
amendment stipulates that both parents of presidential candidates
be ''of Ivorian origin'' -- a change widely believed to be aimed at
excluding Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara says both his parents were Ivorian. His opponents
insist they were from Burkina Faso. Ouattara is a former prime
minister and International Monetary Fund official who has been a
popular advocate for Ivory Coast's marginalized northern Muslims
and foreign immigrant community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-30-00 2334 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
