<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez: Colombia May Mirror Vietnam  </HEADLINE>
By HAROLD OLMOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Colombia's U.S.-backed efforts to combat
drug traffickers and leftists guerrillas could engulf much of South
America in a Vietnam-like war, Venezuelan president Hugo Chavez
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez was in Brasilia for the first South American summit,
called by Brazil to boost economic and physical integration among
the South American nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be very dangerous if the operation leads to a
military escalation of the conflict,'' Chavez said. ''It could lead
us to a Vietnamization of the whole Amazon region.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a South American leader had cautioned that
''Plan Colombia,'' a $7.5 billion initiative launched Wednesday by
Colombian President Andres Pastrana and President Clinton, could
degenerate into guerrilla warfare of continental dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela shares a 1,400-mile border with Colombia, while Brazil
shares 960 miles of Amazon frontier with Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some sectors in Colombia and other places may think that the
conflict has a military solution. That is incorrect,'' Chavez said.
''Peace negotiations are the only way to achieve a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said Venezuela was ''the most affected country by the
conflicts in Colombia after Colombia itself'' because of the
fleeing refugees who have crossed into Venezuela over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials in Brazil also have expressed concern that
the initiative could force drug traffickers and guerrillas to cross
into Brazil, which has placed army and police troops in the region
on alert.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, President Clinton pledged solidarity and $1.3
billion to that country's anti-drug campaign while dismissing fears
that conflict could lead to a new Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ''A condition of this aid is that we are not going to get into a
shooting war,'' Clinton said. ''This is not Vietnam, neither is it
Yankee imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said he would propose to his South American colleagues
the creation of a South Atlantic Treaty Organization, which would
have similar objectives as NATO.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Venezuela would propose to the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries an automatic oil price band that
would increase or decrease oil production by 500,000 million
barrels per day whenever oil prices rise over $28 per barrel or
fall below $22 during a period of 20 consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil closed Wednesday at a two-month high of $33 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez did not specify when the proposal would go into effect or
if it was still to be discussed by OPEC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
