<HEADLINE> Town evacuated after rail car leaks ammonia  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos XGLF101-102
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT EDWARD, N.Y. (AP) - About 800 residents headed into their
second night away from home Wednesday, evacuated nearly 24 hours
earlier when a rail car began leaking ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   Safety officials and repair crews were still on the scene late
Wednesday, figuring out how to stop the escaping anhydrous ammonia
that was headed to a local paper plant when the leak happened.
</P>
<P>
   The spill is being blamed on a gasket on top of the tanker car.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said 61 people were treated at a local hospital,
some of them children who suffered asthma symptoms as a reaction to
ammonia vapors and stress. None of the injuries was believed to be
serious and no one was admitted to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a 30,000 gallon tank from Canadian Terra
International began leaking ammonia vapor at 11 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at about 1 a.m., police, fire and rescue officials
went door to door to evacuate all downtown homes in the Washington
County village, including those downwind from the leaky Canadian
Pacific rail car.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 of the evacuated residents gathered a local school,
and others went to the homes of friends or relatives. Since then,
an emergency shelter has been opened at the roomier Hudson Falls
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen ambulances and rescuers from Washington, Warren and
Saratoga counties were sent to the scene. Emergency response teams
were trying to put a temporary cap on the valve, said Max Fruchter,
spokesman for the Fort Edward Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Roads around the village were closed for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no train accident, just a valve malfunction,''
Fruchter said, adding that if the cap effort was unsuccessful,
people would be unable to return home for 24 to 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Edward is 43 miles northeast of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
